<1ST_LINE>r i PM-LongHijackings     04-12 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Long Hijackings,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Longest Ordeals of Captives of Hijacked Planes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hijack Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The hijacking drama of a Kuwaiti airliner seized April 5 entered
its second week today. Here is a list of prolonged hijack incidents:
   
   JULY 23-SEPT. 1, 1968 _ El Al flight from Rome to Tel Aviv,
Israel, is diverted to Algeria by Arab nationalists. Forty days
later, Algeria releases the last 12 passengers held hostage.
   SEPT. 6-30, 1970 _ Palestinian commandos hijack three airliners
to a desert airstrip outside Amman, Jordan. Most passengers are
released by Sept. 12, when the Palestinians blow up the three
planes, but 54 people are held hostage for 24 days.
   JUNE 15-JULY 1, 1985 _ Shiite Moslem gunmen hijack TWA
Athens-to-Rome flight to Beirut. Some passengers are released but
40 men are held hostage. One hostage, U.S. Navy diver Robert
Stetham, is shot dead; 17 days later the remaining 39 are released.
   MARCH 2-15, 1981 _ Pakistani hijackers commandeer Pakistani jet,
diverting it to Afghanistan and on to Syria. All 148 hostages are
released after 13 days aboard the plane.
</TEXT>
