<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FinanceMinisters     04-12 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Finance Ministers,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baker Plan Receiving Warm Reception</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III seems to
be making progress in his drive to get the world's top economic
powers to use the price of gold and other commodities to help them
coordinate economic policies.
   Baker took economic leaders by surprise when he advanced the
idea last September, with some countries openly skeptical.
   But Baker has demonstrated considerable skill as one of the
administration's top negotiators and officials indicated Monday
that the world's seven top industrial countries are likely to give
formal approval to Baker's commodity-index proposal on Wednesday.
   The seven nations, the United States, Japan, West Germany,
Britain, France, Italy and Canada, will hold high-level talks in
Washington as part of the spring meeting of the 151-nation
International Monetary Fund.
   A senior Treasury Department official, briefing reporters
Monday, said the administration is ``hopeful there will be some
agreement'' by the seven countries to adopt the commodity-basket
proposal. The official spoke on condition his name not be used.
   Baker has stressed that he is not proposing a return to the gold
standard, the system in use for 25 years after World War II. For
most of that time, the price of gold was fixed at $35 an ounce and
the currencies of other countries were pegged at fixed exchange
rates to the dollar.
   That system broke down in the early 1970s under the weight of
higher inflation and a rising flow of international capital between
countries. It was replaced with today's floating exchange rate
system under which the value of each nation's currency is set on
the open market.
   But the extreme volatility in floating rates, especially for the
U.S. dollar, has driven the big industrial countries in search of
ways to stabilize exchange rates.
   One method that Baker has pushed since the Tokyo economic summit
in 1986 has been the use of a variety of economic indicators to
monitor each country's performance in helping to sustain worldwide
growth. This group of indicators includes individual growth rates,
inflation and trade balances.
   Baker's proposal would add gold and other commodity prices to
the list of economic yardsticks the countries use to coordinate
policies.
   This approach would introduce a price-sensitive measure into the
economic planning process. In addition to gold, other commodities
which might be included are iron ore, copper, rubber, cotton,
wheat, rice, corn, coffee and tea.
   If the price of these commodities rose in particular countries,
those nations would be encouraged to boost interest rates to fight
inflation. But if commodity prices were falling, the countries
would know they had room to cut interest rates and stimulate
economic growth without danger of inflation.
   Some countries, in particular West Germany, have opposed the
commodity index because they see it as a device that would be used
to goad them into achieving faster growth at the risk of sparking
inflation.
   But in a television interview Monday, Baker said the seven top
industrial countries were in basic agreement at present over the
steps needed to stabilize exchange rates.
   ``The major industrialized countries of the world obviously
favor stability of exchange rates and we have been very pleased
with the stability we have seen since our last meeting in
December,'' Baker said on NBC's ``Today'' program.
   Last Dec. 22, the seven countries pledged to support the dollar,
which at the time was under heavy selling pressure. That commitment
was backed up by massive intervention, the process by which
governments buy weak currencies such as the dollar to drive up the
price.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
