<2ND_LINE>AM-Jet-Windshield,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Damaged Window Forces Jet To Make Emergency Landing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jumbo jet bound for Germany from Los
Angeles made a successful emergency landing here Monday after the
plastic layers in one of the cockpit side windows began to come
apart, an airport spokesman said.
   Pan Am Flight 150, with 322 passengers on board, left Los
Angeles for Frankfurt about 3 p.m., turned back about an hour and a
half later, and made a safe emergency landing at San Francisco
International Airport about 5:30, said spokesman Ron Wilson.
   The pilot of the Boeing 747 turned back after he heard a loud
snap and saw a window on his left begin to ``delaminate,'' Wilson
said.
   ``Obviously the aircraft could not fly at any altitude or great
speed with that,'' Wilson said. ``I don't think there was ever any
danger. The pilot did what he was supposed to do.''
   The pilot had to reduce the plane's altitude and depressurize
the cabin somewhat on the way back, Wilson said.
   He said the window would be repaired at the airport.
</TEXT>
