<HEAD>Pizza Parlor Owner Wanted In Italy Ordered Deported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pizza parlor owner wanted in Italy in
connection with the murder of an Sicilian judge on Monday was
ordered deported by an Immigration and Naturalization Service judge.
   Salvatore Inzerillo, part-owner of a restaurant in Woodbridge,
Va., had asked to be allowed to leave the country voluntarily.
   But Judge Joan V. Arrowsmith denied the request, saying that
would allow Inzerillo to go to the country of his choice. She said
he should be returned to Italy for trial.
   Inzerillo has been in INS custody since Feb. 23. Italian
authorities have issued an arrest warrant for him in the 1980
slaying of Judge Gaetano Costa, who was investigating drug
trafficking in Sicily.
   FBI agent James L. Glass Jr. testified that Inzerillo had
connections with the Mafia, but Inzerillo denied being a member of
the Mafia and said he is not a drug dealer.
   Inzerillo said he hired a smuggler to get him into the United
States in 1981 to seek work. His attorney said he will appeal the
deportation ruling.
