<HEAD>Reagan Praises Jayhawks, Lady Techsters For Championships</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan saluted the University of
Kansas Jayhawks and the Lady Techsters of Louisiana Tech for
winning NCAA basketball championships, calling them ``fighters''
who overcame adversity.
   Reagan met the teams Monday in the White House Rose Garden to
honor them for earning the national titles last week.
   ``Now it's no secret that at the beginning of the NCAA
tournament, you Jayhawks, well I suppose the way to put it is to
say you weren't exactly favored to win,'' said Reagan. ``So what
happened is a testament to determination, to hard work, lots and
lots of hard work, to pride, to teamwork and the courage to dream.''
   The Jayhawks defeated the Oklahoma Sooners 83-79 a week ago to
win the men's title, and finished the season 27-11.
   Reagan recounted how the Lady Techsters overcame a 12-point
halftime deficit to defeat Auburn 56-54 in the final moments of
their championship game.
   ``You had a lot of great games this season, but none was greater
than the last,'' the president told the Louisiana Tech team.
   Star guard Teresa Weatherspoon presented Reagan with an
autographed basketball.
   Danny Manning, who scored 31 points in the Jayhawks'
championship win, gave Reagan two KU letter jackets _ one bearing
the president's nickname, ``Dutch,'' and the other for his wife,
Nancy.
   ``We're very thrilled and it's especially an honor to be here,''
said Manning.
   Reagan also took note of an announcement by KU Coach Larry Brown
last week that he intended to remain at KU and not accept the UCLA
coaching job.
   To applause, the president said, ``I know Jayhawk fans
everywhere are rejoicing that next year I'm the only one moving
back to California.''
