<HEAD>China Hoping To Increase Trade With Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China, hoping to increase trade with the Soviet
Union and Eastern Europe, has set up five new trade ports and plans
eight more, the official China Daily newspaper said today.
   China says it has a large surplus of labor, arable land and
industrial commodities but is short of timber, electricity and
fertilizer.
   The Soviet Union suffers shortages of labor, agricultural
products and light industrial and textile products but has good
supplies of timber, coal and petroleum, the paper said.
   Presently, China has only three trade ports, all in Heilongjiang
province, bordering the Soviet Union.
   The State Council has given provincial authorities the power to
approve its own export projects, to set up barter trade, to set up
joint projects with the Soviets and to exchange technology.

