<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0736,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Propose Renewed Technical Talks With Contras</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf pvs bgng: Marta Sacasa... with 3 grafs rebels
responding to government proposal for techical meeting to resume
Wednesday. Pick up 5th graf pvs: A preliminary peace...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Monday proposed a
resumption of talks with rebels on details of a cease-fire plan
after negotiations ended last week in disagreement over arms
shipments.
   The Sandinista government suggested the technical discussions be
resumed Wednesday or Thursday in Managua, the capital.
   It also proposed that the rebels, known as Contras, send an
advance team to Managua on Tuesday to prepare for discussions
Sandinista and rebel political leaders are scheduled to hold on
Friday.
   In Washington, Contra spokesman Bosco Matamoros who is a member
of the special negotiating commission released a statement late
Monday saying the technical talks should resume at noon on
Wednesday in the border village of Sapoa.
   The statement said the Contra's ranking political leaders would
travel to Managua on Friday for negotiations, based on progress at
the Sapoa talks. There was no immediate response from the
government.
   Matamoros' statement said the Contras would send an advance
delegation to Managua Thursday to prepare for the political talks.
It said the Contra representatives would include Roberto Ferrey,
secretary of the directorate of the Contras' umbrella Nicaraguan
Resistance group, and David Stadhagen.
   A preliminary peace plan signed March 23 in Sapoa called for the
two sides to hold technical discussions to work out details of a
60-day cease-fire that went into effect April 1. The talks between
military commanders are to spell out how the Contras are to gather
in cease-fire zones.
   During the truce, the two sides are to hold negotiations leading
to a permanent agreement to end more than six years of war between
the U.S.-backed Contras and the government.
   Military leaders have held six days of technical talks since
March 28 at Sapoa, 90 miles south of Managua and beside the Costa
Rican border.
   They have agreed only on seven zones in which the Contras are to
gather but have failed to decide on security measures and how the
rebels are to receive supplies in the zones.
   The meetings ended Friday after the Contras asked for a recess
of several days to discuss a 25-point plan the government proposed.
The Contras earlier offered a 34-point plan.
   Last week the Sandinistas suggested the technical talks be
resumed Friday, when the political leaders are to hold their
discussions.
   Paul Reichler, an American lawyer negotiating for the
Sandinistas, said over the weekend that there were only two points
of contention in the proposal presented by the Contras.
   The Contra proposals would allow the rebels to receive arms,
ammunition and war materiel while in the zones. It also would ban
the Sandinistas from receiving any military aid, which is supplied
by the Soviet bloc.
   Reichler described those two points as ``absolutely
unacceptable.''
   The original cease-fire plan would permit the Contras to receive
only food and basic supplies channeled through a neutral
organization, such as the International Red Cross.
   Political leaders of both sides had been scheduled to meet last
Wednesday in Managua. The rebels postponed them, saying the
technical talks had not advanced enough to move toward political
issues.
   The rebels also have said they will not participate in this
week's high-level political talks unless they are free to meet with
opposition leaders.
   The government maintains that the peace agreement specifies
Contra representation in politics begins only after the rebels move
into the cease-fire zones.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
