<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--RareOx     04-12 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Rare Ox,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Reportedly Sight Rare Ox In Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLAND, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnamese biologists reportedly have
sighted a rare Indochinese gray ox for the first time in nearly 20
years, raising hopes the endangered species can be saved from
extinction.
   A newspaper published Monday by the World Wildlife Fund said the
animal, called a kouprey, was seen last year by a Vietnamese team
in a densely forested area near the Laotian border. The sighting
was revealed in January at an international conservation meeting in
Hanoi, the fund said.
   It was important because scientists had begun to fear the animal
might be extinct, at least in Vietnam, said Elizabeth Kemf, who
edits the newspaper.
   Experts are especially interested in the kouprey because it may
be immune to rinderpest, an often fatal infectious disease that
afflicts cattle, sheep and goats, Ms. Kemf told The Associated
Press.
   Scientists want to study the possibility of cross-breeding
kouprey with cattle to render them immune to the intestinal
disease, she said.
   The kouprey is a migratory animal found chiefly in Vietnam, Laos
and Cambodia, and also in Thailand.
</TEXT>
