<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ArmsMeetings     04-12 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Meetings,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Team Arrives To Discuss Logistics Of INF Inspections</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top prospects uncertain; arrival expected in mid-to-late
afternoon.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of Soviet officials is readying for a
second round of talks aimed at sorting through arrangements for
verifying the arms treaty eliminating intermediate-range nuclear
weapons.
   The Soviet team of 10 to 14 military and civilian officials was
due in Washington today and planned to meet behind closed doors
with an American group starting on Wednesday, the Pentagon said
Monday.
   According to one U.S. official who asked not to be named, the
talks will extend at least to Saturday and will focus on a variety
of ``housekeeping details'' that must be settled before the two
sides begin compliance inspections.
   ``Some of the topics on the plate include living quarters for
inspectors, call signs for aircraft traveling in each country, the
logistics of moving and putting in place the equipment we'll need
and what equipment we're planning to use, and even how we deal with
the news media,'' said the source.
   The United States and Soviet Union want to reach agreement on
such details in advance of the Senate vote on ratifying the new
treaty to ensure a smooth start for the compliance inspections, the
official added.
   Signed by President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev on Dec. 8, the new treaty specifies that all nuclear
missiles in the two superpower arsenals with a range of roughly 300
miles to 3,500 miles be destroyed within three years.
   Within the U.S. government, the Pentagon has created an
organization known as the On-Site Inspection Agency to verify
Russian compliance with the new treaty. The head of that agency,
Army Brig. Gen. Roland Lajoie, will lead the U.S. team in this
week's discussions.
   The two sides held their first round of talks in Moscow last
month.
   The OSIA will be responsible for escorting Soviet inspectors who
travel to the United States and Western Europe to monitor the
removal and destruction of American nuclear weapons, as well as
performing the same role inside the Soviet Union by visiting
Russian facilities and deployment sites.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
