<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-ForeignPress     04-12 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Foreign Press,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Campaign Attracts Hordes Of Foreign Reporters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riding the Jesse Jackson press bus at times
can be like attending a meeting of the United Nations.
   Jackson has attracted intense interest by the international news
media _ in part, because of what one Frenchman called his ``star''
quality. News agencies from all over the world have sent writers
and TV crews to cover his bid for the Democratic presidential
nomination.
   ``The campaigns of the other candidates are so boring that Jesse
Jackson is the only one to emerge,'' said Paris Match correspondent
Oliver Royant.
   The foreign coverage is increasing in anticipation of the
crucial New York primary on April 19, his aides say.
   Traveling with Jackson's entourage last weekend were reporters
from Ecuador, Lebanon, France, Japan, Great Britain, Canada, Italy
and West Germany. Off and on, the campaign also has seen
representatives from news agencies of other nations including
Denmark and Holland.
   At one point campaign aides even considered having a news
conference just for the foreign press _ because all wanted
interviews with the candidate and their questions were of a
different nature than those asked by U.S. reporters, said press
secretary DelMarie Cobb.
   The interest seems to center on Jackson as a person and
international celebrity, his eloquence and flair, and on the
historical significance of his candidacy.
   Foreign reporters said they were looking for those kinds of
stories more than at Jackson's stance on issues.
   Cobb said the foreign press also asks a lot of questions about
whether the United States is ready to elect a black president.
   On the other hand, Raghida Dergham of the London-based Lebanese
magazine Al-Hawadress said editors in the Middle East are very
interested in the foreign policies of Jackson, who enjoys
considerable support in the Arab-American community.
   British Broadcasting Corp. correspondent Kent Barker said
Jackson was ``certainly the most interesting to foreign eyes. He's
the most colorful, dramatic'' presidential candidate this year.
   The BBC's audience is also interested in Jackson's liberalism
and sees him as aligned with the philosophies of the Labor Party in
Great Britain, he said.
   In Italy, people are more aware of Jackson than the other
candidates, even though RAI television has done a profile on
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, said RAI cameraman Michele
Capasso. He cited ``the style and excitement around him'' as
reasons Jackson makes a good story.
   ``In France, every U.S. election, people want to know two
things,'' said Royant of Paris Match. ``Are we going to find a
Kennedy this year? ... Who is the star? This year Jesse Jackson is
the star.''
   Paris Match did a profile of Jackson in October, and Royant is
working on a second profile that will appear some time before the
summer nominating conventions. Jackson has visited France in the
past and is well-known there, said Royant.
   Additionally, there is interest in the candidacy of a black man
20 years after the death of civil rights leader Martin Luther King,
Royant said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
