<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Candidates-Layoffs     04-12 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Candidates-Layoffs,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stumping In Union Stronghold Of New York, Democrats Back Layoff
Notices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic presidential contenders are
telling Congress to disregard President Reagan's threat to veto a
trade bill if it calls for mandatory advance layoff notices.
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore and Jesse Jackson sent letters over
the weekend urging Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, a key architect of
the sweeping trade bill, to resist further weakening of the
labor-sought notice provision.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis earlier had sent a similar
letter to Bentsen, urging him to retain the notice provision
``regardless of the president's intentions.''
   The letters arrived on Capitol Hill as Gore, Jackson and Dukakis
are engaged in an intense competition for the 255 convention
delegates at stake in the April 19 primary in New York, a state
where one in every three workers carries a union card.
   ``I can only conclude that the real reason many companies oppose
a notice requirement _ and the reason those same companies do not
give advance notice now _ is that they do not care what happens to
workers or their communities,'' Gore said in his letter.
   Jackson said his campaign speeches on the need for advance
layoff notices have received enthusiastic responses and that ``it
is difficult to believe that Congress would not override such an
ill-advised veto.''
   ``The inclusion of the provision in the trade bill has been
helpful in making working people aware that the Congress is
responding to some of their very fundamental concerns,'' he said in
his letter to Bentsen.
   The AFL-CIO, which has made the trade bill its top legislative
priority for six years, has threatened to withdraw its support for
it entirely if the layoff notices are eliminated.
   ``I could understand our so-called trading partners being
opposed to the bill,'' AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Thomas R.
Donahue said Monday. ``But he's (Reagan) supposed to be the
president of the United States.''
   Under the provision, companies with more than 100 employees
would be required to give 60 days advance notice when they intend
to close a plant or lay off one-third or more of its workforce.
However, the layoffs would have to total at least 50 workers to
trigger the mandatory notices.
   Bentsen and other Senate and House ``superconferees'' are
scheduled to start meeting today in hopes of getting a final
version of the trade bill by Thursday or Friday for separate votes
in each house on final passage.
   Without citing specific provisions, Reagan said in his weekend
radio address Saturday he still has ``very _ underline very _
serious reservations'' about the bill.
   ``The bottom line is this: I will veto a bad trade bill before I
let a bad trade bill veto our economy.''
   While administration officials have outlined objections to
several provisions, congressional leaders describe most of the
protests as ``padding'' for its vehement opposition to the
mandatory layoff notices.
   ``It's a classic game of everybody trying to figure out what the
other guy's bottom line is,'' said one legislative aide, who
acknowledged one purpose of the candidates' letters is to counter
administration veto threats.
   Just a week ago, Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin wrote Senate
Democratic Leader Robert Byrd she would be ``forced to recommend
that the president veto the bill ... if these protectionist
mandatory plant closing and layoff requirements remain.''
   A Labor Department task force last year called advance notices
``an essential component of a readjustment program'' for helping
laid off workers get new jobs, but stopped short of saying the
notices should be mandated.
   According to the Bureau of Labor Statistics, two of every three
workers laid off in the United States receive no advance notice.
   The average notice, according to a separate survey by the
General Accounting Office, is 14 days for white-collar workers and
seven days for blue-collar workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
