<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Lite Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEVADA CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Sierra Nevada foothill community
had a bear of a weekend, and loved it.
   Some 10,000 teddy bears were on hand to be cuddled, admired and
enjoyed by 6,000 humans, who also indulged in music, food, clown
performances, shopping and story telling.
   Besides the bears of all shapes and sizes at the Nevada City's
Fifth Annual International Teddy Bear Convention, there were grown
men in furry bear suits and teenagers wearing fuzzy ears. There
were toddlers and grandmothers alike clutching favorite teddy bears.
   And if some looked askance at the goings-on at the American
Victorian Museum and the nearby teddy-bear castle, 3{-year-old
Sydney Gerson of Nevada City wasn't among them.
   After getting a couple of big hugs from a shaggy brown cinnamon
bear, Sydney beamed and said, ``I love teddy bears a lot because
they are so soft and snuggly.''
   The ``teddy'' bear title, according to the story repeated at the
convention, was given a small stuffed bear by a Brooklyn candy
store owner who read of the refusal of President Theodore ``Teddy''
Roosevelt to shoot a small bear cub while on a hunting trip in 1902.
   The vendor, who later founded the Ideal Toy Co., sent his
creation to the president, who kept it for his children.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SALIDA, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Glenn Harrington's rhinoceros may be an
unlikely cross between a bull and a Buick, but he says he'll miss
the life-size, metallic sculpture when it moves to a Ripley's
Believe It Or Not museum.
   ``The mountains are no place for an 8-year-old rhinoceros,''
Harrington said. ``It's time he moved to a lower elevation and a
warmer climate.''
   The rhino was made about eight years ago from old steel
automobile bumpers by ``bumper sculpture'' artist Jon Bedford, a
former Salida resident. Harrington bought it for display in front
of his hardware business on U.S. 50.
   When the business closed a year ago, the rhino moved to the
front lawn of Harrington's home.
   ``We felt it didn't belong in a private yard,'' Harrington said.
``It should be in a public place, where people can see and
appreciate it.''
   So Harrington put the rhino up for sale, advertising it at a
gallery in Taos, N.M., where Bedford now works. Last week, word
came that the rhino was sold to Ripley's Believe It Or Not Museum
in Laguna Beach, Calif.
   Still, Harrington says, he'll miss the old beast.
   ``The rhino brought a lot of interesting comments and situations
when we were at the store,'' he said. ``There was the old rancher
from Saguache, for example. He showed up one morning, just as I was
opening the store, and he stood outside for a long time, studying
that rhinoceros.
   ```When he finally came in he said, `I know where that came
from. ... It's a cross between a Brahma bull and a Buick.'''
</TEXT>
