<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CommunistPresident 1stLd-Writethru a0666 04-12 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Communist President, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0666,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Judiciary Board To Settle Communist Election Dispute</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with evening hearing. Picks up
8th graf pvs ``He's more.''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A University of Massachusetts student
judiciary board agreed Monday to settle a dispute over a
communist's election as co-president of the student body.
   The three-member student Supreme Court heard a motion Monday
night that would declare the election invalid. John Sanchez, the
panel's chief judge, said a ruling on the motion would be issued
Wednesday prior to a scheduled meeting of the undergraduate Student
Senate.
   Jason Rabinowitz, a member of the Young Communist League, and
his co-candidate, non-communist Shari Silkoff, were elected March
15. Rabinowitz is believed to be the first YCL member elected
campus president since the group was formed five years ago.
   Student Attorney General William Collins filed the motion asking
the judiciary board to declare the Rabinowitz-Silkoff ticket
invalid because the student government constitution allows only one
person to hold the office of president.
   ``I think I'm winning,'' Collins said after the session, ``but
the point is I can't just win. I have to win convincingly.''
   Monday night's hearing was mostly spent on arguments by a
student lawyer representing Rabinowitz and Silkoff, who attempted
to show that the writers of the student constitution did not mean
to prevent more than one person from serving.
   Conservatives on the 90-member undergraduate student senate
filibustered last week to keep the election from being ratified and
stop Rabinowitz and Silkoff from taking office.
   Collins said his motion had nothing to do with the candidates'
political beliefs, but Rabinowitz contended otherwise.
   ``He's more interested in petty factional politics than the
well-being of the whole student government,'' said Rabinowitz, a
20-year-old junior from New York City.
   Rabinowitz and Silkoff, also 20, won 1,454 votes, 391 more than
conservative candidate Aram Hamparian, at the 19,000-student campus.
</TEXT>
