<HEAD>Michael Douglas Awarded First Acting Award, Second Oscar for
``Wall Street''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Douglas, the ruthless inside trader
of ``Wall Street,'' won his second Oscar and first acting award
Monday night at the 60th Annual Academy Awards ceremony.
   Douglas previously won an Oscar for being one of the producers
of ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest,'' best picture of 1975.
   When accepting the award, Douglas credited ``Wall Street''
director Oliver Stone ``for having the courage to cast me in a part
that not many people thought I could play.''
   Douglas described the character of Wall Street king Gordon Gekko
as ``the best part that I've ever had in my career.''
   The actor also thanked his wife and his parents, especially his
father, actor Kirk Douglas, ``for helping a son step out of the
shadow.''
   Douglas also had been considered by the Academy for his
performance in the psycho-thriller ``Fatal Attraction,'' which was
nominated for best picture, but the actors branch of the Academy
decided to nominate him for ``Wall Street.''
   Marlee Matlin, who won the best actress Oscar last year for
``Children of a Lesser God,'' presented the award, using sign
language, but speaking aloud the names of nominees Douglas, William
Hurt, Marcello Mastroianni, Jack Nicholson, and Robin Williams.
   Douglas' film debut was with ``Hail, Hero.'' He spent four years
with the ABC-TV series ``The Streets of San Francisco,'' and became
established as a movie star with the smash-hit adventure films
``Romancing the Stone'' and ``Jewel of the Nile.''
</TEXT>
