<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Shearson-Takeover     04-12 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shearson-Takeover,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shearson Defends Role In Koppers Takeover Attempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The investment banking firm Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. came under attack during a congressional hearing for
what one senator said was its role as a corporate raider in a
hostile takeover.
   ``In effect, what we have is a bank acting as a corporate
raider,'' Sen. Jim Sasser, D-Tenn., said Monday at a hearing of the
Senate Banking Committee. The committee met for three hours on the
attempted takeover of Pittsburgh-based Koppers by Beazer PLC of
Britain, which is being advised by Shearson Lehman.
   ``Shearson is only the first to cross a line that Wall Street
believes will be obliterated by others racing across it in the
future,'' said Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., referring to the distinction
between banking and commerce.
   Steven B. Wolitzer, managing director of Shearson, said the
firm's role was limited to providing short-term, or ``bridge,''
financing for Beazer's tender offer and giving advice. Such
financing is ``typical for investment banks in deals of this
kind,'' he said.
   Wolitzer acknowledged that Shearson is contributing equity of
its own _ $23 million _ to the bidding group, but he said
management and control of the group would be held by Beazer PLC.
   But Charles R. Pullin, chairman and chief executive officer of
Koppers, said Shearson ``has dominated and actively guided every
aspect of the planning and execution of the Koppers takeover
attempt since its secret initiation one year ago.''
   Brian C. Beazer, chairman and chief executive officer of the
British company, defended the takeover attempt, saying his
company's goal is ``not to make a quick buck by laying off
employees, and selling the company's operations piecemeal.''
   ``I am not a corporate raider,'' Beazer said. He said Koppers'
management has mounted ``a massive campaign of disinformation''
about his bid.
   Beazer led a group that made an unsolicited cash tender offer of
$45 a share for Koppers on March 3, a deal that has since been
sweetened to $60 per share, or $1.7 billion. Koppers produces
construction materials and chemicals.
   ``From an American Express Co. viewpoint, not only do we think
this to be a Shearson transaction and activity in the normal course
of its business, but we also view the uproar by some allies of
Koppers as ill-informed, provocative and ill-advised,'' said Harry
L. Freeman, executive vice president of American Express,
Shearson's parent.
   He said it was ill-informed because of the ``continued erroneous
assertion that somehow Shearson, rather than Beazer, is trying to
acquire Koppers, which is simply not true and strikes the
management of American Express Co. as a bizarre allegation.''
   Beazer's offer has been extended until April 15 while courts
consider legal challenges by Koppers that have slowed the takeover
bid.
</TEXT>
