<NOTE>Eds: A version of the following item moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abel Kiviat, the world's oldest Olympic
champion, has outlasted the gold and silver medals he won in the
1912 Stockholm games. In fact, he says, he hasn't seen them since
they were lost nearly 60 years ago.
   So on Thursday, King Carl XVI Gustaf of Sweden, the grandson of
the man who originally awarded Kiviat his medals, will present the
95-year-old former runner with specially crafted duplicates during
a visit to Trenton.
   Glenn Kasper, a member of the Governor's Council on Physical
Fitness, came up with the idea of replacing the original medals
after taking Kiviat home from an Olympic fund-raising event in
February.
   ``I knew the king and queen were coming here and I thought,
`Wouldn't it be great if we could get replacement medals to give to
Abel?''' Kasper asked.
   In the 1912 Olympics, when he was a roommate of Decathlon
champion Jim Thorpe, Kiviat won the silver medal in the 1,500-meter
run and the gold medal in the 3,000-meter cross-country event.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two stars from Leningrad's Kirov Ballet will
appear as guest artists with the American Ballet Theater in a
performance choreographed by Natalia Makarova, who defected from
the Soviet Union while a Kirov star in 1970.
   The appearances by Altynai Assylmuratova and Faruk Ruzimatov in
``La Bayadere'' at the Metropolitan Opera House were announced by
ABT artistic director Mikhail Baryshnikov, a former Kirov dancer
who defected in 1974.
   Baryshnikov met with Kirov artistic director Oleg Vinogradov
last December in Paris to arrange the May 28 and May 30
performances.
   The first visit by Soviet dancers to perform with an American
ballet company came in February when Nina Ananiashvili and Andris
Liepa of the Bolshoi Ballet danced in three pieces choreographed by
George Balanchine with the New York City Ballet.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PETERBORO, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Styron, author of ``Sophie's
Choice'' and other prize-winning fiction, will receive the 1988
Edward MacDowell Medal ``for his unique insight and vision of the
American novel,'' a writer's group said.
   Styron, 62, is being recognized for his novels, articles and
essays, including the 1967 book ``The Confessions of Nat Turner,''
which won a Pulitzer Prize, and ``Sophie's Choice,'' which won the
1980 American Book Award.
   ``Through his works, he has helped us understand man's
limitations. He has taught us lessons about the human condition,
about how to survive, about right and wrong,'' Mary Carswell,
executive director of the MacDowell Colony for artists, said Monday.
   ``We will honor William Styron for his contribution to American
literature and for his unique insight and vision of the American
novel,'' she said. The MacDowell Colony is an artist's retreat
founded in 1907 by composer Edward McDowell and his wife, Marian.
   Styron was chosen by a committee of seven American literary
figures. It was chaired by John Updike, a former MacDowell
medalist, and included Michael Blumenthal, Brendan Gill, Elizabeth
Hardwick, Norman Mailer, Elizabeth Sifton and Robert Taylor.
   Among the 28 previous medalists: writers Thornton Wilder, Eudora
Welty and Lillian Hellman; composers Aaron Copland, Leonard
Bernstein and William Schuman; and visual artists Georgia O'Keeffe,
Willem de Kooning and Louise Nevelson.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grammy-winning jazz guitarist Larry Carlton
is slowly recuperating after being shot in the neck by two teen-age
intruders, but police have failed to identify the suspects or their
motive, a detective said.
   ``The last I heard he was still in stable condition, and seems
to be better the last couple days,'' Detective Rick Swanston said
Monday.
   Carlton, 40, underwent four hours of surgery for a single
gunshot wound to the neck when he was brought to St. Joseph Medical
Center in Burbank after Wednesday's attack at his Hollywood Hills
home. He was later transferred to an undisclosed hospital for
security reasons.
   Carlton won a Grammy this year for best pop instrumental for his
version of the Doobie Brothers' ``Minute By Minute.'' In 1981, he
shared a Grammy with pianist Mike Post for the theme to ``Hill
Street Blues.''
   Police have not been able to identify the shooting suspects,
Swanston said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steven Ford wanted to be a cowboy and stay
out of the public eye when his father became president, but he
ended up pursuing an acting career after Gerald R. Ford himself
left the limelight.
   Ford, who was 18 when his father succeeded Richard Nixon in
1974, said he had little interest in attending state dinners and
other White House functions.
   ``I left home and spent most of my time out west in Montana,
Utah and Idaho, '' he said at a recent appearance here.
   Ford, 31, said he had been on the professional rodeo curcuit for
about two years when he landed a job as a stunt man in Mexico.
Later, he played in the daytime soap opera ``The Young and the
Restless'' for seven years.
   ``It wasn't hard to see where the money was,'' he said.
