<2ND_LINE>AM-Oscars-Dukakis, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0778,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Olympia Dukakis Wins First Oscar, Urges on Cousin in Presidential
Race</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs ``Like her'' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with
backstage comments.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Olympia Dukakis took the best supporting
actress Oscar for ``Moonstruck'' Monday night, then hoisted the
statuette in the air and urged on first cousin Michael Dukakis
with: ``OK Michael, let's go!''
   The nomination was the first for Miss Dukakis, who has long been
a working actress in theater, films and television, but failed to
reach a national audience until she played Cher's wise and enduring
Italian mother in ``Moonstruck.''
   After hearing her name announced from among nominees Anne
Ramsey, Norma Aleandro, Anne Archer, and Ann Sothern, Miss Dukakis
said she was ``very honored'' by the award and thanked her family,
friends and colleagues, then hollered, ``OK Michael, let's go.''
   Backstage, she declared: ``It's the year of the Dukaki!'' and
said she hoped her good fortune would help her cousin, who is
seeking the Democratic presidential nomination. She was eager to
telephone the Massachusetts governor who was campaigning in New
York in anticipation of the state's primary.
   Miss Dukakis said she planned to run for election as a delegate
to the Democratic National Convention from New Jersey.
   Like her cousin, the actress grew up in a Greek family in which
everybody argued politics. After graduating from Boston University,
she worked as a physical therapist to earn enough money to return
and study theater arts.
   She remains the artistic director of the Whole Theater in
Montclair, N.J., and says of her new-found fame: ``I'm not
convinced that this being a celebrity is going to be long-lived.''
</TEXT>
