<DOCNO> AP880412-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     04-12 0688</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says He Hopes Cousin's Oscar Win Is `Omen For Next Week'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis celebrated his cousin's
Academy Award and, with his eye on New York's important
presidential primary, said ``I hope it's an omen for next week.''
   Dukakis talked to cousin Olympia Dukakis by telephone Monday
night shortly after she won an Oscar for her supporting role in the
movie ``Moonstruck.''
   The Massachusetts governor made his call from a Greenwich
Village restaurant that figured in the movie and was decorated with
photos and posters from it. Dining on pasta and lamb chops, Dukakis
watched a videotaped replay of his cousin's award and clapped when
she waved her statuette and said, ``OK, Michael, let's go!''
   He had just seen the movie the night before.
   ``You're fantastic, you're unbelievable,'' he gushed on the
telephone. ``You're radiant. ... I'm so happy for you.''
   ``What are we doing here, you and I, just a couple of street
kids?'' he asked.
   Dukakis, the front-runner for the Democratic nomination, had
been saying all afternoon as he campaigned around New York City
that an Oscar victory could be a harbinger for his presidential
candidacy in next Tuesday's primary.
   ``I hope it's an omen for next week,'' he said. ``I hope it's a
good sign for the `Dukaki' _ all of them.''
   Earlier in the day, Dukakis bid for Jewish support and sided
with Israel in blaming Arab leaders for violence in the West Bank.
He found no fault with Israel's policies or use of force in dealing
with Palestinian uprisings, but he also absolved the young Arab
protesters, saying they have been misled by their leaders.
   ``It is critically important that the world understand who is
responsible for the turmoil and the violence,'' he told the
Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations.
   ``It is not the generation of young Palestinians who have grown
up in uncertainty.'' he said. ``It is not a government in Jerusalem
that struggles to maintain order. ... It is, regrettably, Arab
leaders themselves, who have time and again rejected the chance to
sit down with Israel and negotiate a permanent peace in the Middle
East.''
   Dukakis' appearance before the group of leaders from 44 major
national Jewish organizations was an effort to attract support from
Jews, who make up some one-quarter of the Democratic primary
electorate in New York, where the state's huge delegate prize is at
stake next Tuesday.
   Rival Albert Gore Jr. appeared before the group earlier, drawing
a distinction with Dukakis in opposing a letter signed by 30
senators urging Secretary of State George Shultz to press Israel to
come to a peaceful resolution of the West Bank and Gaza violence.
Leaders of the group said Democrat Jesse Jackson, who has drawn
opposition from some Jews for his 1984 reference to New York as
``Hymietown,'' declined an invitation.
   Dukakis faced questions that appeared to challenge him to go
further in drawing distinctions between himself and Jackson,
including one questioner who called Jackson an ``anti-Semite.''
Others pressed him to state opposition to creation of an
independent Palestinian state _ which Dukakis refused to do, saying
that was a matter for Israel and its neighbors to negotiate.
   He was also asked to state a position on the future of
Jerusalem. Dukakis initially said Jerusalem too was ``subject to
negotiation.'' He later told reporters, however, that ``I'm for a
united Jerusalem'' under Israeli control.
   ``Always have been,'' he said.
   He said Jerusalem ``will remain the capital and should remain
the capital'' of Israel.
   Dukakis refused to be drawn into a personal characterization of
Jackson on the Jewish issue. But he cited several differences with
Jackson, such as Jackson's call for returning corporate taxes to
1980 levels, and in general on the Middle East.
   Dukakis also spoke to a large gathering of supporters at an
evening rally on Staten Island.
   He urged them to ignore polls showing him ahead, saying he lost
his 1978 re-election bid despite a lead of as much as 50 points in
polls. ``I've learned from that experience,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
