<2ND_LINE>PM-Box Office,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Beetlejuice' Still Top Of Box Office List</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Beatlejuice,'' a ghostly comedy starring
Michael Keaton, remained the nation's top-grossing movie for a
second week, followed by Neil Simon's comedy ``Biloxi Blues'' and
the religious cult thriller ``Bad Dreams.''
   Academy Award publicity gave ``Moonstruck'' enough increase in
box office gross to return it to a spot in the top 10 last weekend.
   ``Bad Dreams'' and the police thriller ``Above the Law'' made
their first appearances on the list, taking Nos. 3 and 8,
respectively. But ``Above the Law'' had the highest per-screen
average gross, $5,822, slightly ahead of the $5,691 for
``Beetlejuice.''
   ``Beetlejuice'' _ in which Keaton plays a ``bio-exorcist'' hired
by a dead couple to rid their home of its new, living occupants _
was shown on 523 more screens than the previous week, maintaining
its No. 1 spot for a second week with a weekend gross of $8.67
million and a total of $22.91 million.
   ``Biloxi Blues,'' knocked out of the top spot by ``Beetlejuice''
a week ago, stayed in second place as Matthew Broderick's portrayal
of an Army boot camp private drew nearly $4.48 million more for a
total take of $23.2 million.
   ``Bad Dreams,'' about the haunting dreams of the only survivor
of a religious cult's mass suicide, had the weekend's third-highest
gross, nearly $4.01 million.
   Fourth place went to the apocalyptic ``The Seventh Sign,'' with
$3.13 million.
   Michael J. Fox's portrayal of a cocaine-snorting yuppie in
``Bright Lights, Big City,'' dropped from third to fifth, with
$3.09 million.
   Disney saw its re-release of ``The Fox and the Hound'' fall from
fourth to sixth with a weekend take of $2.56 million, while
Disney's comedy ``Good Morning, Vietnam'' stayed No. 7 with a $2.37
million gross.
   ``Above the Law,'' with its nonstop violence, placed eighth with
nearly $2.04 million for its first weekend.
   ``Moonstruck,'' with six Oscar nominations, finished ninth with
$1.82 million.
   No. 10 was the college football recruiting farce ``Johnny Be
Good,'' which took in $1.61 million.
   Here are the top films as tallied by Exhibitor Relations Co.
with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater screens, average
per screen, total gross, number of weeks in release and, when
available, estimated production costs:
   1. ``Beetlejuice,'' Warner Bros., $8.67 million, 1,523 screens,
$5,691 per screen, $22.91 million, two weeks, n-a.
   2. ``Biloxi Blues,'' Universal, $4.48 million, 1,330 screens,
$3,365 per screen, $23.2 million, three weeks, $16 million.
   3. ``Bad Dreams,'' Fox, $4.01 million, 1,180 screens, $3,397 per
screen, $4.01 million, one week (released Friday), n-a.
   4. ``The Seventh Sign,'' Tristar, $3.13 million, 1,258 screens,
$2,487 per screen, $8.69 million, two weeks, n-a.
   5. ``Bright Lights, Big City,'' MGM-UA, $3.09 million, 1,199
screens, $2,575 per screen, $10 million, two weeks, n-a.
   6. ``The Fox and the Hound,'' Disney, $2.56 million, 1,533
screens, $1,672 per screen, $16.49 million, three weeks, $4.8
million.
   7. ``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' Disney, $2.37 million, 1,304
screens, $1,819 per screen, $108.86 million, 15 weeks, $21 million.
   8. ``Above the Law,'' Warner Bros., $2.04 million, 350 screens,
$5,822 per screen, $2.04 million, one week (released Friday), n-a.
   9. ``Moonstruck,'' MGM-UA, $1.82 million, 985 screens, $1,848
per screen, $59.71 million, 16 weeks, $17 million.
   10. ``Johnny Be Good,'' Orion, $1.61 million, 1,164 screens,
$1,385 per screen, $12.94 million, three weeks, $8 million.
