<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WhaleSighting     04-12 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Whale Sighting,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Whale Sighted In Delaware River Near Delaware and New Jersey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A whale was sighted swimming in the
Delaware River Monday, and the Coast Guard warned small boaters to
stay away from the area.
   The Coast Guard, the state marine police and members of the New
Jersey Marine Stranding Center plan to search for the whale
Tuesday, said David Small, spokesman for the Department of Natural
Resources and Environmental Control.
   They and the National Marine Fisheries Service will try to guide
the whale out to sea Tuesday, said a Coast Guard officer.
   ``We've heard reports that it's been out in the (Delaware) Bay
for a couple of days, and that it's up the river near the port of
Wilmington,'' said Small, but he said that state natural resources
officials have not seen the whale themselves.
   The whale has been reported as 35 to 50 feet long, officials
said.
   The Coast Guard in Gloucester, N.J., received a report from a
passing tug about 3:30 p.m. that a whale was in the vicinity of the
Delaware Memorial Bridge, said Coast Guard Petty Officer Keith
Ferguson. The bridge crosses the Delaware River about 30 miles
south of Philadelphia, and connects Delaware and New Jersey.
   ``The Coast Guard is recommending that recreational and private
vessels exercise extreme caution in transiting the Delaware River
in the vicinity of the Delaware Memorial Bridge due to the size and
temperment of the whale,'' Ferguson said. ``The whale could inflict
serious damage to a small boater.''
   Small said he had never heard of a whale swimming up the river
to the industrialized Wilmington-Philadelphia area before, although
whales have been sighted in the bay.
</TEXT>
