<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StolenDocuments     04-12 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stolen Documents,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scholar Convicted Of Selling Stolen Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An indigent art historian says he couldn't afford
to present his side of the case before he was convicted of
transporting stolen historic documents, including letters from
Abraham Lincoln and Winston Churchill.
   Charles Merrill Mount, a Brooklyn native who affects the accent
and manners of a British gentleman, says he will appeal Monday's
conviction for transporting goods belonging to the National
Archives and Library of Congress.
   ``This was not a trial. It was only a hearing of government
allegations,'' said Mount. ``A trial is when both sides present
their case. It did not happen here. ... The government wanted a
conviction and they got a conviction.''
   The 59-year-old historian and author faces up to 10 years in
prison and a $500,000 fine when he is sentenced in U.S. District
Court. He was released on $50,000 bail pending sentencing May 23.
   Charles McGinty, Mount's public defender, said he will appeal on
grounds that the court should have paid transportation costs for
two Irish men Mount wanted as defense witnesses. Mount, whose
$18,400 in savings was seized by the government following the
arrest, claimed his status as indigent required prosecutors to pay
to bring witnesses to Boston.
   At issue were 166 documents, including letters by Lincoln,
Churchill, artist James McNeill Whistler and author Henry James,
that allegedly belonged to the Library of Congress but were sold by
Mount to Goodspeed's Book Shop in Boston for about $20,000 in July.
   Mount, a respected art historian and former Guggenheim
Foundation fellow, said he owned the documents for years, and
showed some of them to the two Irish men, including the president
of a national art academy, in the 1960s in Dublin.
   The government said Mount gained access to the documents last
May and July. Goodspeed's officials had contacted the FBI after the
first transaction with Mount.
   Only one witness appeared for the defense during the three-week
trial, a Nebraska woman who met Mount in a hotel in Ireland in 1961
and said she saw some documents. She paid her fare to Boston.
   The jury deliberated four hours Friday and met for 2{ hours
Monday before returning the verdict.
   Mount also was indicted on possession of federal property
charges by a grand jury in Washington. Frank L. McNamara Jr., U.S.
attorney in Boston, said he did not know if federal prosecutors
would pursue those possession charges.
   Claire Rochefort, a manuscript director at Goodspeed's who
purchased the documents from Mount, is pleased the documents may
return to the National Archives.
   ``They are part of our national heritage,'' said Rochefort. ``We
would like to be reimbursed, but to get the documents back is the
most important thing.''
   Mount, who changed his name from Stanley Merrill Suchow in the
1950s, said he will return to his room in a Washington boarding
house.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
