<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-DavePrater     04-12 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Dave Prater,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dave Prater Sr. Of Sam And Dave Soul Group Dies At 50</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PATERSON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dave Prater Sr. of the Sam and Dave soul
duo, who recorded such hits as ``Soul Man'' and ``Hold On I'm
Comin,''' has died at age 50 in a Georgia car accident.
   Prater was on his way to visit his mother, Mary, in Ocilla, the
small Georgia town where he grew up, his widow, Rosemary, said
Monday. The Praters have lived in Paterson since 1974 and his body
will be returned to New Jersey for burial next week, she said.
   ``Dave was very strong and very able and entertaining was his
life,'' Mrs. Prater said of her husband.
   Prater met partner Sam Moore in Miami in 1958. Their
Memphis-style soul won them popularity through the 1960s and a
Grammy Award for ``Soul Man.'' But by the early 1970s, their
popularity had waned, and in 1981, Moore and Prater broke up.
   Prater revived the Sam and Dave act in 1982 with a new partner,
Sam Daniels of Miami.
   Daniels said he saw Prater the Sunday before he died when they
performed together in Atlanta.
   ``I still feel a little shocked,'' he said Monday night.
   Sam and Dave gained further popularity when the Blues Brothers
of ``Saturday Night Live'' fame, Dan Ackroyd and John Belushi, had
a hit with ``Soul Man.''
   Lately, Prater had run into trouble with drugs, although Mrs.
Prater said he seemed to have the problem beat.
   Prater was arrested last summer in Paterson for selling a vial
of crack to an undercover police officer. He pleaded guilty and was
sentenced March 5 to three years probation and was ordered to pay a
$2,580 fine and perform 150 of community service.
   A funeral service will be held for Prater in Ocilla on Thursday
and his body will be flown back to New Jersey for burial Monday at
a Totowa cemetery, his wife said.
   Prater also is survived by five children from an earlier
marriage.
</TEXT>
