<HEAD>Cher Wins First Oscar for ``Moonstruck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cher, who first gained fame as the
long-haired singing sidekick to a straight man named Sonny Bono,
took home the best actress Oscar Monday night for her performance
as the superstitious young widow of ``Moonstruck.''
   ``I want to really say something,'' she said, upon accepting the
award. ``When I was little my mother said, `I want you to be
something,' and I guess this represents 23 or 24 years of my work,
and I've never won anything before from my peers. I'm really,
really happy.''
   The actress was dressed in a somewhat less revealing gown than
her sensational headdress and bare-belly contraption of two years
ago. But this year's outfit was far from modest _ a black sequined
gown with see-through netting around the torso that was covered
strategically by a thick black cape.
   As she left her seat to come on stage, the audience stood and
applauded, and Cher was hugged by Olympia Dukakis, who won the best
supporting actress award for playing her mother in ``Moonstruck.''
   Oscar in hand, Cher thanked Meryl Streep, who also had been
nominated for ``Ironweed,'' and Miss Streep, who starred with Cher
in 1983's ``Silkwood,'' answered from the audience by blowing
kisses.
   ``I don't think that this means that I am somebody, but I guess
I'm on my way,'' Cher said in closing. She had been nominated in a
supporting role for ``Silkwood'' but did not win.
   Earlier, Bono, who is seeking election as mayor of Palm Springs
in a Tuesday election, said he was sure Cher would win.
   ``I had this vision,'' Bono said. ``This incredible thought
occurred to me. Cher's going to win the Academy Award. I called her
yesterday. I said, `Cher, you're going to win.' She said, `From
your mouth to God's ear.'''
   It's been 23 years since the bell-bottomed, furry-vested rock
couple hit the top of the record charts singing ``I've Got You
Babe,'' and 14 years since both their television show and marriage
hit the rocks.
   ``Wouldn't it be fun if she won the Academy Award and I was
elected mayor?'' Bono asked.
   Nominated for best actress with Cher and Miss Streep were Holly
Hunter for ``Broadcast News,'' Sally Kirkland for ``Anna'' and
Glenn Close, ``Fatal Attraction.''
</TEXT>
