<HEAD>Coy Koch: Decided Whom He'll Support But Won't Say 'Til Week's End</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Mayor Edward I. Koch has decided whom
he will endorse for president _ either Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore
or Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis _ but says he won't reveal
his decision until the end of the week.
   ``I want to keep you thinking about it,'' he twitted reporters
on Monday at the Mayflower Hotel, where he was presenting awards
for urban economic development at a luncheon.
   ``I already made up my mind,'' he said. ``I'm not going to
announce it 'til the end of the week.''
   Koch had been pushing for New York Gov. Mario Cuomo as the
Democratic nominee who would emerge from a deadlocked national
convention. But Cuomo said during the weekend that he will not
accept a draft, freeing Koch to endorse someone else.
   The mayor said he was disappointed at Cuomo's announcement, but
added, ``I believe the impact is nobody is waiting for the other
shoe to fall.''
   The outspoken mayor repeated his reasons for opposing the
candidacy of Jesse Jackson, including his position on the Middle
East and spending programs which Koch says would bankrupt the
nation.
</TEXT>
