<HEAD>Texas' Hightower Stumps Upstate New York for Jesse Jackson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas' populist and popular commissioner of
agriculture went to upstate New York to reassure farmers and other
rural New Yorkers about voting for Jesse Jackson in the state's
April 19 presidential primary.
   ``I bring some comfort factor to farmers who instinctively want
to support Jackson but want to hear it from somewhere in the family
that this is an OK thing to do,'' said Jim Hightower as he began
his tour Monday.
   ``Jesse Jackson has the single best farm program of any of the
candidates,'' said Hightower, who called himself the first white
state official to endorse Jackson for president.
   Hightower's help in upstate New York is ``of enormous value'' to
the Jackson campaign, said Assemblyman Arthur Eve, a Buffalo
Democrat who is chairman of Jackson's upstate campaign.
   ``People know him in the rural areas. They know of his
committment to very progressive agriculture policy,'' said Eve. ``I
think he can help us win New York. ... This election is going to be
won upstate.''
   Upstate New York traditionally accounts for about 25 percent of
the presidential primary day ballot. About 60 percent of the votes
statewide will be cast in New York City and 15 percent in the
city's suburbs.
</TEXT>
