<HEAD>Campbell Aides: Governor To Play Role At Republican Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Carroll Campbell, Southern chairman
for Vice President George Bush's presidential campaign, is likely
to play a highly visible role at the Republican National
Convention, according to a published report.
   A member of Campbell's administration said during the weekend
that Campbell is likely to either nominate Bush or make one of the
three seconding speeches, The Greenville News said in Monday's
editions.
   ``It's going to be one of those,'' said the administration
official who asked not to be identified.
   Lee Atwater, Bush's national campaign chairman and Campbell's
former campaign manager, said he didn't want to discuss the
Republican governor's specific role at the national convention in
New Orleans Aug. 15-18. ``But he'll have one,'' Atwater told the
newspaper.
   Campbell, who is both personally and politically close to Bush,
also is considered a long-shot vice presidential possibility, but
Campbell has said he doesn't believe he will be chosen.
   Making a nominating or seconding speech would enhance the
prestige of the governor, who is expected to run for re-election
beginning in 1990 and is widely perceived as having Senate
aspirations, the News said.
   Bush has all but locked up the GOP nomination with only Pat
Robertson retaining some delegate commitments and an organization,
mainly to influence platform and party direction and to build for a
1992 presidential campaign.
