<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FosterAbuse     04-12 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Foster Abuse,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youth Club Founder Indicted on Abuse Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MENSING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A community activist who founded a city youth
center and has been a foster parent to 21 children was charged with
sexually assaulting two teen-age boys in his care, authorities said.
   A grand jury on Monday indicted the Rev. Paul J. Hall, 41, of
suburban South Holland, on 16 counts of criminal sexual assault and
eight counts of aggravated criminal sexual abuse.
   Hall surrendered late Monday and was released after posting 10
percent of a $25,000 bond, said South Holland police spokeswoman
Georgianna Musket.
   He will plead innocent to the charges, said his attorney, Brent
Stratton.
   Hall, a non-denominational clergyman, attracted widespread
attention through food giveaways and other community programs run
out of a storefront headquarters on Chicago's South Side. Since
beginning the giveaways in 1980, he has kept a 25-day fast each
Christmas.
   The assaults on the two boys, now ages 15 and 16, occurred from
mid-1986 through last fall, when Hall was a foster parent to six
children at his home, said Cook County State's Attorney Richard M.
Daley.
   ``The evidence clearly shows that the Reverend Hall betrayed the
trust of these two children,'' Daley said.
   In January, South Holland Police Chief Dennis Smits said Hall
had called Chicago police to report that a 15-year-old foster child
had run away.
   The teen-ager, found at O'Hare International Airport, made
allegations of abuse, Smits said. The six children living with Hall
were removed from his supervision.
   Hall has been a foster parent for the state Department of
Children and Family Services since 1979 and has cared for 21 foster
children, said department spokeswoman Jo Warfield.
   The agency had received no complaints about Hall before, said
Robert Moore, chief of internal investigations for the agency.
   ``How did he slip through the cracks? If we knew that, we could
solve the problem,'' said Moore. ``You can't just stop every act.
We continue to look at and review what went wrong and hope we can
close up that crack.''
   Hall founded the Paul Hall Boys Club in the 1960s. He later
branched out into other youth-oriented programs, such as a 24-hour
hotline for gang members seeking to go straight.
   Hall also established drop-off centers for gang members who
wanted to turn in weapons.
   Daley said the charges are not connected to Hall's youth center,
which admits girls and boys. The club is not associated with the
Boys & Girls Club of Chicago or its national affiliate, the Boys
Clubs of America.
   Daley said allegations concerning other children in Hall's care
are being investigated. Ms. Warfield said her agency is taking
steps to lift Hall's license to be a foster parent.
   Hall is to be arraigned May 2. If convicted of all the charges,
he could be sentenced to 296 years in prison.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
