<DOCNO> AP880412-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Oscars-Bertolucci     04-12 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oscars-Bertolucci,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>``The Last Emperor'' Sweeps Nine of Nine Nominations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As expected, ``The Last Emperor'' swept the
60th Academy Awards ceremony Monday night, taking Oscars in each of
its nine nominated categories including direction and Best Picture.
   ``I must give a Chinese kow-tow to the Academy. This is one of
the strongest emotions of my life, and I can't hide it,'' said
Bernardo Bertolucci, who directed the epic about China's boy ruler
Pu Yi.
   Bertolucci took the Oscar for best director, the first Italian
director to win in this category. The film also won for art
direction, cinematography, sound, film editing, original score,
costume design, adapted screenplay and picture.
   It was the most Oscars won by a single movie since 1962, when
``West Side Story'' took 10 awards. The record is held by the 1959
``Ben-Hur,'' which won 11.
   Producer Jeremy Thomas accepted the best picture award saying,
``I must say this is certainly an imperial evening for me.''
   Bertolucci thanked China for allowing him to shoot there. The
director amazed the film industry by winning permission to shoot a
movie with political overtones in China and to take cameras into
the fabled Forbidden City, the shrine of Chinese history.
   The logistics of the film's production included actors from six
nations, and 19,000 extras who played the soldiers of the People's
Liberation Army.
   It was Bertolucci's second nomination for directing, the first
being for ``Last Tango in Paris'' in 1973. He also received a
writing nomination for his screenplay of ``The Conformist'' in 1971.
   ``As an Italian, a European, the Acadeny Awards always seemed
like a distant ceremony: Distant, remote, something I did not
belong to,'' Bertolucci told the Shrine Auditorium audience.
   ``Then one day ``The Last Emperor'' got nine nominations and
everything changed immediately,'' he said.
   Asked backstage about the lack of acting nominations for the
picture, Bertolucci said, ``This is a democratic election, so what
can I say?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
