<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Oscars-ForeignLanguage     04-12 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oscars-Foreign Language,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>``Babette's Feast'' Named Best Foreign Film</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Oscars, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Babette's Feast,'' a Danish movie about two
pious, unmarried sisters who take a political refugee into their
home, won best foreign language film at the Academy Awards.
   ``It's the first time a Danish movie can take an Oscar home,''
director Gabriel Axel, who spent 14 years trying to get the movie
made, said as he accepted the award Monday night.
   ``I am very grateful for this honor and I want to thank you
Academy members from the bottom of my heart.''
   Also nominated were ``Au Revoir Les Enfants,'' France; ``Course
Completed,'' Spain; ``The Family,'' Italy, and ``Pathfinder,''
Norway.
   Axel has divided his career between his native Denmark and
France.
   ``Babette's Feast'' portrayed the lives of the sisters who took
in a political refugee named Babette (Stephane Audran) fleeing the
French revolution.
   The refugee, a former world-class chef, later repays their
kindness by devoting her winnings from a lottery to creation of a
sumptuous feast.
   The film, titled ``Babettes Gaestebud'' in Denmark, was based on
a short story by Isak Dinesen, whose book ``Out of Africa'' was the
basis for the 1986 best movie Oscar winner.
   Following his success with ``Babette's Feast,'' Axel has said he
hopes to film a project he has nurtured for 20 years _ a version of
``Hamlet'' based on the earliest histories of the saga from which
Shakespeare borrowed his plot.
   Thirty countries submitted movies for consideration as best
foreign film for this year's Academy Awards ceremony. The record
for foreign submissions was 32 in 1984, according to Bob Werden, an
Academy spokesman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
