<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0308EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-APonTV-Oscars     04-12 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Oscars,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Despite Writers Strike, Oscar Is Wordy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Oscars, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for story listed on PM-News Digest as PM-Oscars-TV</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's amazing that despite a writers' strike
the Academy Awards could still be so gaseous and wordy.
   Everybody talked nonstop during Monday night's 60th annual
Oscars ceremony on ABC: the host, the presenters, and especially
the winners.
   There were frequent references to the strike by the Writers
Guild of America, and to the fact that some people had no scripts.
It didn't slow anyone down, however. The winners seemed to have
carte blanche to blab on until there was no one left to thank.
   Even master storyteller Billy Wilder, in accepting the Irving
Thalberg Award for lifetime achievement, rambled before making a
poignant statement about his permanent entry into this country.
   It was an awards show that offered few surprises. Every front
runner won as expected. The only suspense was whether ``The Last
Emperor'' would win in all nine nominated categories. It did.
   The biggest thrill was seeing Cher win as best actress for
``Moonstruck.'' Cher, like Sally Field before her, has come a long
way after a start in music and television that gave little hint of
her talent.
   The awards show, as it has in recent years, got off to a fast,
promising start. The opening number with the dancing gold Oscars
was original and rousing. Host Chevy Chase set an irreverent tone
when he addressed the audience: ``Good evening, Hollywood phonies.''
   The presentation of the animated shorts award by Mickey Mouse,
with an assist from Tom Selleck, was an inspired piece of casting.
   Last year's most eloquent winner, Marlee Matlin of ``Children of
a Lesser God,'' stole the show again. The hearing-impaired actress
spoke as she announced the nominees for best actor and named
Michael Douglas as the winner.
   Robin Williams, a nominee for best actor and presenter of the
Oscar for best director, also stole the show in his own inimitable
way. He was very funny, and when he uttered a phrase that could
have gotten on the air only on a live show he chortled at his own
naughtiness. ``The phones are lighting up, folks,'' he said. ``The
number is 1-800-Robin.''
   Bernardo Bertolucci won as best director for ``The Last
Emperor.'' When he returned later to accept another award as
co-writer of the screenplay he explained that the guards wouldn't
let him back into the auditorium until he displayed his Oscar.
   The show, scheduled to run three hours, ran slightly more than
3{ hours. Not quite a record, but wearily close.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880412-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0224EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Zimbabwe Bjt   04-12 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zimbabwe, Bjt,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Merger Of Rivals Brings Virtual One-Party State To Zimbabwe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The merger of two black political groups
that led the war to end white-minority rule in Zimbabwe, then
Rhodesia, virtually abolishes one of Africa's few multiparty states.
   ``We have one Zimbabwe, one nation and one national army. We
will be stronger if we have one party,'' President Robert Mugabe
said at a weekend rally.
   Mugabe, an avowed Marxist, led his party to victory in elections
held after a British-sponsored peace conference ended years of
guerrilla warfare and Zimbabwe became independent in April 1980.
   His chief rival in the balloting was Joseph Nkomo, one of the
country's wealthiest men. They had organized guerrilla armies in
the 1960s to gain black-majority rule and toward the end of the
campaign joined forces. But the alliance collapsed in 1980, after
Mugabe's resounding victory and scattered clashes followed between
the supporters of both sides.
   Mugabe, head of the Zimbabwe African National Union, advocated
one-party rule and was opposed by Nkomo and his Zimbabwe African
Peoples Union.
   But last week, a Peoples Union convention endorsed a merger
approved in December by Mugabe and Nkomo. On Saturday, National
Union conference delegates approved the agreement.
   It is expected that by the end of the year, Mugabe's party will
be by law the sole political party in this southern African nation.
   Opponents say Mugabe's party will turn capitalist Zimbabwe into
a socialist state with Parliament becoming a rubber-stamp
legislature.
   Supporters claim the merger will bring unity to an area divided
by tribal differences and with political structures too fragile to
withstand the rigors of Western-style multiparty politics.
   The merger does not basically expand Mugabe's solid power base.
He has been in control since his party won 57 of Parliament's 100
seats in pre-independence elections and has increased the number
the number since then to 85.
   But the merger will give him the support to revise the
British-drafted constitution that dictated a multiparty system for
the first 10 years after independence. The constitution can be
changed during that period only by a unanimous parliemtary vote.
   The new united party will control all but one legislative seat.
   A businessman, Goodson Sithole, is the only representative of a
small party that broke from the National Union.
   He could block the one-party move with a negative vote, but
isn't expected to stand up against the combined weight of the two
main parties.
   For Mugabe, 64, his goal of creating a Marxist-Leninist state
has involved more rhetoric then reality in his eight years in
power. Zimbabwe remains one of Africa's staunchest capitalist
countries and whites, internally and externally, still control the
economy.
   But Mugabe has made it clear he expects the country's leaders to
be socialists.
   ``Surely, they (his opponents) cannot be allowed to walk our
public path of socialism with us, when at the same time they have
charted for themselves their own private path of capitalism,'' he
said at the convention on Saturday.
   For 70-year-old Nkomo the merger is a chance for the ``old
lion,'' as his supporters call him, to leave the political scene
with some of his former glory.
   Nkomo had been dumped from a coalition government shortly after
the 1980 elections. But when the merger plans were announced in
December after three years of negotiations, he became one of three
senior ministers in the Cabinet. In the new united party he will be
second vice-president _ the No. 3 slot.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Jerry Gray has covered southern African politics
for three years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880412-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0309EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-OrganizedCrime 1stLd-Writethru   04-12 0670</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Organized Crime, 1st Ld-Writethru,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witnesses Say It Has Become Easier To Get Testimony From Mafiosi</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RETRANSMITTING to add writethru designator and correct
overline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Omerta _ the Mafia code of silence _ is
crumbling as authorities find it easier to turn mobsters into
witnesses, according to top law enforcement officials and a former
member of the Sicilian Mafia.
   ``When the going gets tough, the smart change sides,'' John C.
Keeney, acting chief of the Justice Department's Criminal Division,
told a Senate subcommittee on Monday. ``The number and stature of
convicted mobsters `flipping' to the government's side in recent
years is unprecedented.''
   Before Keeney testified at the most extensive Senate organized
crime hearings in a quarter-century, former Sicilian mobster
Tommaso Buscetta helped prove Keeney's point.
   Shielded by a screen to protect the public from seeing him,
Buscetta said the Mafia in Italy has changed so drastically because
of the drug trade that ``I no longer feel bound by the code of
`omerta.'''
   He testified before the Senate Permanent Subcommittee on
Investigations, which held dramatic hearings on organized crime a
quarter-century ago. The chief witness then was Joseph Valachi, who
told the panel the inner workings of La Cosa Nostra.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., said he will hold three more hearings, so
the panel can assess the state of organized crime 25 years after
Valachi's testimony.
   Monday's most dramatic testimony came from Buscetta, who spoke
in Italian and had his words translated for the committee. Buscetta
has testified previously for the U.S. and Italian governments and
helped convict nearly 500 mobsters, most in Italy, Nunn said.
   FBI Director William S. Sessions, two of his top aides, and
Keeney all told the senators that law enforcement officials have
severely damaged organized crime _ in part through new statutes and
partly because the code of silence is now often broken. Buscetta
gave some insight on why this has happened.
   ``Over the years, I have seen our organization change from
within,'' Buscetta testified. ``I have seen money, drugs, and greed
corrupt and destroy the Cosa Nostra code of honor and loyalty to
the families.
   ``I began to realize that drugs had changed everything, the
family loyalties and codes of respect that I had known as a Mafioso
were quickly becoming things of the past.''
   Sessions testified: ``Omerta ... has been broken in recent
years. The FBI has not only secured the cooperation and testimony
of numerous individuals who have been utilized by the LCN (La Cosa
Nostra) to promote their criminal activities but has elicited the
cooperation of four LCN members whose knowledge and testimony ...
has enabled the FBI to expand the attack on this national criminal
enterprise.''
   He identified the four as Aladena Frattiano, the former acting
boss of the Los Angeles LCN family; Angelo Lonardo, the former
underboss of the Cleveland organized crime family; and Thomas Del
Giorno and Nicholas Caramandi, a capo (lieutenant) and soldier
respectively in the Philadelphia family.
   FBI executive assistant director Oliver B. Revell III said Mafia
families in the United States have not taken over the drug trade,
although individual organized-crime members are involved with
narcotics.
   ``There's a change in LCN membership,'' said Anthony E. Daniels,
deputy assistant FBI director in the criminal investigative
division. ``Where there is money to be made, members of LCN will
become involved in anything.''
   Revell also told the committee that the FBI believes it knows
who is responsible for the disappearance of former Teamsters union
head Jimmy Hoffa on July 30, 1975.
   Revell did not name them, but said they are in prison on other
charges. Revell said he doubted there would be enough evidence to
bring them to trial.
   The FBI on earlier occasions has asserted that it believed it
knew who killed Hoffa. An FBI memo suggested Hoffa's disappearance
was linked to Anthony ``Tony Pro'' Provenzano, a former New Jersey
Teamsters boss and reputed organized crime captain imprisoned on a
racketeering conviction. Provenzano has denied he was involved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
