<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--AT&T-Olson, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0483,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AT&T Chairman Steps Down Temporarily After Surgery</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to restore name of newspaper that published the
story; Version moving on financial wire</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James E. Olson, chairman and chief executive of
American Telephone & Telegraph Co., has relinquished his duties
temporarily following major surgery for removal of a malignant
tumor, a newspaper reported today.
   Olson, 62, underwent surgery March 25 for removal of a tumor,
The New York Times quoted an unidentified AT&T spokesman as saying.
The tumor was malignant and Olson is undergoing chemotherapy as an
outpatient, the spokesman said.
   Robert E. Allen, AT&T's president and chief operating officer,
has taken charge.
   The spokesman said it was too soon to determine how long Olson
would need to recover.
   Olson, a 44-year employee with the telecommunications giant, has
served as its chairman and chief executive since 1986.
   He began his career cleaning dirt from telephone manholes and
eventually rose through several management jobs at other Bell
companies before becoming president of Illinois Bell. He moved to
AT&T headquarters in 1977.
</TEXT>
