<DOCNO> AP880412-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BabyHearts     04-12 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby Hearts,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anencephalic Donor Program Temporarily Halted; Baby's Respirator
Removed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hospital suspended its largely unsuccessful
effort to harvest organs for transplants from infants born with
most of their brains missing, as doctors took the sixth such baby
off life support.
   Ten-day-old Hope Lovette Mount, of Knoxville, Tenn., was removed
from life support Monday and will be allowed to die, spokesman Dick
Schafer said by telephone from Loma Linda University Medical
Center, 60 miles east of Los Angeles.
   Schaefer said that while Loma Linda plans to maintain five to
seven more anencephalic babies on life support so they can be used
as organ donors, the hospital won't do so until it modifies its
existing guidelines for use of such infants, who are born with most
of their brains missing.
   The review will be completed within two weeks, he said, refusing
to elaborate on the planned changes.
   Loma Linda's program was aimed at maintaining anencephalic
babies on respirators for seven days or until they were declared
brain-dead, whichever came first. Anencephalic babies inevitably
die within days to weeks.
   The idea was to maintain them on life support so their organs
wouldn't deteriorate as they died. The seven-day limit was
established to counter criticism that the doomed babies were being
kept alive _ and suffering _ indefinitely merely to save the lives
of other babies needing donated organs.
   A Southern California infant identified only as Baby John was
the only one of the six anencephalic babies maintained on life
support at Loma Linda to be declared brain-dead within the
seven-day limit. But a suitable recipient for his heart and other
organs could not be found.
   None of the five others were suitable for donations of major
organs, although heart valves and corneas were transplanted from
some of them.
   Loma Linda surgeons did transplant an anencephalic's heart into
Paul Holc, the son of a British Columbia couple, last Oct. 16. But
that heart came from a baby girl who was maintained on life support
in London, Ontario, not at Loma Linda.
   Paul, who received his new heart three hours after his birth by
Caesarean section, was the world's youngest transplant recipient.
He has been released from the hospital and physicians said recently
he was doing well.
   Loma Linda triggered a major medical controversy in 1984 when
Dr. Leonard Bailey implanted a baboon's heart in a girl known as
Baby Fae, who was born with a fatally underdeveloped heart and died
20{ days after the transplant. Since then, the hospital turned
toward anencephalic babies as possible organ donors for infants
with fatal heart defects.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
