<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BetterTV     04-12 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Better TV,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Finds Mixed U.S. Viewer Reax For High-Resolution TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American television viewers welcome the
improved picture quality of high-resolution television but are
unwilling to pay a premium for it, according to initial audience
testing studies.
   One study presented Monday at the National Association of
Broadcasters convention here found that viewers usually preferred
the clear and more brilliant picture produced by experimental
high-definition TV (HDTV), though the perceived improvement over
conventional TV was subtle when watched on the size of sets found
in most American homes.
   Screens would have to be two to three times larger to have a
significant impact, it concluded.
   ``There will be HDTV. Most viewers most of the time prefer HDTV
(to conventional TV),'' said W. Russell Neuman, associate professor
at the Media Laboratory at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, who conducted the study. ``But with the wrong price and
the wrong programming and at the wrong time, HDTV could fail.''
   Audience research conducted by Home Box Office, which provides
programming to cable TV systems, shows that viewers, particularly
young men, prefer the improved-quality picture of HDTV but were
resistant to paying significantly more for it.
   ``Consumers are going to have to be aggressively marketed and
the price will have to be close to the price for existing TVs,''
said Robert Maxwell, HBO vice president for research.
   Maxwell said the company's testing found that viewers could
recognize HDTV's better quality picture when comparing it
side-by-side to a conventional TV picture, but most could not tell
the difference when alternately watching an HDTV picture separately
from a conventional one.
   Two hundred sixty-eight viewers participated in HBO's in
side-by-side testing and 499 in an alternate viewing test. Both
groups were watched 25-inch conventional sets and 28-inch HDTV sets.
   Maxwell said his results were preliminary and his research was
not yet completed. But, he said, ``when we have better equipment
and material and tests, I think the results will show consumers
have high interest'' in HDTV, though ``they aren't going to pay a
lot more for a TV set than they are now.''
   The HBO and Media Lab research indicates that the introduction
of HDTV to American consumers could be slow, especially considering
that the first HDTV sets are estimated to cost more than $3,500. As
with most new technology, prices would be expected to drop as sales
increase.
   Neuman said his research contradicts the accepted wisdom of
video professionals ``which posits that HDTV knocks the socks off
everyone who sees it, represents an entirely new medium for
storing, transmitting and displaying moving images, and will
replace older media just as color TV replaced black and white.''
   The Media Lab study, admittedly an early experiment, was
conducted in a shopping mall in Danvers, Mass., in early December.
For 30 minutes, 613 randomly selected shoppers, in groups of five
to 20, watched a variety of programs on conventional and HDTV sets.
   Sixty-two percent said they preferred the quality of HDTV
overall, a figure Neuman said shows the new technology will not be
a revolutionary development.
   He said he finds no basis for TV broadcasters' fears that their
very survival could be threatened if the Japanese begin selling
HDTV video cassette recorders and receivers in the United States
before broadcasters settle on an HDTV transmission system for their
over-the-air signals.
   The Japanese plan to offer a satellite-based high definition TV
system to homes in that country in 1990. The Europeans are expected
to introduce their own system a couple of years later, but U.S.
research has lagged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880412-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0334EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     04-12 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Agree To Resume Technical Talks On Peace Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan rebels agreed to a call
from the leftist Sandinista government to resume technical talks on
a cease-fire plan that had stalled over arms shipments to the
U.S.-supported Contras.
   In another development, the opposition newspaper La Prensa
received a fresh supply of newsprint from the government on Monday
and said it would resume publication today for the first time since
April 5.
   Cristiana Chamorro, La Prensa assistant director, said the paper
received 42 tons of newsprint from the government-owned monopoly at
mid-day Monday, too late for La Prensa editors to put out an
afternoon edition.
   La Prensa had attributed the cutoff of newsprint to
``discrimination of the government.'' It noted that Barricada, the
Sandinista party mouthpiece, and the pro-government El Nuevo Diario
continued to publish without interruption.
   The Nicaraguan Resistance, the main Contra umbrella group, on
Monday night said it will send a delegation to the southern town of
Sapoa on Wednesday to resume the talks. There was no immediate
reaction from the government.
   Earlier Monday, the Sandinistas proposed that the talks be held
Wednesday or Thursday and suggested the Contras send an advance
team to Managua to prepare for high-ranking political discussions
scheduled for Friday.
   In Washington, D.C., Contra spokesman Bosco Matamoros released a
statement proposing the technical talks resume at noon Wednesday in
Sapoa.
   Top-level Contra leaders will travel to Managua on Friday to
continue the peace negotiations with the Sandinistas based on
progress at the Sapoa talks, the statement said. ``The high level
commission composed of members of the directorate will arrive in
Managua April 15 subject to the work of the special commission,''
it said.
   The statement added that Roberto Ferrey, secretary of the
resistance directorate, and David Stadhagen, another Contra
representative, will arrive in Managua on Thursday to work out the
agenda for the high-level meeting.
   Last Friday, military commanders of the two sides suspended
negotiations on defining how the Contras are to gather in
cease-fire zones in Nicaragua. The meetings ended after the Contras
asked for a recess of several days to discuss a 25-point government
plan.
   The talks are called for in the March 23 cease-fire agreement
reached by Sandinista and Contra leaders in Sapoa. Under terms of
the plan, Contra guerrillas were to gather at the zones during the
first 15 days of April. A provisional 60-day cease-fire went into
effect April 1.
   In six days of discussions, both sides agreed on seven zones but
failed to define the operating conditions and security measures.
   A 34-point Contra proposal would allow the rebels to maintain
munitions in the zones. It also would prohibit the Sandinistas from
receiving any military aid from the Soviet bloc.
   Paul Reichler, an American lawyer negotiating for the
Sandinistas, described those two points as ``absolutely
unacceptable.''
   The cease-fire plan would permit the Contras to receive only
food and basic supplies channeled through a neutral organization.
   Political leaders of both sides had been scheduled to meet last
Wednesday in Managua but the rebels postponed the meeting, saying
the technical talks in Sapoa had not advanced enough to move toward
political issues.
   The rebels also have said they will not continue the high-level
political talks unless they are free to meet with opposition
leaders in Managua.
   The government maintains that the peace agreement specifies
Contra representation in politics begins only after the rebels move
into the cease-fire zones.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
