<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0337EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador-Killings     04-12 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador-Killings,0635</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Pleased With Revocation Of Amnesty In Slaying Of Americans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Embassy applauded a
decision by President Jose Napoleon Duarte that revoked an amnesty
for three men charged in the 1985 slaying of six Americans.
   Duarte cited an international treaty as the legal basis for
denying amnesty to the three suspects, said Rene Valdivieso, the
secretary of the Martial Court, who announced the decision Monday.
   ``On the issue of amnesty, it has been the position of the U.S.
government that this attack on innocent unarmed persons should not
go unpunished,'' said U.S. Embassy spokesman Joseph McManus. ``We
welcome President Duarte's decision to forward the case to the
courts where evidence can be brought and a decision rendered.''
   Thirteen people were killed on June 19, 1985, when assailants
wearing Salvadoran ary uniforms opened fire with automatic weapons
on patrons at two outdoor cafes in San Salvador. Among the dead
were four off-duty Marines and two U.S. businessmen.
   The Marines, who were guards at the U.S. Embassy, wore civilian
clothes and sat at two tables with other young people when the
attackers drove up.
   A little-known leftist group, the Mardoqueo Cruz Urban Guerrilla
Commandos, claimed responsibility for the killings. The group is an
offshoot of one of the five guerrilla armies that form the
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, which has been fighting
the U.S.-backed Salvadoran government for eight years.
   Juan Garcia Melendez and Jose Dimas Aguilar are charged with
helping plan the ``Pink Zone massacre,'' named after the
fashionable district of shops and restaurants where the killings
occurred.
   William Rivas Bolanos is the only one of the three the
government alleges was among the gunmen.
   None of the three has been tried. Eight other people, who are
fugitives, allegedly took part in the crime.
   Duarte's government decreed a broad amnesty in November 1987 as
part of a regional peace accord. About 450 people were freed under
the measure, which applied to those convicted or accused of
politically motivated crimes.
   When the Martial Court, the country's highest military tribunal,
ruled in January that the three men should receive amnesty, the
U.S. government called the decision ``morally mistaken and
politically damaging.''
   The U.S. Congress later approved a measure that calls for
withholding 10 percent of appropriated economic aid to El Salvador
if the suspects are freed. The three were kept in jail pending
Duarte's review of the case.
   A lower court military judge had ruled the three should be
covered by the amnesty because their alleged crime was politically
motivated. Duarte, as commander-in-chief of the armed forces, is
empowered to review the Martial Court's decision.
   The treaty cited by Duarte, the Convention on the Prevention and
Punishment of Crimes Against Internationally Protected Persons, was
ratified by El Salvador in 1980.
   ``According to the president, the treaty takes precedence over
the amnesty law,'' Valdivieso told reporters.
   Lawyer Armando Portillo, representing the suspects, said he has
not decided whether to appeal the case to the Supreme Court. He
called Duarte's reasoning ``arbitrary.''
   The amnesty program was part of El Salvador's compliance with a
Central American peace plan signed in August 1987 by Duarte and the
presidents of Nicaragua, Costa Rica, Honduras and Guatemala.
   About one-third of those freed under the program were leftist
guerrillas. Another third were accused or convicted of crimes,
including murder and torture, by rightist organizations. The
political leanings of the other third was unclear.
   Two former national guardsmen convicted in the 1981 murders of
two U.S. land reform advisers were freed under the amnesty. Five
national guardsmen convicted in the 1980 murders of four American
churchwomen were not covered by the measure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
