<HEAD>Stocks Rise, Edge Back; Dollar Higher In Tokyo</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with market close, details;
pickup 4th pvs, `A selling ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices finished at a record close Tuesday in
Tokyo, while the U.S. dollar also edged up in trading against the
Japanese yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 175.98-point gainer Monday, added another 5.97
points, or 0.02 percent, to finish the day at 26,930.84, its
highest close ever.
   The dollar closed at 126.50 yen, up 0.79 yen from its close of
125.71 yen Monday. It had opened the day at 126.40 and traded
between 126.38-126.67 yen.
   ``A selling mood is in the stock market,'' said Michio Katsumata
of Nomura Securities. ``The average (share) price is quite high, so
some investors are quite sensitive to profit-taking.''
   The Nikkei touched a record 26,998.36 in early trading Monday.
   On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar traded at about
126.65 yen at mid-morning, up from Tuesday's opening of 126.40 yen
and from Monday's close of 125.71 yen.
