<HEAD>Judge Orders Hinckley To Be Questioned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ordered presidential
assailant John W. Hinckley Jr. to be questioned in a deposition
prior to a civil trial arising from the 1981 shooting of President
Reagan.
   U.S. District Judge John Garrett Penn on Monday approved a
motion by lawyers representing White House press secretary James S.
Brady and two other people wounded in the March 30, 1981, shooting
to question Hinckley before the case goes to trial later this month.
   The trial of the multimillion-dollar lawsuits brought by Brady,
retired Washington policeman Thomas K. Delahanty and Secret Service
agent Timothy J. McCarthy is scheduled to begin April 26 before
Penn.
   Hinckley, who was confined to St. Elisabeths mental hospital
here following his 1982 acquittal by reason of insanity of
attempted murder charges, has asked to attend the trial, which
could last several days.
   Penn said at a hearing that he has made arrangements with the
U.S. Marshals Service for Hinckley to be present.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Amnesty To Be Extended to Aliens Who Overstayed Visas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says that it will immediately
begin accepting applications for amnesty from illegal aliens who
overstayed their student and tourist visas.
   Until further notice, the Immigration and Naturalization Service
also announced Monday that it will defer the fee for such
applications and issue a temporary work authorization card, in
accordance with a court directive.
   INS regulations originally stipulated that non-immigrant aliens
who overstayed their tourist or student visas must demonstrate that
any violation of their immigration status had come to the attention
of the INS before Jan. 1, 1982, for them to qualify for the amnesty
program.
   In a ruling on a class-action suit, U.S. District Judge Stanley
Sporkin said the regulation was too restrictive and declared that
Congress intended the law to mean that any government record, such
as tax or Social Security documents, could be used to document that
an illegal alien was known to federal authorities as of Jan. 1,
1982.
   Immigration experts say the clarifications affect at least
50,000 people.
   Under the 1986 immigration law, illegal aliens who have been in
the country at least since Jan. 1, 1982, may qualify for legalized
status. A 12-month application period for the amnesty program is
due to expire May 4.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pizza Parlor Owner Wanted In Italy Ordered Deported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pizza parlor owner wanted in Italy in
connection with the murder of a Sicilian judge has been ordered
deported by an Immigration and Naturalization Service judge.
   Salvatore Inzerillo, part-owner of a restaurant in Woodbridge,
Va., had asked to be allowed to leave the country voluntarily.
   But Judge Joan V. Arrowsmith Monday denied the request, saying
that would allow Inzerillo to go to the country of his choice. She
said he should be returned to Italy for trial.
   Inzerillo has been in INS custody since Feb. 23. Italian
authorities have issued an arrest warrant for him in the 1980
slaying of Judge Gaetano Costa, who was investigating drug
trafficking in Sicily.
   FBI agent James L. Glass Jr. testified that Inzerillo had
connections with the Mafia, but Inzerillo denied being a member of
the Mafia and said he is not a drug dealer.
   Inzerillo said he hired a smuggler to get him into the United
States in 1981 to seek work. His attorney said he will appeal the
deportation ruling.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Swedish Monarchs Preview Exhibit, Mark 350th Anniversary Of Colony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Carl Gustaf XIV and Queen Silvia of
Sweden have begun a tour of the United States to participate in
events around the country marking the 350th anniversary of the
first Swedish colony in America.
   On Monday the royal couple posed in front of an oil painting of
their family as they previewed a 60-piece exhibit of masterpieces
from the Gripsholm Castle at the National Portrait Gallery .
   The exhibit which opens formally Wednesday, includes their
family portrait, painted by John-Erik Franzen in 1985, whichis one
of the 4,000 works at Gripsholm Castle which is Sweden's national
portrait museum.
   Among the exhibits are 100 objects, never before shown in the
United States, including the Swedish crown jewels, a selection of
armor and weapons, the wedding costume of Gustavus Adolphus and the
elaborate velvet gown worn by 4-year-old Charles XI when he became
king.
   The exhibition will be on display in the gallery's East Building
until Sept. 5. Then the items will go to the Institute of Arts at
Minneapolis, Minn., where many immigrants from Sweden settled. They
will be on view there from Oct. 9 to Jan. 1, 1989.
</TEXT>
