<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Oscars-Scene     04-12 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oscars-Scene,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parade of Hollywood Glitter Wows Fans, But The Winner Is ... Cher!</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Oscars, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cher was as big a hit outside the Shrine
Auditorium as inside, drawing gasps from more than a thousand fans
packed into street grandstands when she stepped from her limousine
in a stunning see-through gown.
   ``Go, go, go, go, go!'' chanted fans on each side of a
red-carpeted walkway leading to the cavernous hall, as nominees
arrived Monday amid a hullabaloo that has become an annual rite of
the Academy Awards ceremony.
   Cher, who won best actress for ``Moonstruck,'' continued her
tradition of outrageous outfits despite the seeming consensus among
the stars this year for toned-down, mostly black fashions _ in
variations of long, short, strapless, body-hugging and
black-on-white or white-on-black.
   Arriving fashionably late in the 90-degree heat, Cher knocked
the scream meter off the scale when she stepped from her limousine
in a diaphanous outfit partly covered by a dark black cape and
swept into the auditorium.
   However, for a time the Oscar ritual of hasty introductions,
interviews and cheers for favorite stars gave way to a traffic jam,
perhaps caused by the show's move from its longtime home at the
Dorothy Chandler Pavilion in the Los Angeles Music Center.
   ``Please make room for the people outside to get in!'' Oscars
greeter Army Archerd pleaded over a loudspeaker as arriving members
of the Academy of Motion Pictures Arts and Sciences and nominees
backed up at the auditorium's doors as showtime neared.
   ``We are working in very tight quarters,'' said Archerd. ``The
Academy has decided to be here for three years, so you better get
used to it.''
   ``Booooo,'' shouted the crowd packed into bleachers alongside
the walkway.
   The 60th annual Oscars marked the award show's first return to
the Shrine, on the edge of an old neighborhood next to the
University of Southern California, since 1947.
   ``The traffic was so bad I was being asphyxiated in the limo,''
said character actor Peter Mark Richman, who appears in TV's
``Bonanza: The Next Generation.''
   Fans dressed in shorts, sandals and T-shirts watched a 10-block
procession of limousines and frequented a garden hose that was set
up by the Academy for curbside refreshment in the heat.
   Fifteen minutes before showtime, actresses Meryl Streep and
Glenn Close, who is nine months pregnant, were seen walking quickly
up Jefferson Boulevard to the theater to make it on time.
   ``Fatal Attraction'' co-star Anne Archer wore a wide-shouldered,
sleeveless black dress with a V-cut back and a silvered midriff
along with black gloves. Sally Kirkland, star of ``Anna,'' was
elegant in a strapless black gown with a velvet bodice.
   Faye Dunaway was sharp in a black skirt and a white jacket with
a black-stripe design. ``Dirty Dancing'' star Jennifer Grey came in
a tight, shoulderless, long-sleeve mini. Liza Minnelli topped a
long black dress with a red cape.
   There were daring exceptions. Candice Bergen arrived
bare-shouldered in a form-fitting red dress. Marlee Matlin stepped
out in strapless, knee-length purple dress with a large bow at her
waist. Daryl Hannah glittered in a white-gold, knee-length dress
and gold high heels.
   And, of course, the perennial Edie Williams strutted back and
forth in front of the cameras in a pale blue bikini top and mini
skirt, sporting a puppy on one shoulder.
   Archerd later whipped up the fans with an impromptu fan poll.
The best picture winner on the applause meter was ``Moonstruck.''
The movie, however, lost out in the Academy voting to ``The Last
Emperor,'' which garnered that Oscar and eight others.
</TEXT>
