<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     04-12 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Moves Further From Arafat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson continued to reach out to Jewish
voters by further distancing himself from Palestine Liberation
Organization leader Yasser Arafat as the candidates enter the final
week of campaigning before the delegate-rich New York primary.
   When asked Monday about meeting with Arafat, Jackson said: ``It
would not be a good approach to start at the table with the most
extreme elements _ that's a formula for catastrophe.''
   Rather, the Democratic presidential contender said, ``In this
city some of your top Palestinian leaders in the world live. Some
of your top Jewish-American and pro-Israeli leaders live. We should
begin to talk here, to implore both sides to a higher level of
security.''
   Jackson's remarks caused some Arab-American supporters to
chastise him Monday, while others rallied to his defense.
   On Sunday, Jackson said that, if elected president, he would not
meet again with Arafat. Jackson has been widely criticized for
meeting with Arafat in 1979.
   Abdeen Jabara, president of the American-Arab
Anti-Discrimination Committee, accused Jackson of abandoning his
principles in his quest for the presidency.
   But James Zogby, executive director of the Arab-American
Institute, said Jackson has a nine-year record of commitment to
Palestinian rights and to justice for both Israelis and
Palestinians.
   Nearly one quarter of the Democrats expected to vote in New
York's April 19 primary are Jewish, and for many of them, the
future of Israel is a critical issue.
   While in New York, Jackson also continued his appeal to
blue-collar voters. Some union leaders called Jackson ``one of us''
at a labor rally on his behalf.
   ``He's the only candidate who will get on the picket line and
walk with the workers,'' said Karen Lantz, vice president of the
Independent Federation of Flight Attendants, after Jackson
addressed a crowd of 5,000 labor leaders and union members Monday
night.
   Lantz, who characterized Jackson as ``one of us,'' said the
other candidates may support labor, but ``you never see them.''
   Jackson told the overflow crowd at the Jacob K. Javits
Convention Center that blue-collar workers ``will have a friend in
the White House'' if he becomes president.
   Jackson reminded the crowd that he has stood with them numerous
times on picket lines, and asked them to stand with him now by
supporting his candidacy.
   Jackson also campaigned north of the city Monday, addressing a
rally at Rockland Community College and greeting workers at a
General Motors plant in North Tarrytown.
   At the GM plant and the labor rally, he sounded his familiar
theme of battling economic violence and told the workers: ``We
built our campaign at the plant gate.''
   Jackson is only a handful of delegates behind Gov. Michael
Dukakis of Massachusetts in the Democratic race. Tennessee Sen.
Albert Gore Jr. is running third.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
