<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ElectionsRdp     04-12 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Elections Rdp,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sonny Bono Headlines Elections in California, Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sonny Bono, whose ex-wife Cher won best actress at the Oscars,
vied for best candidate in a mayoral race with six opponents today
in Palm Springs, Calif., one of several elections in Texas and
California.
   In Texas, Rep. Beau Boulter of Amarillo opposed Houston
businessman Wes Gilbreath in a primary runoff for the Republican
nomination to challenge Democratic Sen. Lloyd Bentsen.
   In San Francisco, eight candidates were running in a special
election to fill the state Assembly seat vacated by Mayor Art
Agnos. The top contenders were former U.S. Rep. John Burton, 55,
and fellow liberal Democrat Roberta Achtenberg, 37, a lesbian
rights lawyer whose election would make her the legislature's first
openly gay member.
   Bono, a 53-year-old entertainer and restaurateur, built a
recording career with Cher during more than the two decades, and
was the butt of her jokes during their TV variety show. Cher won
the best actress at Monday night's Oscar ceremonies for her
performance in the movie ``Moonstruck.''
   Bono said he has campaigned hard to convince voters his
candidacy for the part-time, $15,000-a-year mayor's job was no
publicity stunt. ``They thought it was a joke,'' he said recently.
``Now they take me seriously.''
   Also running were Vice Mayor Eli Birer, businesswoman Deyna
Hodges, accountant Lloyd Maryanov, Agua Caliente Indian Tribe
Secretary Ray Patencio, real estate agent Neil Beatty and retired
dentist Lewis Friedman.
   The Texas runoff was required because no candidate received a
majority in the March 8, four-way GOP primary.
   Gilbreath, who has spent about $1 million of his own money in
the race, was the top candidate with 37 percent of the vote.
Boulter, who received 30 percent, later picked up endorsements from
the third- and fourth-place finishers as well as the majority of
Texas Republican leaders.
   Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y., campaigned Monday for Boulter in several
Texas cities. Boulter, a 46-year-old two-term congressman, backed
Kemp's failed bid for the GOP presidential nomination.
   The presidential race and Gilbreath's money were the campaign's
main issues. Gilbreath, a 59-year-old first-time office seeker,
said Boulter's support of Kemp would hurt Texas if Vice President
George Bush becomes president.
   Boulter said Gilbreath supported former television evangelist
Pat Robertson's unsuccessful bid for the GOP presidential
nomination. Gilbreath has declined to say he voted for in Texas'
Republican presidential primary.
   The Boulter campaign, which spent about $250,000, complained
about Gilbreath's deep pockets.
   Bentsen, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, breezed to
renomination in March over a little-known San Antonio professor.
The incumbent has said he does not care which Republican he faces
in his November bid for a fourth term.
   In San Francisco, Achtenberg, 37, campaigned Monday at transit
stations and a senior citizens' home.
   ``We are extremely optimistic,'' she said. ``It all depends on
the voter turnout. Our polls indicate it's a dead heat.''
   Burton visited churches in the district on Sunday, reminding
parishioners of his civil rights voting record and that of his late
brother, Phillip, and late sister-in-law, Sala, who also
represented the city in Congress.
   Burton, who held the Assembly seat between 1965 and 1975, was
sidelined from politics in 1983 by a cocaine addiction.
   The other candidates were Republicans Max Woods and Brian
Mavrogeorge, Libertarian George Meyer, Peace and Freedom candidate
Melissa Ehman, and independents Hope Joles and James Schmitt.
   The district is overwhelmingly Democratic, and candidates from
other parties were given little chance of mounting serious
opposition.
   If no candidate wins a majority, the top two vote-getters will
face each other in a runoff June 7.
   Agnos' two-year term ends this year, and the Democratic primary
for the seat also will be held June 7.
</TEXT>
