<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Oscars-Backstage     04-12 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oscars-Backstage,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Celebrity Backstage Soirees Offer Some Intimate Tidbits</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Oscars, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cher celebrated by exclaiming ``Anybody can
do anything,'' Sean Connery knocked back a few drinks and Olympia
Dukakis telephoned her presidential candidate cousin in New York
with the good news.
   These were some of the highlights of chit-chat backstage Monday
night, as Oscar winners and presenters shuttled into a huge white
tent erected behind the Shrine Auditorium where the 60th-annual
Academy Awards presentations were made.
   With an estimated billion people watching the show on
television, the parking lot big top was teeming with hundreds of
reporters brimming with questions at an ongoing news conference
during the ceremony.
   How does it feel? What does it mean? What are you going to do
with the statuette? Gabriella Cristiani, winner of the editing
Oscar for ``The Last Emperor,'' was most succinct: ``I'm just
happy. I don't know what it means.''
   But most winners of behind-the-scenes Oscars _ those for
editing, costumes and the like _ were ignored by reporters. One of
the co-winners of the visual effects award stood at a microphone
and, questionless, began singing ``Moon River.''
   An ambulance took an unconscious actress to a hospital after she
collapsed near the lobby in 90-degree heat before the show began,
touching off whirlwind of backstage rumor and questioning. It was
finally determined Anita Page, the 77-year-old star of ``Broadway
Melody,'' fainted and was all right.
   Reporters from the Village Voice, Daily Variety, the Hollywood
Reporter, USA Today and columnists Roger Ebert and Marilyn Beck
blurted out questions then scribbled answers on note pads and
punched quotes into portable computers.
   At the same time, they listened to acceptance speeches on
earphones feeding them audio from the inside the Shrine. Two giant
television screens were the reporters' link to the show. The media
is not allowed inside the auditorium.
   Cher, who won as best actress for ``Moonstruck,'' and Miss
Dukakis, the best supporting actress for the same movie, both
revealed they were rooting for political candidates. Miss Dukakis
boosted the presidential aspirations of her cousin, Massachusetts
Gov. Michael Dukakis, and Cher put in a good word for ex-husband
Sonny Bono's bid today as Palm Springs mayor.
   ``OK Michael, let's go!'' said Miss Dukakis during the ceremony;
Cher said she wasn't sure if Bono would win, but said: ``I hope
so.''
   Miss Dukakis excused herself, saying her cousin was waiting for
her call in an Italian restaurant in New York City, where he is
campaigning in the state's Democratic primary. ``It's the year of
the Dukaki,'' she said.
   Sipping on a glass of wine, Sean Connery stepped before the
backstage microphone and declared his award for best supporting
actor was ``an accumulation of the body of his work.''
   ``I'm going to have a few drinks,'' he said when asked how he
would celebrate.
   A footsore Cher carried her black high heels in one hand and her
Oscar in the other, apologizing to reporters for her aching feet.
But the topic of conversation focused on her see-through Bob Mackie
gown.
   ``I don't think it's too far,'' Cher said, looking down at the
sparse coverage that left little to the imagination. ``Everything's
covered. I don't think you can see anything. There's not much to
see anyway.''
   Her son Elijah Blue Allman was promised the Oscar statuette for
the night and from there it will spend an extended period on her
bedroom fireplace.
   ``If I can win this statue, I think anybody can do anything,''
Cher said.
   The 5-week-old Writers Guild of America strike was an occasional
topic of backstage conversation.
   Best-actor winner Michael Douglas said he was taking the summer
off because his next project couldn't proceed without the writers,
but presenter Billy Crystal, a union writer and performer, was
unfazed.
   ``It didn't really affect me. We were doing old material, that's
why there's nothing topical,'' said Crystal.
   ``My entire monologue was generously donated by five
Teamsters,'' quipped show host Chevy Chase. ``There may be a
writer's strike, but there isn't a readers strike.''
</TEXT>
