<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BloodTest     04-12 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Blood Test,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearing Begins Into Blood Test Not Allowed in Criminal Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A type of blood test barred as evidence in
Michigan criminal trials is on trial itself this week, as
supporters seek to overturn the state Supreme Court's 1986 ruling
declaring it inadmissible.
   Prosecutors from Wayne and Kent counties claim electrophoresis
has been refined since the high court's decision. Attorneys
representing two defendants against whom test results could be
applied deny the prosecutors' claims.
   The Supreme Court's 1986 ruling came on a 3-2 decision with two
justices not taking part. Since then, one of the justices in the
majority _ former Chief Justice G. Mennen Williams _ has died and
has been replaced by Robert Griffin.
   In an unusual arrangement, Circuit Judges Robert Benson of Kent
County and Maureen Reilly of Wayne County began taking testimony
Monday in a joint evidentiary hearing. Assistant prosecutors Mark
Vander Molen of Kent County and Paul Bruno of Wayne County are
seeking decisions from the judges allowing use of electrophoresis
tests as evidence in stabbing cases they are handling.
   Vander Molen is prosecuting a case against Robert Tanner, 26,
charged with two counts of assault with intent to murder. Bruno is
prosecuting Scott Stoughton, 21, charged with two counts of
first-degree murder in the deaths of two people in Taylor.
   ``We think the (Supreme Court) decision was a mistake and we
hope to correct it,'' Vander Molen said before Monday's hearing
began.
   But Bernard Schaefer, Tanner's attorney, said he doesn't think
the test has been accepted generally by scientists for use in
criminal trials.
   ``I think the prosecution and the prosecution community want to
change the ruling,'' he said. ``There's been a change in the
(Supreme) court. ... It's not that there has been a scientific
advancement.''
   Electrophoresis is a process to separate molecules of a
substance by their electrical charge. It has been used in genetic
testing, identification of certain enzymes in a variety of organs
and in analysis of DNA, which carries genetic characteristics.
   The hearing is expected to last a week and should involve
detailed scientific testimony about proteins, enzymes and
``markers'' they leave in dried blood.
   Vander Molen said use of the test in his case against Tanner is
not critical. But, he said: ``We've got nearly 10 cases in which we
need this test. This kind of evidence is important in the most
serious of cases.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
