<DOCNO> AP880412-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0513EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PainConference     04-12 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pain Conference,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researchers Gather for Pain Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Describing an ache may be easy to the sufferer,
but to pain researchers the feeling of hurt is complex almost
beyond description.
   Researchers at a four-day international ``Pain Measurement''
conference that began Monday are trying to develop a unified theory
for the study of pain. The conference is sponsored by the
University of Washington and funded by a grant from the National
Institutes of Health.
   One in three people in America suffers from chronic pain and
millions are routinely incapacitated by it, but medical science
often can do little to to prevent or effectively treat recurrent
pain, because patients are suffering from something that can't be
seen, felt or observed by someone else.
   The subjective and intangible nature of pain frustrates many
people involved in its research.
   ``The problem with the meaning of the word pain has been around
since Aristotle,'' said Dr. John D. Loeser, a neurosurgeon and
director of the university's Multidisciplinary Pain Center.
   ``How do you go about measuring pain?'' Loeser asks. ``We're not
very far along in the clinical setting. It's too complex a
phenomenon.''
   Only within about the last two decades has the problem of pain
gained serious attention in medical research, in large part because
of the pioneering efforts of Dr. John Bonica, chairman emeritus of
the school's department of anesthesiology. Bonica's work on the
management of pain, which emphasizes a comprehensive approach
rather than hit-and-miss drug therapies, paved the way for the
serious study of pain.
   ``Everybody measures pain in a different way,'' said C. Richard
Chapman, a psychopharmacologist in pain research at the university
and the independent Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center.
   ``We don't at present have a theory, a single theory, that
everyone agrees upon,'' said Chapman.
   Pain measurement research generally relies on laboratory tests
of animals, lab tests on humans or studies of patient care, each
with its own accepted methods for measuring and defining pain. None
completely translates into an acceptable method for the other.
   Chapman said pain often is taken seriously by medical
professionals only when tissue damage can be identified, although a
lot of chronic pain apparently exists without any identifiable
tissue damage.
   Some researchers try to measure this kind of pain by analyzing
behavior or looking at brain waves and other electrical signals.
   Those dealing with humans ask the sufferer to describe the hurt,
``but how can you tell if an infant, who can't yet speak, is
experiencing pain?'' asked Loeser.
   University of Washington researchers expect a good deal of
argument and contention at the conference. In fact, they
deliberately scheduled scientists with opposing views to speak in
succession. About 60 researchers are expected to attend.
   ``It's my belief that we can bring this all together if we can
find a uniform theory for pain,'' said Chapman. ``When we have
reached it, our power to solve the perplexities of pain
scientifically and to control the human and animal suffering that
it causes will be greatly increased.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880412-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0513EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Markets     04-12 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tokyo Market Hits Record High Closing; Dollar Edges Upward</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tokyo's key stock market indicator closed today at
an all-time high and the U.S. dollar climbed in trading against the
Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
175.98 points Monday, added another 5.97 points, or 0.02 percent,
to close at 26,930.84.
   On Monday, the stock market's key barometer briefly touched a
new high of 26,998.36 points during the morning trading, but then
fell back.
   Boosted by the steady dollar and a strong Monday showing on Wall
Street, the Nikkei index soared again today to 26,976.21 points
minutes after the start of trading.
   Then profit-taking set in, indicating ``the market was rising
too high (and) eased share prices a little in the afternoon,'' said
Tadaaki Uehara of Wako Securities.
   However, the index rose again in the market's last hour, led by
blue chip electricals, Uehara said. Many investors were encouraged
by the dollar's stability and felt the electricals would continue
to benefit from the stable dollar, traders said.
   Other popular issues included precision machineries, drugs and
constructions. Losers included chemicals, securities and real
estates.
   Volume on the first section trade was estimated at a moderate
750 million shares, down from 900 million shares Monday.
   On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, meanwhile, the dollar
closed at 126.50 yen, up 0.79 yen from its close Monday of 125.71
yen and up also from its opening today of 126.40 yen.
   ``It appears the dollar has stabilized at what it should be,''
said a foreign exchange dealer at a major commercial bank, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   Trading was mixed in dollar-buying and selling, with a strong
wait-and-see attitude among participants regarding this week's
meeting in Washington of monetary authorities from seven major
economic nations, he said.
   The bank dealer said Japan's shrinking trade deficit contributed
to the dollar-buying.
   Japan's trade surplus in fiscal 1987 declined 15.3 percent from
the previous year, the first such drop in six years, shrinking from
$89.736 billion in 1986 to $76.015 billion last year, according to
the Finance Ministry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880412-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0521EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Haganah-Clemency     04-12 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Haganah-Clemency,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Murderer Flies To Israel To Finish Murder Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted murderer has flown to Israel after
renouncing his citizenship under a special clemency agreement that
allowed him to finish his prison term working on a kibbutz.
   William Shapiro, 62, had served 13 years of a life term that
carried a minimum 25-year sentence when he boarded an El Al jet
Monday night.
   A notary public witnessed his renunciation after a federal judge
said it did not fall under his authority.
   ``I have researched the law thoroughly, but I have found nothing
in any federal law which gives me jurisdiction to accept such
renunciation,'' Judge Eugene P. Spellman told Shapiro and defense
attorney Jan Jacobowitz before calling a notary public to the
courtroom.
   Shapiro was granted clemency under an agreement between the
state Board of Executive Clemency, made up of Gov. Bob Martinez and
his Cabinet, and the Israeli government because of Shapiro's past
ties to Israel's old Haganah, a secret military force that helped
win Israeli independence in 1948.
   Shapiro, a Miami businessman born in New York, was accused of
hiring two men to kill a business partner. A Dade County circuit
jury convicted him in February 1976 of first-degree murder and
conspiracy to commit murder for the pipe-beating death of Burt
deWitt.
   But Shapiro's supporters have long pointed to his Haganah
background, his World War II and Korean War service as a Marine
combat officer and his 12 years with Israel's police to support
their claim that he couldn't have been been guilty.
   Elements of the Haganah, with about 10,000 members by the
mid-1930s, served with the British in defense of the Middle East
during World War II. After Israel gained independence in 1948, the
Haganah became the core of Israel's army.
   Shapiro's legal file shows he didn't participate directly in the
pipe-beating.
   ``The evidence just wasn't very strong against Shapiro,'' said
attorney Alvin Lodish, who was asked to handle the case by Israel's
consul general in Miami, Rahamin Timor. ``It is highly unusual to
have someone convicted of first-degree murder on evidence like
that.''
   Clemency was granted last month. Under the deal, Shapiro had to
renounce his U.S. citizenship and relocate at Kibbutz
Ayelet-Hashar, where he will work at least eight hours a day, six
days a week.
   Herut Lapid, director of the United Kibbutz Movement of which
the collective farm is a member, assured Florida officials in a
letter that a rehabilitation plan has been worked out for Shapiro.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
