<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880412-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0554EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Profiles     04-12 0816</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Profiles,0850</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>With PM-China-Congress
^By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are brief sketches of some of the new
members of China's Cabinet appointed today by the National People's
Congress.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Qin Jiwei</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Qin, a veteran general and protege of senior leader Deng
Xiaoping, is expected to increase the ministry's role in making
military decisions, long handled by the party.
   Qin, 74, commander of the Beijing Military Region, is a veteran
of the 1934-35 Long March, the Communist forces' epic retreat
during the Chinese civil war. In 1946-49 he served as an army
officer under Deng's command and later commanded troops in the
Korean War.
   He replaces the ailing Zhang Aiping, 80. Real power in the
military, however, long has resided in the Communist Party's
Central Military Commission, headed by Deng.
   The Defense Ministry has been deliberately kept weak since 1971,
when then-Defense Minister Lin Biao allegedly plotted a coup
against Mao Tse-tung. Western military analysts believe the
leadership plans to reduce the party's military role to setting
overall policy and strengthen the Defense Ministry as part of its
efforts to make the military more professional and modern.
   Qin was born in 1914 in central China's Hubei province, and
joined the party in 1930. He was purged during the far-leftist
Cultural Revolution that began in 1966, and was rehabilitated in
1973.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Foreign Minister Qian Qichen</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Qian, 60, is a career diplomat who has headed China's border
talks with the Soviet Union and had been vice foreign minister
since 1982. He succeeds Wu Xueqian, who was promoted to vice
premier.
   Qian, who speaks English and Russian, studied in Moscow from
1954 to 1955 and was second secretary and counselor at the Chinese
Embassy in Moscow in the 1960s. He spent a total of 10 years in the
Soviet Union from 1954 to 1974, according to his official biography.
   In 1974, he became ambassador to Guinea and Guinea-Bissau in
northwest Africa. He returned to Beijing to become head of the
Foreign Ministry's Information Department.
   When China began talks with the Soviet Union in 1982 over their
disputed border, Qian was appointed to head negotiations. After 11
rounds, neither side has reported significant progress.
   Qian was born in the northeast industrial city of Tianjin in
1928 and joined the Communist Party in 1942. He worked for the
party's underground while reporting for the Ta Kung Pao newspaper
in Shanghai during the 1040s.
   He is a member of the party's policy-making Central Committee.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>People's Bank of China Governor Li Guixian</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Li, a provincial party leader with little experience in finance,
was the surprise choice to fill the difficult post of governor of
the People's Bank of China, the country's central bank.
   The 50-year-old Li, a Soviet-trained engineer who since 1986 has
been party secretary in Anhui Province, also became one of nine
state councilors named by the National People's Congress.
   He succeeds Chen Muhua, 67, one of China's most visible and
powerful women politicians, who had held the post for three years.
Chen was elected vice chairwoman of the National People's Congress,
China's legislature.
   Li takes over the bank at a critical stage as it tries to change
from exercising administrative control over the banking system to
adopting indirect controls through interest rates and credit.
   It also is promoting interbank markets, making greater use of
bonds and foreign credit to finance China's development and trying
to rein in excessive growth in money supply.
   Li, a native of Liaoning province, spent about five years in the
Soviet Union beginning in 1960 studying electric vacuum chemistry.
   After returning to China, he worked in the Ministry of Public
Security and between 1967 and 1976 was a technician, deputy
director and chief engineer of a large factory.
   He later was chief engineer of the Liaoning Provincial
Electronics Industry Bureau, deputy governor of Liaoning, and in
1985 became party secretary of the northeastern province.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Railways Minister Li Senmao</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Li faces the daunting task of resolving problems of aging
equipment and sloppy discipline that have contributed to four fatal
train accidents this year.
   Li, 58, became vice minister of the Railways Ministry in 1982
and has been acting foreign minister since early March. It is his
first Cabinet post.
   Ding Guangen, Li's predecessor, resigned in disgrace to take
responsibility for three train accidents in January, which killed a
total of 141 people.
   A few weeks later, 28 people were killed in the fourth accident,
the collision of two passenger trains in Shanghai.
   Investigations revealed deep-seated problems in the Railways
Ministry's administration, including the lack of a safety control
system, serious overloading of trains, outdated equipment, loose
discipline, poor worker training and frequent thefts of railway
materials.
   Li was a member of the Communist Party's 12th Central Committee
but was downgraded last October to an alternate membership in the
policy-making body when it was reduced from 210 members to 175.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
