<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Little Changed, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was little changed against most major
foreign currencies in light European trading early today. Gold
prices rose.
   Dealers said they expected the dollar to trade within a narrow
range before Wednesday's meeting of finance ministers from the
seven major industrialized democracies and the release of U.S.
trade figures for February on Thursday.
   Few traders predicted any sharp improvement in the merchandise
trade deficit from January's shortfall of $12.44 billion.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose to a closing 126.50 Japanese yen from
125.71 yen at Monday's close. Later, in London, it edged up to
126.53 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.6853 West German marks, down from 1.6855
   _1.3957 Swiss francs, up from 1.3953
   _5.7180 French francs, up from 5.7145
   _1.8897 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8910
   _1,249.75 Italian lire, up from 1,249.50
   _1.2390 Canadian dollars, unchanged
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.848 from $1.856 late
Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $450.50 a troy ounce, up
from $449.50 bid late Monday. At mid-morning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $450.20.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $450.20, up from $449.00 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose to a closing bid of $452.21
from $451.95 at Monday's close.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $6.44 a troy
ounce, up from a $6.42 bid late Monday.
</TEXT>
