<HEAD>Texas Hit by Spring Freeze, Strong Winds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A bitter spring chill accompanied by gale-force winds swept over
south Texas this morning, prompting a warning to Texans that they
protect pets, plants and pipes.
   Rain and thunderstorms extended from Mississippi to Alabama,
northern Georgia and South Carolina. In Mobile, Ala., sleet mixed
with rain.
   Skies were generally cloudy from southern New England to the
central Appalachians and were fair over much of the rest of the
nation.
   In south Texas, the chill prompted a freeze warning for the Hill
Country. It was an unseasonably low 39 degrees in San Antonio.
   Gale warnings remained in effect along Texas' upper Gulf Coast,
but the winds were expected to diminish.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
Carolinas to northeast Florida, Tennessee, eastern Kentucky,
southern West Virginia and southwest Virginia; clouds over the
central Atlantic Coast and the central Gulf Coast states and sunny
skies over the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures were expected to reach the 40s and 50s from New
England to New Jersey, the northern Appalachians and the Great
Lakes; low 80s over southern Texas; 80s and 90s from southwest
Texas to the desert Southwest, and much of California and 60s and
70s in the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 23
degrees at Houlton, Maine, to 74 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 42 cloudy; Boston 39 cloudy; Buffalo 40 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 60 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 45 partly cloudy;
Cleveland 40 fair; Detroit 40 fair; Miami 66 partly cloudy; New
York 45 cloudy; Philadelphia 42 cloudy; Pittsburgh 46 fair;
Portland, Maine 34 cloudy; Washington 44 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 51 fair; Chicago 44 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
49 fair; Denver 45 fair; Des Moines 42 fair; Indianapolis 46 fair;
Kansas City 43 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 39 fair; Nashville 51
partly cloudy; New Orleans 50 windy; St. Louis 48 fair.
