<DOCNO> AP880412-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0641EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PolygamistTrial     04-12 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polygamist Trial,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Testimony Begins Today In Polygamist Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Trial scheduled to start at 11:30 a.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mostly Mormon jury will sit in judgment
of four members of a renegade polygamist clan charged in the
bombing of a Mormon chapel and the subsequent 13-day standoff with
police.
   Federal prosecutors plan to call at least 150 witnesses,
including a Mormon bishop, neighbors of the defendants and
reporters, in the high-profile case beginning today.
   Defense lawyers, however, aren't sure it can be judged fairly.
   Attorney Fred Metos, asked if the 12 jurors seated Friday, truly
were the defendants' peers, responded, ``They have no peers.''
   A Utah correction officer was killed in an exchange of gunfire
at the end of the siege. The Utah attorney general's office plans
to file homicide charges as soon as the federal trial ends, said
Associate Attorney General Paul Warner.
   The trial will be one of the most closely followed in recent
memory in a state with an estimated 30,000 members of polygamist
families. Most coexist peacefully with their Mormon neighbors, who
make up nearly 70 percent of Utah's population.
   The Mormon Church renounced polygamy in 1890 and now
excommunicates advocates and practitioners of multiple-wife
marriages.
   The four defendants include Vickie Singer, 44, mother of seven
and widow of slain polygamist John Singer, who was gunned down in
1979 by police serving a contempt citation at the same farm where
his family held authorities at bay while awaiting the dead
patriarch's resurrection.
   Law enforcement officers believe Mrs. Singer was the brains
behind the bombing and standoff, while her son-in-law, Addam Swapp,
provided the muscle.
   According to Mrs. Singer's diary, submitted as evidence during
pretrial hearings, Swapp and two others planted the bomb at the
Kamas Stake Center in Marion on Jan. 16 as the Singer women prayed
at the family home two miles away.
   Swapp, 27, and Mrs. Singer are charged with seven and eight
counts, respectively, in a nine-count indictment that was handed up
shortly after their arrests. It was reduced last week to eight
counts when U.S. District Judge Bruce S. Jenkins dismissed a
conspiracy charge.
   Charged with four counts each are Jonathan Swapp, 21, Addam
Swapp's brother, and John Timothy Singer, Mrs. Singer's 21-year-old
wheelchair-bound son. Singer is state authorities' prime suspect in
the slaying of the corrections officer.
   All four defendants are charged with the attempted killing of
FBI agents during the standoff, assault on federal officers and two
firearms violations.
   Mrs. Singer and Swapp are charged additionally with using an
explosive to damage the chapel, use of a bomb and possession of a
bomb. Mrs. Singer also faces one count of possession of a sawed-off
shotgun.
   In telephone calls to news organizations shortly after the
bombing, Mrs. Singer and Swapp said the blast was symbolic of the
``collapse of the church, state and nation'' that would occur with
the second coming of Christ and the return of John Singer.
   Clan members contend Singer's death was the result of a
``government-church conspiracy'' and a ``long train of abuse''
against the family.
   Addam Swapp's attorneys asked that the trial be moved out of
state, arguing their client could not receive a fair hearing in
Mormon-dominated Utah.
   While Jenkins has not ruled on the motion, John Bucher, an
attorney for Swapp, said Monday the case probably would not be
transferred once the trial begins.
   Bucher and Metos, representing John Timothy Singer, said the
pool of 170 prospective jurors that reported for possible court
duty last week was 90 percent Mormon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880412-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0647EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hijack-Thailand     04-12 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hijack-Thailand,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thais Deny Weapons Smuggled On Hijacked Plane In Bangkok</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investigator today ruled out the
possibility that the hijackers of a Kuwaiti airliner smuggled their
weapons on board the plane in Bangkok through a ramp area used by
service personnel.
   The possibility was raised on Monday by Rodney Wallis, head of
security for the Montreal-based International Air Transport
Association.
   The Kuwaiti jet was carrying 112 people when it was hijacked
April 5 on a flight from Bangkok to Kuwait and forced down in Iran.
   The hijackers, who are armed with grenades and handguns, later
forced the plane to Larnaca, Cyprus, where they have killed two of
the approximately 50 passengers they are still holding hostage.
   ``It is not possible,'' Group Capt. Anake Udit said today when
asked about Wallis' theory. Anake, a deputy managing director of
the Airports Authority of Thailand, is a member of a team
investigating what happened during the 15 hours the Kuwait Airways
jumbo jet was on the ground in Bangkok.
   ``Anyone going through the ramp area had to go through tough
security clearance,'' Anake said in a telephone interview. ``That
is not easy.''
   On Monday, Wallis said: ``On the basis of discussions we've had
so far, the probability is that weapons were placed on board the
aircraft through the coercion or collusion of staff on the ramp.''
   The International Air Transport Association is an international
association of commercial airlines.
   Anake said Kuwait Airways hires guards from the airport
authority and from a private security firm to guard its planes
while in Bangkok. ``The security men do not take their eyes off the
plane once it landed,'' he said.
   Anake said the airport authority has not discussed the origin of
the weapons with the Air Transport Association. ``We expected
suppositions like this and we're saying (the weapons) didn't come
from here.''
   Thai investigators have theorized that the weapons were smuggled
aboard before the plane reached Bangkok on April 4 from Kuwait.
They said the hijackers may have left the weapons on board during
the stop.
   On the possible coercion or collusion of staff on the ramp,
Anake said: ``It was more likely they (the hijackers) used their
own people.''
   He said airport authority investigators were questioning about
100 people, including guards of the private security company and
airport authority personnel, including cleaners, mechanics,
engineers and employees of the Bangkok Airport Fuel Service.
   Anake said he could not say when the probe would be completed.
   A separate investigation team is headed by Interior Minister
Prachuab Suntrangkoon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
