<2ND_LINE>PM-Explosion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0551,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Explosions, Fire Force Evacuations In Texas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New with employees released from hospital, owner on cause, no
pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GODLEY, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A series of explosions and a fire at an oil
field supply manufacturing plant early today forced the evacuations
of nearby residents, authorities said.
   Two plant employees suffered minor injuries, and were treated
and released at a Fort Worth hospital.
   The explosion was at the Owens Tool Co., located between Godley
and Cresson, about 25 miles southwest of Fort Worth.
   Authorities said they ordered the evacuations of about 30 people
from a square mile of the mostly rural area around the plant
because they believed 20,000 to 30,000 pounds of explosives were
stored in the area.
   Dean Owens, the plant's owner, said a charge being manufactured
for use in oil drilling operations exploded, triggering other
explosions and a fire. The plant was destroyed, he said.
   Firefighters from several surrounding towns, and volunteers
battled the blaze, but were pulled back at times because of fears
of possible additional explosions.
   The evacuees were taken to the Godley Fire Department, where
they were told to wait until it was safe to return home.
</TEXT>
