<DOCNO> AP880412-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0906EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugTrafficking     04-12 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Trafficking,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reputed Drug Lord Held Without Bail; Another Indicted by Federal
Grand Jury</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reputed Mexican drug king was ordered held
without bail on a 1980 narcotics indictment, while an indictment
charging another alleged trafficker with heading a worldwide drug
cartel was unsealed.
   Jose Contreras Subias appeared before U.S. Magistrate Joseph
Reichmann on Monday on an 8-year-old indictment for allegedly
selling cocaine to undercover narcotics agents.
   Contreras Subias, who had been a fugitive since escaping from a
Mexican jail in 1985, was captured April 1 in Salt Lake City.
   Authorities believe Contreras Subias was the right-hand man to
alleged Mexican drug lord Rafael Caro Quintero, jailed in Mexico on
charges of murdering U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration agent
Enrique Camarena in 1985.
   Also Monday, Juan Ramon Matta Ballesteros, 42, who authorities
say ordered Camarena's murder, was named in a 14-count indictment
charging him with heading an organization that brought Colombian
cocaine into the United States via Mexico between May 1983 and June
1985.
   Matta Ballesteros was arrested by U.S marshals last week after
he was expelled from his native Honduras. The expulsion led to
student riots in Honduras that included setting fire to a U.S.
embassy annex there.
   Contreras Subias told Reichmann Monday that federal authorities
have the wrong man. He claimed he is actually Jose Gonzalez
Guillen, but prosecutors presented evidence that his fingerprints
matched those taken during a 1985 arrest in Los Angeles.
   He was scheduled to be arraigned in Los Angeles on Monday,
prosecutors said.
   Nine people have been indicted in the Camarena slaying, and
three are in custody, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Jimmy Gurule.
Matta Ballesteros is considered one of four prime suspects, said
DEA chief John Lawn.
   According to the indictment, Matta Ballesteros shipped thousands
of pounds of South American cocaine to Mexico. The narcotics were
then flown to a remote air strip in Young, Ariz., and moved in
recreational vehicles to several ``safe houses'' in the Los Angeles
area, the indictment said.
   The drug ring owned four airplanes, rented homes in New York
City and Southern California and set up several corporations, the
indictment charged.
   The indictment also accused Matta Ballesteros of conspiracy,
possession of cocaine with intent to distribute and running a
continuing criminal enterprise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
