<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Nixon     04-12 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nixon,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nixon Says Shultz's Efforts Will Go for Nought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Richard M. Nixon said today
that only secret and prolonged negotiations can bring about a
change in U.S. relations with Israel and that George Shultz's
efforts will go for nought in an election year.
   ``You have to recongize that we can do nothing about those
relations in an election year,'' said Nixon. Israel, too, is
holding elections in 1988.
   In the secnd of three consecutive daily appearances on NBC's
``Today'' program, Nixon suggested that the United States use a
heavyweight negotiator, whom he did not name today. But on Sunday,
on NBC's ``Meet the Press'', he suggested Henry Kissinger for that
role.
   The former president, who is making public appearances to
promote a new book, ``1999,'' also touched on these subjects:
   _ On others' global responsibility: ``Unless the Europeans do
more in their own defense ... you are going to find the Congress is
going to reduce the American presence without getting anything for
it from the Russians.''
   _ On the next president: He ``is going to be urged, the moment
he gets in, to go running over to Moscow or have them come here. It
would be the greatest mistake he can make.'' Nixon suggested the
first summit meeting should be without glamour or spouses and
``should go on for at least two weeks and we should develop a
common strategy.''
   _ On China: ``China's first priority is progress at home.
They've given up on expansion and aggression abroad ... (Mikhail)
Gorbachev has to choose. If he can get progress at home and give
away aggression abroad, we can have the same relations with him
that we do with the Chinese.''
   Nixon said he gives Secretary of State Shultz high marks for his
shuttle diplomacy in the Middle East in recent weeks. ``But there
isn't enough time to do it this year and it cannot be done in an
election year. I don't want to say it's going to fail, because he's
going to continue to try, but I say that 1989 is the optimum year
to do it in.''
   The Israelis, said Nixon, should make their deal now ``because
they are going to find that time is not on the side of the
Israelis.''
   Asked what he thinks might restrain the sometimes brutal
behavior toward Arabs in the West Bank and Gaza, Nixon said:
   ``They must not ignore the problem. They must not be blind to
the fact that there are a million and a half Palestinians there who
don't have the right of self-government. And that's a time bomb
that's going to explode. They have to deal with that or they are
going to have great problems in the future.''
</TEXT>
