<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--EnglishTalmud     04-12 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--English Talmud,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>English Talmud Planned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Random House is planning to publish a modern
English translation of the Talmud that it hopes will make the
1,500-year-old collection of Jewish law, legend and philosophy more
accessible to laymen.
   The translator is Adin Steinsaltz, an Orthodox rabbi and noted
Talmud scholar. The project will be published in stages, with the
first three volumes expected by 1990.
   Steinsaltz, of the Israel Institute for Talmudic Publications in
Jerusalem, said the effort may entail as many as 15 volumes and
take 10 years to complete.
   Peter Osnos, the Random House associate publisher who will edit
the project, said the volumes will probably cost $30 to $40 each.
   ``We have now possibly a major part of the Jewish people whose
native tongue is English,'' Steinsaltz said, ``and who really are
not comfortable in any other language.''
   The translation will be of the Babylonian Talmud, compiled in
the sixth century after Christ and considered more authoritative
than the shorter Jerusalem (or Palestinian) Talmud.
   The University of Chicago Press has published 22 of a projected
36 volumes of the Jerusalem Talmud in English.
</TEXT>
