<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0934EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-GlobalForum     04-12 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Global Forum,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dalai Lama Says Tibetans In Constant Fear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dalai Lama, the self-exiled leader of
the Tibetan people, said today that Tibetans remain in constant
fear of the Chinese government which rules their homeland.
   However, he said, he is increasingly hopeful that a solution to
the Tibetan problem can be found.
   ``Many things are changing _ particularly in China _ things are
changing for the better, and generally speaking things are becoming
more humanized. That is a positive and hopeful sign,'' the Dalai
Lama told the Global Forum of Spiritual and Parliamentary Leaders
on Human Survival, a gathering to discuss the planet's problems.
   The Dalai Lama is the spiritual and temporal leader of the
Tibetan people. He fled Tibet in 1959 after an aborted uprising
against Chinese rule.
   China claims that Tibet has been part of China for at least the
past 700 years. Many Tibetans claim that Tibet is an independent
state.
   Following a British stipulation, the Dalai Lama's 30-minute
speech eschewed politics, but when the 52-year-old Tibetan sat
down, a questioner asked whether the 200 conference participants
could help in any way to ``stop the suffering'' and restore Tibet's
religious and cultural freedom.
   The Dalai Lama thanked the questioner and said he was continuing
negotiations with China.
   China boycotted the conference in Oxford because of the Dalai
Lama's presence. In a letter to the Times of London, published
Tuesday, Chinese Ambassador Ji Chaozhu defended his country's rule
of Tibet.
   The letter welcomed the Dalai Lama's ``intention to continue
such contacts. Our only condition is that he does not demand
`independence' for Tibet, which we would never accept.''
   The unique gathering of 200 personalities from more than 60
countries is trying to find ways of using their influence with
national decision makers to tackle international issues like
nuclear war, population control, violence, pollution and
conservation.
   In the first keynote speech at the opening ceremony Monday in
Oxford city hall, Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie admitted
that religious differences were still ``the root cause of tensions
and deep divisions between different human groups.''
   ``It is premature to presume that the age of holy wars is long
past,'' said Runcie, spiritual head of the state Church of England
and leader of the world's 70 million Anglicans, including 3 million
U.S. Episcopalians.
   James Lovelock, a British scientist concerned with saving the
natural environment, said in a main theme speech prepared for
delivery today: ``We face the hard task of reintegrating creation _
of learning again to be part of the Earth and not separate from
it.''
   Lovelock, who with Lynn Margulis formulated the Gaia theory that
Earth itself is alive to the extent that it can regulate its
climate and chemical composition, said tropical forests which
helped to create the rain that sustains them, are being ``removed
at a ruthless pace.''
</TEXT>
