<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CatBan     04-12 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cat Ban,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Good News for Salt Marsh Harvest Mice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN RAFAEL, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There may be some good news in store
for the salt marsh harvest mice that live in that soggy, swampy
land along Las Gallinas Creek.
   The city council is bruiting a ban on cats.
   The ban was proposed by city planners for a 224-home subdivision
near the creek because of fears that housepets would hunt the
endangered mice, which live only in the wetlands of the San
Francisco Bay area.
   The Planning Commission also fears cats might hunt clapper rail
birds, another endangered species.
   Under the measure, homeowners would be required to trap stray
cats that venture into the marshland.
   But the measure may encounter some opposition when it shows up
on the council agenda next week.
   ``It's ridiculous that the city's trying to restrict people from
having animals,'' said Councilman Gary Frugoli. ``We'll be the
laughingstock of everybody.''
   Richard Garlinghouse, a spokesman for Southwest Diversified
Inc., the developer of the housing project, called the cat ban a
``reasonable compromise'' with environmentalists.
   He said construction is expected to start this summer.
   But Pat Miller of the Marin County Humane Society said the ban
might be unenforceable.
   ``Dogs are hard enough to catch,'' she said.
</TEXT>
