<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--GoldBanned     04-12 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Gold Banned,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Bans Gold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The principal of a Manhattan high school has
banned students from wearing the big gold jewelry he says is
responsible for three ``near-deaths'' at the school.
   Principal Edward Reynolds met students at the door of West Side
High as they returned from spring break. The ban includes gold
necklaces like thick rope, breast plates and medallions, rings with
three or four finger holes and earrings the size of door knockers.
   ``There have been three near-deaths at the school _ including an
incident with a gun in the gym _ over gold,'' Reynolds said.
   ``Most of the gold the kids wear is from drug money, theft or
buying of stolen gold,'' said Reynolds. ``Gold has become a symbol
of the street and all of the destructive values it represents.''
   Twelve years ago Reynolds banned jackets with gang colors at the
high school to decrease strife.
   Gold has taken the place of jackets, he said, with the most
popular styles being the Mercedes logo, studded with diamonds, and
an image of Jesus Christ affixed to an anchor.
</TEXT>
