<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 1016EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Afghanistan     04-12 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Afghanistan,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>50,000 Soviet Soldiers to Leave Within Three Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet Foreign Ministry official told Italian
parliamentarians today that 50,000 Soviet soldiers will be
withdrawn from Afghanistan within three months beginning May 15, an
Italian source said.
   The statement by First Deputy Foreign Minister Yuli Vorontsov
appeared to be the first time an official source gave any
indication of the size of the Soviet force in Afghanistan.
   Under an accord to be signed Thursday in Geneva, the Soviet
Union will agree to remove all of its soldiers from Afghanistan
within nine months of May 15, the first half of them by Aug. 15.
   The figure provided by Vorontsov would make the size of the
Soviet force about 100,000 soldiers. Western sources have estimated
there are 115,000 Soviet soldiers in Afghanistan, but the Soviets
never have provided a figure.
   The Italian source attended the meeting but spoke on condition
he not be further identified.
   Vorontsov told the group of eight Italian lawmakers that half of
the Soviet force would leave Afghanistan within three months, and
``he mentioned 50,000 soldiers,'' the source said.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Vadim Perfilyev, speaking at a
regular news briefing today, said he could not give a figure for
the number of Soviet soldiers in Afghanistan.
   Perfilyev indicated that Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze and U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz, who will
sign agreements to guarantee the Geneva accord, also may meet
separately to discuss other issues.
   Shultz will be in Moscow a week later to continue negotiations
for a 50 percent cut in strategic nuclear weapons, but ``it can't
be ruled out that there will be a meeting dealing with a broad
range of topics'' in Geneva, Perfilyev said.
   The Italian delegation that met with Vorontsov was headed by
Christian Democrat Flaminio Piccoli, president of the Foreign
Commission of the Italian Chamber of Deputies.
   Vorontsov did not provide any further details on the Soviet
forces in Afghanistan, but said that the soldiers would begin
taking up positions to begin withdrawing in a month, the Italian
source said.
   Vorontsov reportedly said nothing about the arming of pro-Soviet
Afghan government forces and Afghan guerrillas, who are supplied by
the United States and other countries.
   U.S.-Soviet disagreement over the future of that aid held up the
Geneva talks for several weeks before the two sides agreed that
they could continue supplying weapons.
   The United States had sought a symmetrical elimination of aid to
government forces and the Moslem guerrillas. But the Soviets
refused to go along, saying the United States interjected the
demand at the last minute and that Soviet Union could not violate
agreements with the Afghan government.
   Soviet soldiers entered Afghanistan in December 1979 and
replaced one pro-Soviet government with another. They remained to
help government forces fight anti-Communist insurgents, many of
whom have bases in neighboring Pakistan.
   The guerrillas have rejected the accords and said they will
continue to fight to oust the Kabul government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
