<HEAD>Safety Commission Warns of Sock Hazard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission is
urging parents to remove the teddy bear and pearl ornaments from
children's stockings to avoid the possibility of choking.
   Stockings for infants, decorated with the small plastic
ornaments, were sold by Le-Roi, a division of Princeton Hosiery
Mills in Princeton, Ky. The socks were sold under the Le-Roi and
Mother Care labels, officials said.
   If the plastic ornaments become detached from the socks, they
could present a choking hazard, the commission said, although no
incidents have been reported.
