<HEAD>Whale Sighted In Delaware, 70 Miles from Sea</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to update with today's search, picking up
at the 3rd graf previous, and Deletes the now redundant 8th graf
previous, beginning ``Officials were unable.''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teams from several state and federal
agencies searched today for a whale that swam about 70 miles up the
Delaware River, attracting flocks of boaters despite warnings it
could damage small craft.
   The 40-foot whale, first reported by a tugboat crew, was last
seen just before nightfall Monday at the Delaware Memorial Bridge,
which crosses the Delaware River about 25 miles south of
Philadelphia, officials said.
   Personnel from Delaware marine police, U.S. Coast Guard and the
state Department of Natural Resources went out in boats after
daybreak to try to find and identify the marine mammal, said
Kathleen Jamison, a public information officer with the natural
resources department.
   ``It's such a gray day here that it's not going to be easy to
spot it,'' Ms. Jamison said.
   The search crews hoped to guide the whale, of undetermined
species, back out to sea, she said.
   The last time a live whale was seen so far up the heavily
industrialized Delaware was in 1890, said Bob Schoelkopf, a
nationally recognized whale expert who directs the Marine Mammal
Stranding Center in Brigantine, N.J.
   ``It could be sick; it could be an old animal dying; it could
have been hit by a boat and dazed,'' Schoelkopf said.
   The Coast Guard was concerned both with the safety of the public
and the whale, which ``was just swimming around in circles,'' said
Chief Warrant Officer Dick Foy in Gloucester City, N.J.
   `A large freighter could kill the whale,'' he said. ``And if a
pleasure boat got too close, he could swish his tail and really
pose a hazard to small craft. We'll just try to entice it, coax it,
herd it, whatever you do with a whale, to try to get him back to
deep water where he belongs.''
   ``When we reached the Wilmington Terminal area, it came up right
in front of the boat,'' said Joyce Hennessey, a state Marine Police
officer. ``We have a 28-foot (boat), and it was bigger than that. I
would estimate it at 40 feet.''
   ``The Coast Guard is recommending that recreational and private
vessels exercise extreme caution in transitting the Delaware River
in the vicinity of the Delaware Memorial Bridge due to the size and
temperament of the whale,'' said Coast Guard Petty Officer Keith
Ferguson. ``The whale could inflict serious damage to a small
boater.''
   Boaters, however, ignored warnings and flocked to the river to
catch sight of the whale.
   ``I've never seen anything like this before in all my life,''
said Dave Boyd.
   ``We saw him first at 4:30. He broke water and jumped in the
air,'' said Gerry Cichocki. ``You'll know when he's coming up.
You'll hear him snort and spray, then come up.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880412-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 1036EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Ireland-Kidnap     04-12 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ireland-Kidnap,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Plead Guilty in Irish Abduction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irish nationalist leader Dessie O'Hare
and four other men accused of kidnapping and maiming a wealthy
dentist entered guilty pleas today as their trial began.
   The five had been expected to plead innocent.
   O'Hare limped into court. Irish Republic police shot and
seriously wounded him and killed a companion at a roadblock three
weeks after police freed the dentist Nov. 5. The kidnappers had
escaped in a hijacked van after a shootout with police.
   The guilty pleas followed two adjournments that delayed the
proceedings at Dublin's anti-terrorist Special Criminal Court for
an hour.
   Scores of armed police and soldiers were posted around the
courthouse. An army helicopter hovered overhead when an armed
convoy escorting the defendants arrived from a top-security prison
in Portlaoise, 50 miles southwest of Dublin.
   The defendants each admitted to falsely imprisoning 38-year-old
John O'Grady. O'Hare also pleaded guilty to maliciously wounding
O'Grady with intent to maim. Other lesser charges were dropped.
   There was no immediate explanation of why the guilty pleas were
made. Prosecution and defense lawyers were expected to outline the
pleas in proceedings later today. Sentencing was expected Wednesday.
   The kidnappers chopped off tips of two of O'Grady's fingers
during his 22 days in captivity, authorities said. He was freed by
police after detectives chanced upon the gang in a Dublin house on
Nov. 5.
   Published reports said they had demanded a $2.5 million ransom,
but police said nothing had been paid.
   O'Hare, 29, is from Ballymacauley in Northern Ireland's County
Armagh. Two other Northern Ireland defendants are Anthony McNeill,
25, of Belfast; and Fergal Toal, 25, of the town of Armagh. The
other two defendants _ Edward Hogan, 25, of Dublin and Gerard
Wright, 45, of Cork _ come from the Irish Republic.
   O'Grady, who did not appear in the court, was abducted at
gunpoint from his Dublin home.
   However, his father-in-law, Dr. Austin Darragh, was the intended
target. Darragh established an international drugs testing company,
the Dublin-based Institute of Clinical Pharmacology.
   O'Hare was accused of masterminding the kidnapping. Nicknamed
the ``Border Fox'' for his activities along the border between the
Irish Republic and Northern Ireland, O'Hare is a former member of
the Irish Republican Army and its offshoot, the Irish National
Liberation Army. Both groups have disowned him as a liability in
their fight to rid Northern Ireland of British rule.
   O'Hare has spent seven years in prison. He vowed police would
never take him alive in a clandestine interview with an Irish
newspaper during the kidnapping.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880412-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 1044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-AIDS     04-12 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-AIDS,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philippines Regulations Among World's Toughest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreigners including businessmen,
sailors and U.S. troops must obtain certificates showing they are
free of the AIDS virus before they can stay in the Philippines, the
government said today.
   The order, which takes effect Monday, requires all merchant
sailors to present AIDS-free certificates regardless of how long
they plan to remain in the Philippines.
   Other foreigners must prove they are free of the virus if they
want to stay longer than six months, the Department of Foreign
Affairs said.
   It added that details of the regulation covering U.S. troops and
dependents would be worked out in talks with American authorities.
   Foreigners admitted for less than six months must obtain
AIDS-free certificates from government-approved hospitals if they
want to extend their stay, the department added.
   The regulation was issued in compliance with an order by the
Commission on Immigration and Deportation banning foreigners with
``loathsome or dangerous and contagious diseases.''
   Immigration officials said the order was issued to prevent the
spread of the deadly disease in a country where prostitution is
widespread.
   Some health officials have criticized the plan as ineffective.
They say foreigners admitted for short periods could spread AIDS
because they would not be required to prove they are free of the
disease.
   They also noted that foreigners could purchase forged
certificates. Immigration Commissioner Miriam Defensor-Santiago
said she did not include short-term residents or tourists in the
order because the move could lead to reprisals against Filipino
tourists by other nations.
   According to the Department of Health, more than 50 people in
the Philippines have been identified as carrying the AIDS virus but
most have not shown symptoms of the disease.
   Most of the infected people have been bar girls working near
U.S. military bases.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, destroys the
body's immune system and makes the victim susceptible to cancers
and other fatal ailments. There is no cure.
   The virus is primarily spread by sexual contact, use of
contaminated needles, and transfusions of contaminated blood. The
disease can be transferred from an infected mother to her unborn
child.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
