<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Oscar Ratings,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oscars Show Could Be Highest in Five Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Academy Awards show seems to have stemmed
the extravaganza's television ratings decline by racking up its
highest rating in five years, according to preliminary data
released today by A.C. Nielsen Co.
   In the 15 largest television markets, Monday night's show had a
rating of 37.7 and a 59 share. The rating is a percentage of the
nation's 88.6 million homes with television. The share is a
percentage of sets in use.
   The last time the Oscars show rated higher was in 1983, when it
got a 38.0 and 59. Last year, the show had a national rating of
27.5 and a 43 share.
   When Nielsen computes the national rating for the show later
today, adding in smaller markets and rural areas, the numbers could
drop somewhat.
   The show lasted from 9 p.m. EDT until 12:30 a.m. But during
prime time, from 9-11 p.m., according to the big-city overnights,
it had a 38.3 rating and 56 share; NBC had a rating of 6.9 and a 10
share. CBS had a 6.4 and 9.
</TEXT>
