<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BallpointSuicide     04-12 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ballpoint Suicide,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Kills Self with Ballpoint Pens</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmits a0608 to fix category code</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BURNABY, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An accused murderer killed
himself while being held at a psychiatric institute by driving two
ballpoint pens through his heart, a corner's jury has ruled.
   The jury in suburban Vancouver issued its findings Monday after
pathologist Dr. Lindsay Sturrock testified on the suicide of Allen
Foster,37, at the Forensic Psychiatric Institute in Coquitlam,
another Vancouver suburb.
   Foster put the sharp end of a pen against his bare chest and,
with the other end propped against a door, leaned forward, forcing
the pen between his ribs and into his heart on Dec. 27, Sturrock
said.
   When that failed to kill him, Foster repeated the process with a
second pen, again penetrating his heart, and died of massive
bleeding into his chest cavity, the pathologist said.
   When a juror asked how anyone could twice complete such a
painful process, the pathologist said, ``If someone is sufficiently
disturbed to do away with himself, pain doesn't mean very much.''
   The jury recommended closer, 24-hour watches on maximum-security
patients and changes in the institute's assessment reporting system.
   Foster had been undergoing a 30-day psychiatric examination
after being charged with first-degree murder in the bludgeoning
death of his common-law wife, Joan Pilling, 34, her daughter Linda
Brewer and Brewer's friend Megan Sue McCleary, both 12.
   Foster surrendered to police Dec. 13, the day after the three
slayings, and was admitted to the institute Dec. 15.
   Terrance Neil, nursing director at the institute, testified that
Foster denied feelings of depression or suicide when he was
admitted.
   Shortly before his suicide, however, Foster wrote a letter to
correction officials begging for special protection in prison.
</TEXT>
