<HEAD>Bush Acknowledges GOP Nomination Race No Thriller, But Hails Party
Unity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with Bush comments today; pick up 5th graf
pvs bgng ``We don't...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SCHENECTADY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said today
``I can't wait'' to take on any of the three Democrats still vying
for their party's nomination.
   Bush is seeking to build big-state support while acknowledging
his campaign lacks the excitement of the Democratic primary contest.
   ``I still intend to campaign right through the end of the
primary season. I can't wait to take on which ever one of those
three Democrats wins the Democratic nomination,'' Bush told a
$100-a-plate Republican breakfast in Schenectady.
   Bush planned to throw out the first ball at a Mets baseball game
in Shea Stadium in the afternoon.
   Bush is spending three days campaigning in New York state, even
though his only Republican opponent on the April 19 primary ballot
is former television evangelist Pat Robertson, who has ceased
active campaigning.
   ``We don't have all the excitement that exists on the Democratic
side of the aisle, but we have a lot more unity and we have fewer
problems,'' Bush told a shopping mall audience on Monday in White
Plains.
   During a visit to an IBM center in Thornwood, Bush declined to
comment on remarks by New York Mayor Ed Koch suggesting that New
York Jews ought not to vote for Democrat Jesse Jackson.
   ``Listen, I've got enough problems on our own side to get into
the Democratic nominating process,'' Bush said. ``Ed Koch is
entitled to his opinion. Each candidate is entitled to run on his
record.''
   In fact, Bush said, Jewish voters should vote for him. ``I think
everyone should vote for me. Besides, I'm a good friend of Israel.''
   Bush attended a fund-raiser Monday night in Greenwich, Conn., at
a private residence. Aides said $220,000 was collected at the
$1,000-a-plate event.
   Another fund-raising dinner was planned for tonight in Manhattan.
   Bush's campaign last week reached the maximum $27 million
pre-convention ceiling on contributions. Funds being raised now are
going toward a separate $2.8 million fund to comply with federal
election law audits.
   The vice president scheduled campaign stops in Buffalo and
Rochester on Wednesday.
