<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GangSweeps     04-12 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gang Sweeps,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Many Weekend Gang Arrest Cases Dismissed For Lack Of Evidence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIC LEYVA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors have rejected about half the
cases brought so far following a giant weekend police sweep against
gangs, saying there is not enough evidence to proceed in court.
   Two nights of dusk-to-dawn patrols last weekend by about 1,000
officers resulted in 1,453 arrests, Officer Joe Mariani said.
   Charges have been filed so far in 32 of 60 cases taken to the
Los Angeles County District Attorney's office, said Deputy District
Attorney Stephen Kay. The other 28 were rejected because of lack of
evidence, he said.
   City attorney's spokesman Mike Qualls said half of the 41 cases
taken to his agency were rejected because of insufficient evidence.
Felony cases are normally prosecuted by the county, while the city
attorney takes misdemeanors.
   Other cases still must be reviewed.
   Police Chief Daryl Gates called for the show of force after a
rash of gang-related shootings, including a drive-by attack Good
Friday that killed one man and wounded a dozen other people.
   The weekend sweep dubbed ``Fly the Flag'' won praise from most
quarters, but three people whose house was allegedly ransacked by
police serving a search warrant called the show of force
heavy-handed.
   There were 387 gang-related murders in Los Angeles County last
year and more than 85 such homicides have been reported so far this
year.
   More than half of those arrested, or 794, were alleged gang
members, Mariani said. Offenses ranged from 171 arrested for
investigation of drug peddling to 138 allegedly driving under the
influence of alcohol of drugs, he said.
   ``We accomplished what we set out to do, namely letting gangs
know we mean to put them out of business,'' said police spokeswoman
Margie Reed. ``But we aren't saying when we'll hit again. We don't
particularly like to let them know we're coming like we did this
time.''
   Gates urged officers to get tough with gang members while
showing restraint in dealing with others living in gang-dominated
neighborhoods.
   But two men and a pregnant woman said officers serving a search
warrant Sunday ransacked their home, beat them and forced to lie on
the floor while handcuffed.
   ``I was just getting ready to watch the Laker game on TV when I
heard them kick in the front door and start breaking windows,''
said O.C. Baker, 34. ``They strapped a plastic loop on my wrists
real tight, made me get down on the foor and kicked me in the
ribs.''
   The plain-clothes officers put guns to the heads of the three
adults and repeatedly swore at them to obey orders, Baker said.
   Police Lt. Dave Hepburn, who led the raid, said a previous
undercover drug purchase at the house prompted the raid, but no
drugs were found.
   Despite the citywide gang crackdown, four people were killed in
drive-by shootings over the weekend, and nine other people were
injured in a similar attack in Willowbrook, authorities said.
</TEXT>
