<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissingNewlyweds     04-12 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Newlyweds,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missing Couple Toyed With Secret Brazil Trip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Missing newlyweds toyed with the idea of secretly
selling her expensive foreign car and running away to another
country, possibly Brazil, according to an entry in the woman's
journal.
   But friends and family of Wheaton College students Scott
Swanson, 23, and Carolyn MacLean, 21, were not taking the entry
seriously on Monday.
   The couple, secretly married March 26, were last seen April 2
when they left Ms. MacLean's grandmother's house in Flint, Mich.,
on their way back to Illinois.
   The two were supposed to have dinner in Chicago before visiting
Swanson's parents in Elgin, but they never showed up. Ms. MacLean's
red BMW was found April 2 in an alley behind Chicago's Orchestra
Hall. The key was in the ignition and the engine was running,
police said.
   The journal entry mentioning selling the car and going away was
undated. It did not mention Swanson by name but used the pronoun
``we,'' police said. They declined to disclose the exact wording of
the entry.
   But police said that if the pair did indeed flee in search of a
new life, they left behind Swanson's passport, both their driver's
licenses and credit cards.
   ``We're looking for a break,'' said Cmdr. Ettore DiVito of the
Chicago Police Youth Division. ``We're being very open-minded.''
   Gwendy Kem, Ms. MacLean's best friend, said the title to the car
is in her father's name, making a secret sale difficult.
   ``The fact remains that they were not organized for (running
away),'' she said.
   Over the weekend and again Monday, searchers used a special
airplane equipped with infrared sensors to detect freshly buried
corpses, but they failed to turn up a trace of the newlyweds.
   ``While we hope the couple hasn't met with foul play, this is
something we have to do,'' state police spokesman Bob Fletcher said.
   DiVito said law enforcement personnel from Illinois, Indiana,
Michigan and Wisconsin are cooperating in the search.
</TEXT>
