<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Hijack     04-12 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Hijack,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Says It Offered To Storm Hijacked Jet</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hijack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran offered to storm the hijacked Kuwaiti
jetliner after it was forced to land in northeastern Iran but
Kuwait rejected the offer, Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister Javad
Larijani said today.
   Larijani, speaking at a news conference at the Iranian Embassy,
said Iran had no alternative but to refuel the aircraft and allow
it to leave Mashhad on Friday. It later landed at Larnaca, Cyprus.
   He said the Kuwaiti authorities rejected the Iranian offer to
storm the Boeing 747 ``saying they are not going to take
responsibility for the outcome of that operation.''
   Asked what advice Kuwait gave, he said, ``I should say, nothing.
And we were afraid that the airplane would be blown up so we were
forced to refuel it. It was against our wish. But this was the only
thing we could do.''
   He said the hijacked aircraft would not be allowed back to Iran.
   ``We think it's for the people in Cyprus to decide,'' Larijani
said. ``Iran will be closed to all hijacked airplanes forever.''
   He denied news reports that additional hijackers were allowed to
board the plane in Iran.
   ``Hijacking innocent people is wrong,'' he said. ``These people
should be released immediately. This is not a noble deed for a
noble cause at all.''
   The hijackers, who commandeered the Kuwait Airways plane April 5
on a flight from Bangkok to Kuwait, have demanded that Kuwait free
17 convicted terrorists.
   The plane carried 112 people when it left Bangkok. Fifty-seven
people were freed in Iran, and one man was released after the plane
reached Cyprus. The hijackers have killed two passengers.
</TEXT>
