<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Siamese Twins, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0627,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hospital Separates Siamese Twins</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf, Dr. John xxx, to CORRECT name to James</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen-month-old Siamese twin girls who
were joined from the waist down have been separated in a 12-hour
operation, Children's Hospital of Philadelphia announced today.
   Both girls were in critical but stable condition, which was
considered normal after such an operation, said hospital
spokeswoman Laura Feragen. The operation was performed Monday.
   The family requested that the girls' names and home town not be
released, the spokeswoman said.
   The twins were joined front to front, said Bonnie Jacobs,
another hospital spokeswoman. Each girl had one leg and they shared
a third, fused leg, she said.
   The type of joining affects only about 1 percent of all Siamese
twins, Ms. Feragen said. However, it was the fourth such incidence
treated at Children's Hospital, she said.
   Since December the twins had been undergoing a series of
skin-expanding procedures using balloon-like silicon implants into
which saline solution was pumped, Ms. Feragen said. The procedure
eliminated the need for skin grafts.
   Dr. James A. O'Neill Jr., the hospital's surgeon-in-chief,
headed a 13-member operating team.
</TEXT>
