<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Pulitzer-Complaint 1stLd-Writethru a0526 04-12 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pulitzer-Complaint, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0526,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Board Upholds Award to Newspaper Reporter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 12th pvs, ``The statement xxx, to add
names of committee members taking part in decision</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reporter for The Philadelphia Inquirer whose
Pulitzer Prize was challenged by a magazine that ran a similar
story says he had no doubt his award would be upheld.
   The Pulitzer board's executive committee said Monday it saw no
reason to question the award to Tim Weiner, who won the national
reporting prize for a 1987 series on the Defense Department's
``black budget'' for secret projects.
   The National Journal last week asked the board to reconsider the
Inquirer's prize.
   The Washington-based weekly magazine said Weiner's series was
``a blatant and egregious case of building a news story according
to someone else's blueprint,'' namely, the magazine's March 1,
1986, cover story about the black budget. It contended that
Weiner's story broke no new ground.
   In Philadelphia on Monday, Weiner called the National Journal's
challenge ``a false charge and a phony controversy.''
   ``I never had any doubts it would be resolved this way,'' he
said. ``It's been very instructive being on the other end of the
telescope.''
   The committee's decision shows its members are ``able to cut
through baloney when they see it,'' said James M. Naughton, the
Inquirer's deputy managing editor.
   ``We appreciate the promptness with which the Pulitzer board
acted on our request for a review,'' National Journal publisher
John Fox Sullivan said in a statement. ``We raised the issue of
recycled journalism in good faith and now consider the current
matter closed.''
   The Pulitzer Board said in a statement that after careful
consideration of the Journal's objections, the executive committee
found no reason to question the award.
   Three committee members met in New York on Monday and two joined
in on the phone from Washington, said board secretary Robert
Christopher.
   ``It was relatively brief and there wasn't any disagreement,''
Christopher said. ``Everybody was in accord on what should be done
or should not be done.''
   The statement said the decision was reached by unanimous vote of
the five executive committee members participating, he said. Two
members, Inquirer executive editor Eugene Roberts and David
Laventhol, president of the Times Mirror Co., which owns the
National Journal, did not take part.
   Those taking part included Christopher; Roger W. Wilkins, senior
fellow at the Washington-based Institute for Policy Studies; James
F. Hoge Jr., publisher of the New York Daily News; Charlotte
Saikowski, Washington bureau chief of The Christian Science
Monitor; and Columbia University President Michael I. Sovern.
   Christopher said last week that prize-winning stories don't have
to break new ground, but only represent ``a distinguished example
of reporting on national affairs.''
   ``Our object was to publish the most complete, thorough,
readable account of the black budget ever done, and we are
convinced we did it,'' said Roberts.
   The Inquirer said Weiner broke new ground with his analysis of
the Defense Department budget, concluding that the department had
$35 billion in hidden programs.
   Weiner said he interviewed more than 100 people across the
nation and was ``knee-deep'' in his work before he saw the
Journal's story.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
