<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Pakistan-Blasts     04-12 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan-Blasts,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>100 Still Missing After Pakistani Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 people were still missing
today, two days after an explosion at an ammunition depot killed 93
people and injured 1,100.
   State-run Pakistan television said 170 teams of explosives
experts, working around the clock, have so far cleared 20,000
missiles, grenades and other weapons that lay around the twin
cities of Islamabad and Rawalpindi.
   President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq said Monday that an estimated
6,500 devices were to be cleared. There was no explanation for the
discrepancy in the figures.
   The Los Angeles Times reported today that agents from the
pro-Soviet government in Afghanistan were apparently responsible
for Sunday's explosion.
   The newspaper, quoting unidentified sources, said Pakistani
military experts had told U.S. officials about the cause of the
blast.
   The explosion was caused by three incendiary devices carried to
the ammunition dump by trucks bearing Afghan license plates and
equipped with time fuses, the Times said. They were exploded in
sequence, the newspaper said.
   Unidentified U.S. sources told the newspaper the explosions
wiped out a major source of CIA-supplied tactical assault weapons
for resistance fighters battling the Soviet-backed government in
Afghanistan.
   A four-man U.S. team of bomb disposal experts is helping to
clear the unexploded ammunition, including some which fell on the
residences of U.S. Embassy personnel and the international school.
   Television reports said most of the children missing from
Sunday's blasts at the Ojeri army camp have been reunited with
their families. About 100 people remained unaccounted for, it said.
   The Cabinet chaired by Prime Minister Mohammad Khan Junejo and
the Senate met today to review the situation.
   Pakistani television said that during the Cabinet meeting, it
was decided that a committee investigating the explosion should
submit its findings with recommendations within 10 days and that
they will be made public.
</TEXT>
