<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Lawyer-Bride     04-12 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Lawyer-Bride,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grateful Residents Offer Bride to Lawyer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grateful black residents who
won a court battle against the government offered their white
lawyer a bride, but he politely declined.
   ``I am very pleased to say that I already have a wife,'' said
John Dugard, head of the Institute of Applied Legal Studies at the
University of the Witswatersrand in Johannesburg.
   The community northwest of Pretoria made the offer in keeping
with tribal tradition.
   Dugard represented the 120,000-member community, Moutse, that
was incorporated by the government into a homeland dominated by a
different tribe on Jan. 1, 1986.
   The government's 10 homelands are part of a plan to grant
limited autonomy to the country's blacks. They are not
internationally recognized, however.
   A court ruled March 29 that President P.W. Botha exceeded his
powers when he incorporated Moutse into the KwaNdebele homeland.
The community is independent of any homeland as a result of the
decision.
   Most Moutse residents belong to the North Sotho tribe. They
argued that their language and culture differed sharply from the
Ndebeles, who make up most of KwaNdebele's 400,000 people.
</TEXT>
