<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Train-Attack     04-12 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Train-Attack,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>33 Hurt as Chinese Rail Workers Assault Train</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of railway employees attacked train
conducters with picks and stones after three co-workers were
prevented from riding free, and 33 people were injured, it was
reported Tuesday.
   The official China Youth News said five people remained in
serious condition, and train windows were broken in the April 4
melee in southeastern Guangdong province.
   The attackers stripped the clothes of women conductors and
kicked one pregnant conductor in the stomach, the newspaper
reported. The workers used sticks to beat other employees and
passengers who tried to protect them.
   The attack came after conductors refused to give free passage to
three men who said they were railway employees but lacked
identification. Railway employees are allowed free travel.
   The paper said the train was heading for Canton, the capital of
Guangdong, at the time. When it returned through the same area
later in the day, 300 to 400 angry rail employees were waiting, the
report said.
   The main attack took place at Shaoguan. When the train arrived
at Zheling, a smaller station down the line, more attackers came
aboard and continued the assault, the newspaper said.
   There was no mention of arrests.
</TEXT>
