<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ResearchFraud 1stLd-Writethru a0421 04-12 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Research Fraud, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0421,620</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: First 9 grafs new, picking up 5th graf pvs, Although NIH</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Massachusetts Institute of Technology
scientist testified today that he knew of fraud taking place in
research at the institute but was reluctant to report it because he
feared retribution.
   Dr. Charles Maplethorpe, who was conducting post-doctoral
research at MIT, said he learned of what he considered fraudulent
research by Thereza Imanishi-Kari but was reluctant to report it
until just before receiving his degree.
   Dr. Maplethorpe said he told an MIT official that he suspected
fraud and the official's only action was to give him a form to fill
out.
   ``I felt there was no question that if I made a formal charge of
fraud it would not be taken seriously and I would be the person
worst off for it,'' he said.
   Appearing today under subpoena before the House Energy and
Commerce subcommittee on oversight and investigations, Maplethorpe
said he was very reluctant to present the testimony and would not
be there except for the legal compulsion.
   ``There is a tremendous disincentive to come forward and once
they come forward, the instigators will pay a price,'' he said.
   The testimony came during hearings on practices of fraud in the
government's $5-billion biomedical research program.
   In testimony before another subcommittee yesterday, Walter W.
Stewart and Dr. Ned Feder, two National Institutes of Health
scientists, said they have received unfavorable job ratings since
they have acted as whistleblowers about false research data
reported by NIH grant recipients.
   Stewart and Feder said they began investigating allegations of
misconduct by grant recipients about four years ago.
   Although NIH officially allows them to spend 20 percent of their
time investigating scientific fraud, Stewart said, he discovered in
1985 that his laboratory equipment at the National Institute of
Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases had been removed and
junked without notice.
   Stewart and Feder, whose work had always been judged
satisfactory, said they began getting unfavorable job evaluations,
which were reversed on appeal.
   Stewart said their troubles clearly stemmed from their inquiries
into fraudulent practices by NIH grant recipients.
   Another whistleblower who complained of mistreatment was Dr.
Jerome G. Jacobstein, who said ``I have been ignored by my friends,
vilified by my enemies, despised, hated, condemned and on a rare
but satisfying occasion, perhaps, respected.''
   Jacobstein alleged that Dr. Jeffrey S. Borer, a cardiologist and
Cornell University Medical College professor, attempted to induce a
student to make numerous misrepresentations in a joint scientific
study report. He said Borer ultimately got away with a mild rebuke.
   Jacobstein estimated that although extreme forms of research
fraud, such as wholesale fabrication of data, were ``fairly rare,''
an estimated 20 percent to 30 percent of research studies supported
by NIH grants contained unethically flawed data.
   ``A scientist who cheats injures other scientists by misleading
them, and he injures the public by wasting their money and
sometimes by falsely claiming discoveries that directly affect the
public health and welfare,'' Stewart and Feder said Monday in a
joint statement to the subcommittee.
   Rep. Ted Weiss, D-N.Y., chairman of the House Government
Operations panel, expressed sympathy for a suggestion by Rep. John
Conyers, D-Mich., that Congress should approve criminal penalties
for scientific fraud or misconduct because of its threat of
``incredible harm and injury to the public.''
   The whistleblowers, who also included Professor Robert L.
Sprague of the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign,
complained that criminal penalties would be excessively harsh and
might create a damaging climate of fear among scientists.
   The witnesses all expressed hope that the scientific community
might find a way to improve internal safeguards against research
abuses. But Weiss said no one _ neither the NIH, the universities
receiving research grants nor professional scientific societies _
had shown willingness to solve the fraud problem.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
