<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PoliceChief 1stLd-Writethru a0630 04-12 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Police Chief, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0630,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Chief Resigns</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs, Prince announcement; picks up 6th graf
pvs, ``Prince, a; adds byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By READ MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police Chief Billy Prince, under fire from top
city officials for criticizing City Council members and opposing
police reforms, resigned today.
   Prince said he is stepping down immediately, and city manager
Richard Knight appointed first assistant police chief Louie C.
Caudell as interim chief, police Sgt. Carol Eberhardt said.
   ``I don't want to be a lame-duck leader or a lame-duck chief,''
said Prince. He said he will serve in an advisory role through the
summer.
   Prince, who has been chief for six years, said he is tired of
the battling between the community and his beleaguered department.
   ``I made this decision, after an 11-day vacation, on Easter
Sunday,'' Prince said at a news conference. ``I woke up Easter
Sunday and just didn't feel good about returning. I told my wife
then, `I think it's time for me to go.'''
   It wasn't one event that led to his decision, but ``I would not
be totally truthful if I said I liked the atmosphere we've been
working under. It's very trying and it wears you down.''
   Prince said he was not forced out of the $87,000 per-year job,
and said he will now concentrate on business interests.
   ``I'm 45 years old, and I feel I'm at a part of my life when if
I'm going to change, now's the time to do it,'' he said.
   Prince, a 24-year Dallas police veteran, has discussed his
resignation with Knight and other associates several times in the
last few weeks, officials said.
   His resignation comes at a time of tension between police and
the minority community. He has been caught between the demands of a
majority of the City Council, including Mayor Annette Strauss, who
want more police accountability, and the Dallas police union, which
opposes greater control.
   Some minority community leaders, including City Councilwoman
Diane Ragsdale and County Commissioner John Wiley Price, have
called for Prince's dismissal.
   City Councilman Jerry Rucker said he was angered by the reports
and called Prince a ``scapegoat for the mayor and the city
manager.''
   ``What a horrible thing for Dallas,'' Rucker said. ``I think
it's a tragedy for a man to be hounded out of his office by
demagogues.''
   Rucker, who has considered running for mayor, predicted Prince's
resignation would be an issue in the 1989 municipal elections.
   ``I think the people will finally say this is the last straw,''
Rucker said.
   Prince has been at odds with the City Council since late last
year, when Knight rebuked Prince for lobbying against police
reforms recommended by Mrs. Strauss' Advisory Committee on Crime.
   The aftermath of the Jan. 23 slaying of officer John Glenn Chase
by a vagrant in downtown parking lot put Prince on a collision
course with the city's elected leadership.
   Prince said some City Council members shared blame for Chase's
death because they had created an atmosphere of hostility toward
police.
   Mrs. Strauss asked Prince to retract his statements, which she
said heightened racial tensions, but he refused to back down.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
