summer.
   Prince, who has been chief for six years, said he is tired of
the battling between the community and his beleaguered department.
   ``I made this decision, after an 11-day vacation, on Easter
Sunday,'' Prince said at a news conference. ``I woke up Easter
Sunday and just didn't feel good about returning. I told my wife
then, `I think it's time for me to go.'''
   It wasn't one event that led to his decision, but ``I would not
be totally truthful if I said I liked the atmosphere we've been
working under. It's very trying and it wears you down.''
   Prince said he was not forced out of the $87,000 per-year job,
and said he will now concentrate on business interests.
   ``I'm 45 years old, and I feel I'm at a part of my life when if
I'm going to change, now's the time to do it,'' he said.
   Prince, a 24-year Dallas police veteran, has discussed his
resignation with Knight and other associates several times in the
