<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Harlem     04-12 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Harlem,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Draws Crowds in Harlem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic presidential candidate's stroll
through Harlem was unannounced but word swept the streets _ ``It's
Jesse Jackson!''
   Children scampered up to touch him, women in curlers called out
from upper-story windows, youths in jeans and basketball shoes
hollered from the street, and old men hobbled over to see him walk
by.
   It was an impromptu walk down Adam Clayton Powell Boulevard from
the renowned Abyssinian Baptist Church where he had preached on
Sunday morning to Sylvia's restaurant 15 minutes away.
   ``Go Jesse,'' the crowds shouted.
   ``You've got my vote.''
   ``Jesse, I pray for you,'' said one old lady.
   It was an incongruous sight. Jackson, tall and crisply attired
in dark blue suit, beamed as he walked hand in hand with his wife,
Jacqueline, their son Jonathan astride. The candidate all but
disappeared except for his head as he was swallowed by a gaggle of
reporters and cameras, a phalanx of police officers and a team of
Secret Service agents.
   They walked a street lined with trash, gutted buildings,
dilapidated stores and apartments, beat-up cars and broken
sidewalks.
   But the street came alive with Harlem residents. In their
excitement over Jackson, they bumped into security agents, running
alongside and behind his entourage as if he were the Pied Piper.
   There seemed to be a sense that Jackson was on home turf here.
   Speaking at the Abyssinian Church earlier, Jackson called the
church's pastor, Sam Proctor, his mentor. He recalled that Proctor
and he had many discussions about the missions of the late Adam
Clayton Powell, the local congressman who gained fame as the
eloquent pastor of the same church, and about civil rights leader
Martin Luther King.
   Jackson told the congregation there is still ``unfinished
business'' in the agenda set by King, that poor people are still
hungry and peace is still elusive.
   On his walk later, Jackson hugged passersby and lifted children.
   ``How you doin' brother,'' he called out.
   He approached a basketball court and some 15 young men raced to
the chain-link fence around it. He couldn't shake their hands
through the fence, but they pressed their palms against one side
and he put his against the other. They tossed him their ball, and
he threw it back over the fence as they cheered wildly.
   ``I'm not going to wash my hand no more in my life,'' one
middle-aged woman gushed after touching Jackson.
   A sidewalk bookseller told him, ``I sold out of your book.''
   Two young women called to his wife that she was ``so lucky'' to
have such an attractive husband. One of them shouted to Jackson,
``You're gonna win, you handsome devil.''
   Jackson laughed as a boy of about 10 took his hand and chattered
about his family and point out where his relatives lived.
   Someone pointed out two tall palm trees in a deserted lot that
were stripped of their fronds, painted crazily and had basketball
hoops suspended about 30 feet in the air.
   ``Ain't no goal too high, right Jesse?'' said a man following
the candidate.
</TEXT>
