<HEAD>Hollywood Glamour and Political Activism Come Together</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 10, ``This is xxx, to restore 1st full reference to
Sladek</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Limousines were bumper-to-bumper
on Sunset Boulevard early today as celebrities made their way to
two big post-Oscar parties.
   Hollywood glamor mixed with political activism at a benefit for
Central American refugees that drew such stars as Rosanna Arquette,
Morgan Fairchild and Nicholas Cage to the ultra-modern Le Mondrian
Hotel.
   Meanwhile literary agent Swifty Lazar's annual bash drew a crowd
at the trendy Spago restaurant.
   About 600 people paid $500 each to attend the Le Mondrian
fund-raiser for El Escerte, an organization that provides board,
food and medical care for Central American refugees.
   Outdoors at poolside under a glittering night sky, Ms. Fairchild
and Ms. Arquette chatted as the head of the Stallone clan,
outspoken Jacqueline Stallone, swept through with her non-Rambo
son, Frank.
   Nicholas Cage of ``Moonstruck'' stopped by after midnight,
joining such other partygoers as Olivia Hussey, Tina Yothers and
John Amos.
   ``I wanted to get into the spirit of the Oscars. It's fun and
exciting,'' said Miss Hussey, whose films include ``Romeo and
Juliet.''
   ``I'm here to raise money for Central American refugees. It's a
very good cause,'' said Miss Arquette, who has appeared in such
films as ``Silverado,'' ``Desperately Seeking Susan'' and ``The
Executioner's Song.''
   Esai Morales, who played rock singer Ritchie Valens' brother in
the film ``La Bamba,'' was co-chairman of the event.
   ``This is an Oscar party with a conscience,'' said another
co-chairman, 22-year-old producer Dan Sladek. ``Swifty's represents
old Hollywood. This crowd represents a new generation of young
Hollywood who are socially committed, who go to an Oscar party and
pay for it, rather than crash it.''
   But although glitter was not in short supply at Le Mondrian, the
main event was still at Spago, where the scene was nearly as
glamorous as the Oscars ceremony itself. Many of Hollywood's
glitterati watched the telecast at the balloon and
streamer-bedecked restaurant rather than brave rush-hour traffic to
the Shrine Auditorium 10 miles away.
   Among the celebrities in attendance at the invitation-only fete
were Roger Moore, Neil Simon, Henry Mancini, Don Rickles, Bob
Newhart and Suzanne Pleshette. Sean Connery, Best Supporting Oscar
in hand, dropped in after the ceremony.
</TEXT>
