<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Zimbabwe     04-12 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zimbabwe,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zimbabwe Says It May Send More Troops to Mozambique</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government may move troops from a
formerly embattled western province to Mozambique, where they would
fight right-wing rebels, the defense minister said Tuesday.
   The soldiers were sent to Matabeleland province six years ago to
hunt down armed dissidents.
   However, rebel activity has vanished there since President
Robert Mugabe and former opposition leader Joshua Nkomo signed a
unity accord Dec. 22, Defense Minister Enos Nkala told the Zimbabwe
Inter-African News Agency.
   The dissidents battled for Nkomo in the seven-year war that
transformed white-ruled Rhodesia into black-governed Zimbabwe on
April 18, 1980. However, they left the army two years later to
fight the new government, killing hundreds of black peasants and
more than 60 whites.
   The parties of Nkomo and Mugabe last week approved a merger
expected to lead to one-party rule by Mugabe's Zimbabwe African
National Union.
   The defense chief said the government could plan for withdrawing
soldiers from Matabeleland and deploying them instead to assist the
government of neighboring Mozambique.
   About 12,000 of Mugabe's troops are in Mozambique guarding trade
routes and an oil pipeline vital to landlocked Zimbabwe's economy.
The military chief did not say how many troops might be moved.
   The area is threatened by rebels fighting the government of
Marxist President Joaquim Chissano.
</TEXT>
