<DOCNO> AP880412-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 1355EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DrugCountries     04-12 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Countries,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Committee Will Let Senate Decide on Mexican Drug Efforts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sharply divided Senate Foreign Relations
Committee refused to slap Mexico on Tuesday over its failings in
the war on drugs, leaving that decision to the full Senate, where
it could come to a vote in the next few days.
   The panel did approve a similar resolution condemning the
Bahamas for not doing enough to combat drug trafficking, and moved
to add Haiti to the list of countries that should come under
increased scrutiny as drug producing or transit points. The vote on
the Bahamas issue was 10-6, and the Haiti resolution passed on a
voice vote.
   The Reagan admnistration last month certified that Mexico and
the Bahamas are ``fully cooperating'' with U.S. efforts to halt
drug trafficking. Such a certification is required for any foreign
country identified as a drug producing or transit point to continue
to receive U.S. aid and other benefits.
   But Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., objected to the Mexico
certification, pointing to continued high rates of marijuana and
cocaine flowing into the United States from that country and
problems with official corruption and lack of cooperation with U.S.
drug interdiction authorities.
   Wilson proposed a resolution to decertify Mexico, which could
subject it to aid, lending and trade sanctions under U.S. law.
   The Foreign Relations panel, after lengthy debate over the
effect of such a move on overall U.S. relations with Mexico,
defeated an effort to send the bill to the floor with a favorable
recommendation. The vote was an 8-8 tie, which defeated the motion
under committee rules.
   In effect, the action left the decision to the full Senate,
since the bill has priority status and must go to the floor for
final action in any case.
   But Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., who has been holding hearings on
Latin American drug trafficking, said the move represented a
victory in the war on drugs. ``It reflects the changing mood and
dynamic in Congress,'' Kerry said, noting that several senators had
switched sides on the issue in light of a growing awareness of the
drug problem.
   Kerry predicted a hard-fought debate when the measure comes to
the floor later this week or next week, and said he could not
predict the outcome.
   The measure is primarily symbolic in its impact on foreign aid,
since Mexico's only current U.S. aid is $14.5 million in money to
combat drugs, money which would be unaffected by any sanctions.
   More important for Mexico, however, could be a requirement that
the United States oppose future loans from international
development banks. The United States has a weighted vote in
decisions on such loans, but not a majority.
   Decertification also could expose Mexico to various trade
sanctions, at the discretion of the president.
   Arguing for the Mexico resolution, Kerry noted that the
administration itself had noted numerous failings by Mexico when it
certified full cooperation on March 1, noting that a ``higher
level'' of cooperation was needed. ``You can't have it both ways,''
Kerry said.
   ``The point has really arrived where other countries are
watching us,'' he said, noting that Panamanian ruler Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega, indicted in the United States on drug trafficking
charges, seems to be drawing strength from U.S. confusion over its
policy toward him.
   But Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., said Mexico already is
devoting large proportions of its national budget to fighting drug
trafficking and that decertification would destroy that cooperation.
   ``They're doing a great deal,'' Dodd said. ``This is a slap in
the face that's going to set us in the wrong direction. ... If this
resolution is adopted, you can expect the worst kind of
cooperation.''
</TEXT>
