<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     04-12 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet reporter was barred from this
gambling and entertainment capital for 16 years because of nearby
military installations and the nuclear test site. Now that he's
seen it, he's less than impressed.
   The lights on the Las Vegas Strip are so bright ``you can read a
newspaper at 3 a.m. _ that is, provided you don't care if people
take you for an idiot,'' Vitaly Gan, a correspondent for the
Communist Party newspaper Pravda, wrote in a profile published
Monday in the Los Angeles Times and Las Vegas Review-Journal.
   He referred to the city's slot machines, commonly known as
``one-armed bandits,'' as ``one-legged bandits.''
   He described the Strip as ``an orgy of buildings, arches,
fountains, statues and ads, striking the eye with the abandon and
wanton nature of the merry-making going on there. All this rolls
before your eyes in a searing ball of fire, 24 hours a day.''
   Gan visited the city briefly in January when Soviet scientists
visited the Nevada Test Site, 65 miles northwest of Las Vegas,
studying ways to verify a nuclear test ban.
   He was especially unimpressed with the city's main industry.
   ``People know that gambling is one of the silliest inventions of
mankind,'' Gan said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One man's idea of progress can be another
man's torture.
   Architects admire the new, streamlined toll booths at the San
Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge.
   ``We thought we were doing the best we could,'' said CalTrans
architect Doug Lowe, who believes the old toll booths looked like
``phone booths in the middle of a freeway.''
   The people who have to work inside the booths aren't so
enthusiastic, because their work space is only 20 inches wide. The
old ones were nearly a yard wide.
   ``I hate them. When you have two people inside to take over
shifts, it really is impossible,'' said toll collector Robert
Montgomery.
   ``I doubt whether any one of us likes the new booths,'' said
toll collector John Harris, 57, who has served on the 8.5-mile span
since 1955. ``It's just too cramped for a person to stay in there
6{ hours a day.''
</TEXT>
