<DOCNO> AP880412-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 1429EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Cuomo-Democrats 2ndLd-Writethru a0604 04-12 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuomo-Democrats, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0604,720</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS that Landow didn't say Dukakis has locked up
nomination, subbing 3 grafs for grafs 5-6 pvs, ``It helps ... his
candidacy.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mario Cuomo's promise not to accept a
convention draft will prove most beneficial to Michael Dukakis'
campaign, say prominent Democrats, who believe the New York
governor's vow will finally put an end to speculation over a Cuomo
candidacy.
   ``The last holdouts, the New York City press corps, may now
understand what the rest of the country understands _ the nominee
is in the race,'' Robert Beckel, a political consultant and onetime
adviser to former Vice President Walter Mondale, said Monday.
   Cuomo said this weekend that Democrats should interpret his
earlier statements criticizing any draft efforts to mean he
wouldn't accept a draft for the nomination.
   Dukakis, who is battling Jesse Jackson for front-runner status
and a major share of the 255 delegates at stake in the April 19th
New York primary, is expected to reap the benefits from Cuomo's
statement.
   Nathan Landow, a Maryland developer and major Democratic Party
fund-raiser said Cuomo's decision ``certainly takes some doubt out
of the people's mind who were hoping for an alternative to Dukakis.
I think it will unite the party much faster and bring the focus of
November into a much earlier view.''
   Landow, who is advising Tennesse Sen. Albert Gore Jr., said,
``Gore could benefit from this too. Gore becomes the clear
alternative to Dukakis.''
   The onetime Cuomo supporter said there will be ``a lot of
disappointed Democrats around the country who had a certain glimmer
of hope concerning his candidacy.''
   Former Democratic National Committee chairman John White said he
believed Cuomo from the start when the New York governor said he
was not a candidate, but the statement ``clears the air.''
   White, an adviser to Jackson, said ``whatever plus in (Cuomo's
announcement) has to go to Dukakis.''
   ``Certainly in New York, it helps Dukakis because there was
considerable reluctance for party leaders to get committed. It
frees them and a good many will go to Dukakis,'' he said. ``I think
that's marginal. I don't think it's enough to tip the race one way
or another.''
   One possible delegate, New York City Mayor Edward Koch,
responded to Cuomo's vow with the announcement that he would soon
endorse either Dukakis or Gore. Koch had been preparing to lead a
draft-Cuomo move at the national convention.
   And former New York Rep. Richard Ottinger, a leader of the
draft-Cuomo movement, said he was suspending his effort.
   ``A large number of the uncommitted, a disproportionate share of
those people, felt that Cuomo should run for president,'' said Lee
Miringoff, director of the Marist Institute for Public Opinion. ``A
larger number of those were people who had indicated (in previous
polling) they were supporting Dukakis.''
   The most recent Marist poll said 8 percent of likely New York
Democratic primary voters surveyed said they planned to support a
pro-Cuomo uncommitted slate on the ballot next week.
   While Miringoff said the numbers weren't large, there should be
a shift, in light of Cuomo's latest statements, that would create
``a slight enhancement of the Dukakis advantage'' for the New York
primary.
   The latest Marist poll, conducted last week, had Dukakis the
choice of 47 percent of the Democrats surveyed. Jesse Jackson was
the choice of 31 percent, and Gore 6 percent.
   Cuomo insisted that his ruling out accepting a draft was really
nothing more than what he has been saying for more than a year, but
he said he felt that he had ``to take extra steps to clarify it ...
I'm trying with as much effort as I've ever expended on it to shut
it down, so there's absolutely no question, so it doesn't get
discussed.''
   White said the political necessity that forced Cuomo to make a
clarifying statement reflects the New York governor's strength.
   ``The more he says `no,' the more we seem to court him and want
him,'' White said. ``People are going to go ahead and accept his
statement, but there's going to be a lot of talk ... He's kind of
like the girl who keeps turning you down.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
