<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GraySentencing     04-12 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gray Sentencing,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Cook Sentenced To Death For Murder And Rape Of Two Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT BRAGG, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 22-year-old former Army cook was
sentenced to death Tuesday by a court-martial panel for raping and
murdering two women.
   Ronald A. Gray already had been sentenced to eight life terms in
a separate civilian case after he confessed raping and killing the
two women.
   The six-member court-martial panel returned its unanimous
verdict after about two hours of deliberations. The panel also
reduced Gray from Spec. 4 to private, forfeited all his pay and
ordered him dishonorably discharged from the Army.
   Under the armed forces' Uniform Code of Military Justice, Gray
gets an automatic appeal.
   Gray, a former cook with the 3rd Battalion, 504th Parachute
Infantry Regiment of the 82nd Airborne Division, was convicted last
week of 14 counts of rape, robbery, murder and attempted murder.
   Army lawyers said earlier in the week that the Army's prescribed
form of execution now is lethal injection.
   In the civilian case, tried in Cumberland County Superior Court,
he must serve at least 60 years before being eligible for parole.
   In the court-martial, Gray was convicted of raping and killing
Kimberly Anne Ruggles, 24, a civilian cab driver, on Jan. 6, 1987,
and Laura Lee Vickery Clay, an Army private, on Dec. 15, 1986. Both
women were from Fayetteville.
   Ruggles bled to death after being stabbed seven times. Clay was
shot four times with a .22-caliber pistol that Gray confessed to
stealing.
   He also was convicted of raping and attempting to kill Pvt. Mary
Ann Nameth, 20, who was stabbed three times in the neck on Jan. 3,
1987, in a Fort Bragg barracks. She testified against Gray during
the court-martial and identified him as her assailant.
</TEXT>
