<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     04-12 0995</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,1030</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kennedy item for release at 6 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Kennedy used give-and-take over the
family dinner table to prod his children to excel and he read a
Bible story to them nightly, his daughter Kathleen Townsend recalls
as the 20th anniversary of Kennedy's murder nears.
   Now 36 and practicing environmental law, Mrs. Townsend said in
an interview in the current McCall's magazine that she preferred
not to talk about Kennedy's death on June 6, 1968, while running
for the Democratic nomination for president.
   ``I want to remember the happy times, the vibrancy of his
presence,'' said Mrs. Townsend, who lives in the Baltimore suburb
of Ruxton with her literature-professor husband, David, and three
daughters.
   She said her father's arrival home always touched off tickling
and roughhousing and later everybody in the big family, except for
the very youngest, had dinner together.
   ``Those mealtimes were school away from school, but we loved
them,'' she said. ``My father would toss questions at us about
history. ... If we knew the answers we'd yell them out as though we
were winning a big jackpot in a quiz show. And if we drew blanks,
my father would say quietly, `You can do better than that.' That
made us want to do better.''
   She remembered his telling the children, ``Take the hard course,
not the easy way. Make the tough decisions.''
   She said that around 8:30 p.m. all the children left their
bedrooms at Kennedy's call and sat on the floor at the top of the
stairs.
   ``Before the cross that hung there, my father would read Bible
stories, one each night, from a children's version of the Old
Testament. And we'd sit in total silence, which was unusual for us,
entranced. ...
   ``I never forgot those evenings. Now we read the same Bible
stories every night to our children, who are just as enchanted by
them as we were.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trumpeter Al Hirt is still having problems with
his right hand and arm.
   Hirt, 65, is back in Methodist Hospital, a spokeswoman said
Tuesday, where he spent four days last month for treatment of an
infection in the same hand and arm.
   ``The infection is under control and, although there is some
pain and inflamation of tendons, I expect a full recovery by week's
end,'' said Dr. Michael DeBakey, Hirt's friend and physician.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Birney item for release at 6 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even though she says she's tired of being seen
as ``the perfect mom,'' Actress Meredith Baxter Birney has agreed
to play that role for a seventh season in the popular television
program, ``Family Ties.''
   ``But I'm not the perfect person,'' the 40-year-old mother of
five says in an interview in the May issue of McCall's magazine.
``And we're not the perfect family. Our kids squabble just like any
other kids.''
   Ms. Birney, a runner and a vegetarian, says she puts a lot of
effort into how she looks. ``In my business, the way you look is so
bound up with getting work, with staying employed. ... When you're
in front of the public eye, your past rises up to haunt you.
   ``People see reruns of shows I did five years ago, and they say
`Look how young she looks there.' You're in constant competition
with your former self,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEVILLE, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Juan Carlos and Queen Sofia toured
the construction site for Expo 92, giving a royal boost to the
international exposition's image in Spain four years before the
opening date.
   The royal couple visited the Expo site Tuesday on Cartuja
Island, across the Guadalquivir River from Seville's historic
district, and inaugurated a traveling exhibit and model of the
513-acre grounds.
   ``The Expo is completely irreversible. It will be done and done
well,'' said one top exposition official, who asked not to be
named. ``The king's visit is the definitive show of backing.''
   The official said he wanted to dispel rumors that the exposition
was in trouble following press reports of an internal squabble
between two Expo commission members.
   Expo 92 and Barcelona's 1992 Summer Olympic Games are the
centerpieces of a government plan to spread a message of a modern,
democratic Spain on the 500th anniversary of Columbus' voyage
across the Atlantic.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDs: This also moved on sports wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlanta Braves officials say Carolyn King has
broken two barriers as the team's ballpark organist this year _ she
is the first black organist and the youngest full-time organist in
major league baseball.
   Miss King, an 18-year-old senior at Avondale High School, ``can
play anything,'' said Miles McRea, the Braves' director of
promotions. ``She's just outstanding. Not many people can walk
right up to an organ as complex as the one we have and just start
playing. She did it.''
   During tryouts for the job, Miss King beat out six other
candidates, including Lowery Ballew, the Braves' organist for the
past 10 years.
   She uses no printed music. ``I play by ear,'' she said. ``After
I first hear a song, I normally can learn to play it between five
minutes and three hours. I'd say classical music is one of my
favorites, and so are songs from children's cartoon shows.''
   Miss King also is a member of her high school band, sings and
plays organ at Ebenezer Baptist Church, and teaches music to nine
students.
   ``Even though she's going away to college somewhere this fall,
we can work something out for the future,'' said McRea. ``She's
great.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Olav V of Norway, Europe's oldest reigning
monarch and a cousin of Queen Elizabeth II, is in Britain for a
four-day state visit.
   The 84-year-old king was formally presented Tuesday by Queen
Elizabeth to Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and other
dignitaries, then taken in a five-carriage procession to Windsor
Castle to greet 10 other members of the royal family.
</TEXT>
