<HEAD>With AM-Oscars Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cher Takes First Oscar For ``Moonstruck''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cher completed her transformation from pop
singer to top actress at the 60th Annual Academy Awards when she
won the Oscar for her role as the superstitious young widow of
``Moonstruck.''
   ``I want to really say something,'' she said when she accepted
the award Monday night. ``When I was little my mother said, `I want
you to be something.'''
   ``I don't think that this means that I am somebody, but I guess
I'm on my way,'' Cher said. She was nominated by the Academy once
before for ``Silkwood.''
   Cher, known for her outrageous garb at past Oscars, was slightly
subdued this time in a black sequined gown with see-through netting
and strategically placed spangles.
   Backstage, she said of her getup: ``I think Theda Bara would
probably be proud of me,'' referring to the famed ``vamp'' of the
silent screen.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Michael Douglas Says Not Many Thought He Could Play The Role</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Douglas caught praise for his
performance in ``Fatal Attraction,'' but it was his role as a
ruthless inside trader in ``Wall Street'' that won him his first
acting Oscar.
   Douglas credited ``Wall Street'' director Oliver Stone ``for
having the courage to cast me in a part that not many people
thought I could play.''
   Douglas described the character of Wall Street king Gordon Gekko
as ``the best part that I've ever had in my career.''
   He previously won an Oscar as co-producer of ``One Flew Over the
Cuckoo's Nest,'' best picture of 1975.
   Douglas also was considered by the Motion Picture Academy for
his performance in the psycho-thriller ``Fatal Attraction,'' which
was nominated for best picture, but the actors branch decided to
nominate him for ``Wall Street.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Olympia Dukakis Accepts Award, Cheers On Cousin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Olympia Dukakis used her best supporting
actress Oscar to cheer on another contender _ first cousin and
presidential hopeful Michael Dukakis, proclaiming backstage, ``It's
the year of the Dukaki!''
   Upon accepting the statuette Monday night, Miss Dukakis urged on
the Massachusetts governor in his race for the Democratic
presidential nomination: ``OK Michael, let's go!''
   The nomination was the first for Miss Dukakis, who has long been
a working actress in theater, films and television, but failed to
reach a national audience until she played Cher's wise, enduring
Italian mother in ``Moonstruck.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Sean Connery Wins Oscar For Role As Chicago Cop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For more than a half-dozen films Sean Connery
was the quintessential British spy, but it was his role as a gritty
Chicago cop in ``The Untouchables'' that earned him his first
Academy Award.
   ``Patience is truly a virtue,'' he said, drawing a standing
ovation.
   In a 30-year film career, Connery has appeared in about 40
pictures, including the James Bond films ``Dr. No,''
``Goldfinger,'' and ``Never Say Never Again.'' This was his first
nomination.
   He ended his acceptance speech by saying: ``If such a thing as a
wish accompanied this award, mine would be that we ended the
writer's strike.''
   The strike by the Writers Guild of America against movie and
television producers is in its fifth week.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>``The Last Emperor'' Sweeps Awards Ceremony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Last Emperor,'' a mammoth epic which
suprised the film world by taking foreign cameras into China's
Forbidden City, won nine of nine Academy Awards nominations,
including best director and best picture.
   ``I must give a Chinese kow-tow to the Academy. This is one of
the strongest emotions of my life, and I can't hide it,'' said
Bernardo Bertolucci, who directed the film about China's boy ruler
Pu Yi.
   Bertolucci took the Oscar for best director, the first Italian
director to win in this category. The film also won for art
direction, cinematography, sound, film editing, original score,
costume design, adapted screenplay and picture, but no awards for
acting.
   It was the most Oscars won by a single movie since 1962, when
``West Side Story'' took 10 awards.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Billy Wilder Honored As 25th Recipient Of Thalberg Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Film legend Billy Wilder, the first person to
ever win three Oscars in one night, for ``The Apartment,'' is the
25th recipient of the Motion Picture Academy's Irving G. Thalberg
Award.
   Wilder, 81, wrote, directed or produced such classics as ``The
Lost Weekend,'' ``Stalag 17,'' ``Sunset Boulevard'' and ``Some Like
It Hot.'' During a nearly 60-year movie career, he has been
nominated for an Oscar 21 times and has taken the statuette home
six times.
   ``As I look back, I've lived a charmed life,'' Wilder said at
Monday's Oscar show.
   The Thalberg Award goes to ``a creative producer whose body of
work reflects a consistently high quality of motion picture
production.'' It is given only when the Academy of Motion Picture
Arts and Sciences board of directors decides there is a deserving
recipient.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>``Babette's Feast'' Named Best Foreign Film</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Babette's Feast,'' a film about two pious,
unmarried sisters who take a political refugee into their home, is
the first Danish film to win an Oscar, honored Monday as best
foreign language film.
   ``I am very grateful for this honor and I want to thank you
Academy members from the bottom of my heart,'' said director
Gabriel Axel.
   ``Babette's Feast'' portrayed the lives of sisters who took in a
political refugee from the French revolution named Babette. The
refugee, a former world-class chef, later repays their kindness by
devoting her winnings from a lottery to creation of a sumptuous
feast.
   Also nominated were ``Au Revoir Les Enfants,'' France; ``Course
Completed,'' Spain; ``The Family,'' Italy; and ``Pathfinder,''
Norway.
</TEXT>
