<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 1534EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Refuseniks     04-12 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Refuseniks,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>35 Jews Seeking to Emigrate Reported Arrested at Demonstration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 35 Jews on Tuesday after a
demonstration in central Moscow in which the asked authorities to
explain why they haven't been allowed to emigrate, a Jewish
activist said.
   Bella Gulko said she and 45 other refuseniks _ those who have
been denied permission to emigrate _ went to the reception office
of the Communist Party Central Committee seeking promised
explanations on why they have been unable to obtain exit visas. No
one would receive them, she said.
   The group of refuseniks had alerted the Central Committee on
Monday of their plan to visit, citing a pledge given them by party
and government officials at a March 1 meeting that they would be
given a reply within 40 days, she said.
   When the refuseniks were denied a meeting with officials, they
went across the street from the Central Committee building and
stood there, some holding placards demanding exit visas, said Ms.
Gulko, 48, who has been seeking for nine years to emigrate.
   Three buses then pulled up to the group, and 35 were arrested,
she said.
   ``The police treated us roughly, ripping up our signs and
pulling us and twisting us by the arms,'' Ms. Gulko said. None of
the demonstrators was injured, she said.
   The Jews were taken to two police stations, where some were held
for more than five hours, she said. A police complaint was filed
against the refuseniks accusing them of holding an illegal
demonstration, she said.
   Two of the protesters were fined the equivalent of $16 by a
Moscow neighborhood court. The others requested legal
representation, and were told they would go on trial later, she
said.
   New regulations that went into effect last year require Soviet
authorities to tell applicants for emigration why their request has
been rejected.
   Jewish activists, however, say the rules are ignored or that
overly general reasons are given that don't tell applicants for an
exit visa exactly why their request has been refused.
   Ms. Gulko formerly was employed as an engineer specializing in
ventilation and air conditioning systems. She said she has never
been given a specific reason for why she has been unable to get an
exit visa.
   She also said she never engaged in secret work for the
government, which Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze has said
is the sole legitimate reason that can cause rejection of an
application to leave the Soviet Union.
   Last year, as relations between the Soviet Union and the West
improved, more than 8,000 Soviet Jews were permitted to emigrate,
nearly eight times as many as the year before and the highest total
since 1981.
   Among those who have left in recent months are longtime Jewish
activists and refuseniks Josef Begun, Vladimir Slepak and Ida
Nudel. Jewish activists say thousands, if not tens of thousands, of
Jews want to emigrate but have been turned down.
</TEXT>
