<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     04-12 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor, Student Unrest Swells in South Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PUPYONG, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of striking workers closed
down the country's second largest auto plant Tuesday, and
anti-government students battled riot police at six campuses
nationwide.
   About 4,000 workers at Daewoo Motor Co. began a sit-in at their
plant in Pupyong near Seoul. Union leaders are demanding a 26
percent increase in monthly salaries at the company, a joint
venture with the U.S. General Motors Corp.
   Labor leaders at the Pupyong auto plant also said more than
9,000 other workers joined their indefinite strike Tuesday at four
company plants near Seoul and in the southern port city of Pusan.
   About 1,000 students from 10 schools battled riot police at
Seoul National University after vowing to lead a unified
anti-government movement before National Assembly elections on
April 26. Police fired barrages of tear gas at about 600 students
shouting ``overthrow the dictatorship together with workers.''
   A policeman was seriously injured in clashes with hundreds of
students at a seminary near Pupyong after a campus rally supporting
labor rights, the Yonhap news agency reported.
   Labor disputes, mostly peaceful, have escalated in recent weeks.
Government officials say workers in several major industries are
now braced for new strikes.
   Union leaders have urged workers to shun violence and political
demands.
   However, near downtown Seoul Tuesday, riot police carried off
400 workers from Daewoo Precision Industries Ltd. who tried to
march into headquarters of the Daewoo conglomerate.
   No injuries were reported.
   Violent protests battered many Korean companies last summer
after student-led demonstrations prompted the government to promise
major reforms, including December's presidential election. Roh
Tae-woo won the election over a divided opposition, and government
opponents have been escalating their campaign to topple him.
   The dispute at Daewoo has delayed delivery of cars for export,
mostly to the United States.
   Workers also continued their two-day-old strike Tuesday at
Daewoo Shipbuilding and Heavy Machinery Ltd., the nation's
second-largest shipyard, on southern Koje island.
</TEXT>
