<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain-Paintings     04-12 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Paintings,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spain to Pay $177 Million for Loaned Paintings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will pay $177 million to
borrow and exhibit more than 700 Swiss-owned paintings in its
capital for 10 years, a newspaper reported Tuesday.
   The report in Spain's leading daily El Pais came less than a
week after Baron Hans Heinrich Thyssen-Bornemisza, whose trust owns
the paintings, signed a loan agreement with Culture Minister Javier
Solana.
   The government and press have hailed the accord as a coup that
cements Spain's reputation as an international art center. The
paintings come from a 1,600-painting collection owned by Tyssen's
trust and valued at $2 billion.
   The loaned paintings have not been announced, but they are
expected to include some by great artists in the 13th to 20th
century collection.
   The Duke of Badajoz, King Juan Carlos' brother-in-law, served as
intermediary in the accord and said earlier it could pave the way
to make Spain the collection's permanent home.
   Under the agreement, Spain will pay $44 million to set up a
national trust, which will in turn pay Thyssen $4.4 million a year
in rent.
   The newspaper, citing unnamed Culture Ministry officials, said
the government would also pay to refurbish and maintain
Villahermosa Palace, a 19th-century building that will house the
paintings. The palace faces the famous Prado Museum.
</TEXT>
