<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CatBan     04-12 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cat Ban,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catty Uproar Over Rare Rodent and Bird</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN RAFAEL, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City planners thought they had the
perfect solution when a developer sought to build homes next to a
marsh where endangered species of mice and birds live: Ban all cats
from the homes.
   But that was before the cat lovers began phoning, and one city
council member says he'll bring up the issue at next Monday's
council meeting.
   ``It's unconstitutional,'' said City Councilman Gary Frugoli.
``We'll be the laughingstock of everybody.''
   ``It's ridiculous that the city's trying to restrict people from
having animals ...,'' he said. ``How do we enforce it? Are we going
to have police officers out there checking to see if they have
cats?''
   But it's not so ridiculous, countered City Planning Director
Anne Moore, who said the city imposed the ban at the suggestion of
the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
   The homes are to be built near swampy grasslands by Gallinas
Creek in this suburb about 20 miles north of San Francisco. The
swampland is home to the salt marsh harvest mouse and the clapper
rail bird, both of which are on state and federal endangered
species lists.
   Permits for the 224-home development were issued March 29 after
the city Planning Commission approved construction on condition
that felines be banned.
   ``There's definitely a logic to this,'' Ms. Moore said. ``This
is the mouse that has stopped development all over San Francisco
Bay when it is found in an area where development is proposed.''
   Ray Royce, chief of subdivisions in the California Real Estate
Department, said the cat ban could be the first in the nation to
affect private homes.
   ``I don't know of a similar proposal,'' he said.
   The developer, Southwest Diversified, had no problems with the
ban.
   It's a ``reasonable compromise'' between the environment and the
need for housing, said Richard Garlinghouse, senior vice president
of Southwest Diversified. ``Twenty years ago we would have simply
gone in and bulldozed.''
   The executive said he has agreed that a section of land that
lies between the housing project and the marsh will remain wild, as
sort of a buffer zone.
   Ms. Moore, who acknowledges getting some irate phone calls from
cat lovers, praised the developer for ``being very sensitive to the
environmental situation. It was not an issue with the developer.
They said `fine.'''
   Gail Kobetich, field supervisor of the federal wildlife
service's Sacramento endangered species office, said that cats
``are one of our major concerns. They're predators.''
   Negotiations aimed at saving the endangered mouse are going on
over several planned developments on the east and south sides of
San Francisco Bay, said Kobetich.
   ``We generally arrive at a reasonable solution,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
