<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Jews     04-12 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Jews,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McGovern Defends Jackson to Jews</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Democratic presidential nominee George
McGovern told Jewish voters in New York on Tuesday that Jesse
Jackson is neither anti-Semitic nor anti-Israel and should not be
judged ``on the indiscretions of an earlier time.''
   ``It is not worthy of the great traditions of Judaism for its
adherents to been seen as unforgiving toward a black man who is
extending the hand of reconciliation and peace,'' McGovern said in
a statement.
   As the 1972 Democratic presidential nominee called for
peace-making, however, leaders of two major Jewish groups slammed
Jackson's campaign manager for saying they wanted to meet with
Jackson simply to harass him.
   The statement by Jackson aide Gerald Austin is ``false,
unfortunate and offensive,'' said Malcolm Hoenlein, executive
director of the Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish
Organizations.
   ``In view of his theme of healing, we are dismayed that the
Jackson campaign seems to have made a decision not to meet with the
leadership of the New York Jewish community,'' said Lester Pollack,
president of the Jewish Community Relations Council of New York,
even as the invitation to speak was issued again.
   Jackson alone among the three remaining major Democratic
candidates has not accepted the invitation of the two groups to
speak before the April 19 New York primary. Jewish voters usually
account for up to one-quarter of the Democratic primary voters in
the state.
   The conference of presidents is made up of 44 national Jewish
groups. The council is a coordinating body for 59 Jewish
organizations in the New York metropolitan area.
   McGovern sought to reduce some of the tensions by writing what
he called an ``open letter to the Jewish voters of New York.'' He
said he is not endorsing Jackson.
   ``I have no doubt that Jesse Jackson is free of anti-Semitism _
a bigotry totally at odds with his years of passionate devotion to
civil rights,'' McGovern wrote. ``I do not want to see this
steadily improving political leader judged on the indiscretions of
an earlier time rather than the more mature conduct he demonstrates
today.''
   Three items in particular were addressed by McGovern: Jackson's
``views on the Middle East, his earlier association with the
intemperate Louis Farrakhan and a slurring reference to New York
City as `Hymietown.'''
   ``I fully understand the concerns of Jews on these matters.
Indeed, four years ago, I took public issue with Jesse because of
this,'' McGovern said.
   During his 1984 campaign, Jackson referred to New York as
`Hymietown'' and Jews as ``Hymie'' in what he thought was a private
conversation.
   ``With reference to the `Hymietown' slur, Jackson has long ago
expressed his regrets over this unfortunate language,'' McGovern
wrote. ``He also clearly ended his association with Farrakhan some
years ago.''
   Farrakhan, the leader of the Nation of Islam, referred to
Judaism as a ``gutter religion'' in 1984, when he was a Jackson
backer.
   On the Middle East, McGovern said that Jackson's positions are
not extreme, that he can be ``a reconciling force in that
hate-ridden region.''
   ``If I were a Jew with special concerns for Israel, I would not
be disturbed by Jesse Jackson's positions,'' McGovern said.
   The 1972 nominee said that Jackson's convictions are ``close to
those'' of some Israeli leaders. He named Abba Eban, Eser Weisman
and Shimon Peres.
   ``It is true that Jackson has met with PLO Leader Yasser Arafat,
favors direct negotiations between Palestinians and the Israelis,
supports the concept of self-determination for Palestinians and the
exchange of Israeli-occupied territory for peace,'' McGovern said.
``These position, with which I agree, do not threaten Israel. Quite
the contrary, they are essential conditions of justice and a secure
peace for Israelis as well as Palestinians.''
</TEXT>
