<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bradys     04-12 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bradys,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jim Brady, Wife Describe Plight Of Head Injury Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential press secretary James Brady and
his wife Sarah asked Congress on Tuesday to expand home health care
and other services vital to head injury victims, describing vividly
their own plight since Brady was shot.
   ``My name is Jim Brady. I am a seven-year survivor of a
traumatic brain injury,'' Brady said evenly as a hush fell over the
packed Senate hearing room. ``I know only too well the tragedy
surrounding a head injury. I am pleased that you are taking a keen
look at our problems.''
   Brady was shot during the 1981 assassination attempt on
President Reagan and at one point was reported dead. He delivered
his brief statement to the Senate Labor and Human Resources
subcommittee on the handicapped from a wheelchair, with little
expression in his face or voice.
   Though clearly not fully recovered, Brady demonstrated during
his wife's testimony that his famous sense of humor survives in
some form.
   ``Speaking as a family member, I can tell you that going through
that initial trauma is surely difficult, but somehow you do,'' Mrs.
Brady said.
   ``It was difficult for me, too,'' Brady interjected dryly,
winning a roar of laughter from the audience, which included many
head trauma victims.
   Mrs. Brady said Brady had received first-rate care, even down to
a 24-hour Secret Service guard by his hospital room door. ``That
was so I couldn't sneak out,'' Brady interrupted.
   The rude shock came when Brady was released from the hospital
and there was no support network, his wife said. She said she felt
trepidation about facing the situation alone and had no one with
whom to discuss the best way to handle Brady's rehabilitation.
   Under questioning, Mrs. Brady said her family's No. 1 need is
for home care for her husband, who cannot be left alone during a
short shopping trip much less the many hours of a full-time workday.
   ``Jim for example is not able to get out of a chair by himself,
and would not be able to leave our home in the event of a fire,''
she said. ``It's very frustrating to see that home health care is
not always covered'' by government or private insurance.
   Mrs. Brady said families and survivors also need support and
counseling programs to cope with the tragedy that has shattered so
many lives _ children, parents, spouses and the victims themselves.
   She said the shooting has had a devastating impact on Brady's
elderly mother and his 9-year-old son. As for Brady himself, she
said, ``He laughs and keeps a sense of humor up, but I know that he
thinks daily of what he could have been doing.''
</TEXT>
