<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Tenor,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tenor Wins Award to Sing in Sweden</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ben Heppner, a 32-year-old heldentenor, or
heroic tenor, has been awarded the first Birgit Nilsson Award,
which means he will make his debut at the Royal Opera of Sweden in
Stockholm.
   Judges chose Heppner on April 10 at a Metropolitan Opera concert
by the 11 singers who won this year's Metropolitan Opera Auditions
for Young Singers.
   Heppner lives in Ontario, Canada. He's a native of Dawson Creek,
British Columbia. In Stockholm he will star in Wagner's
``Lohengrin.''
   A gala concert at Carnegie Hall this Saturday night, to be
attended by King Carl XVI Gustaf and Queen Silvia of Sweden, will
raise the money to establish the self-perpetuating Birgit Nilsson
Prize. The concert is to honor the Swedish Wagnerian soprano and
the Swedish vocal tradition in America which began with Jenny Lind.
</TEXT>
