<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis     04-12 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Campaigns Among Jews in Brooklyn</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis campaigned in a
conservative Jewish community Tuesday, declining to criticize rival
Jesse Jackson despite shouted invitations from some in the crowd.
   Dukakis, seeking Jewish support in next Tuesday's New York
presidential primary, met privately with Jewish leaders in the
Borough Park neighborhood of Brooklyn and later spoke to hundreds
of Hassidic and orthodox Jews who filled the street outside.
   It was the second day of meetings with Jewish leaders for the
Massachusetts governor, who came to the neighborhood just hours
after facing rivals Albert Gore Jr. and Jackson in a locally
televised debate.
   Gore earlier had said Dukakis has shown ``enthusiasm'' for
creation of a Palestinian state in the Middle East, something some
Jewish leaders oppose. Dukakis denied that during the debate.
   As Dukakis took questions from reporters in Brooklyn, some young
Hassidic Jews in the crowd shouted to him asking what he thought
about Jackson _ who has drawn the ire of some Jews for his
positions regarding Palestinians in the occupied West Bank and for
his 1984 reference to New York as ``Hymietown.''
   ``I have some disagreements with Rev. Jackson; I have some
disagreements with Sen. Gore,'' Dukakis said to reporters. ``I'm
going to run a strong campaign that puts my best foot forward ...
in the hope I can win suppport of the people of New York.''
   Dukakis referred to his own heritage as the son of Greek
immigrants and praised the largely Jewish community as ``a model of
what a caring community is all about, a recognition that we're all
in this together.''
   New York's primary campaign has focused on Middle East issues,
reflecting the fact that Jews generally make up close to
one-quarter of the Democratic primary electorate.
   Dukakis said he also planned to campaign in black and Hispanic
communities, and he went from Brooklyn to a health clinic in a
predominantly Hispanic section of New York City's Upper West Side.
There he talked of his commitment to basic health insurance and day
care, addressing several dozen people, most of them women who work
at the clinic and their children.
   In Borough Park, he was strongly endorsed by the council's
leader, Rabbi Morris Schmidman, who said a Palestinian state would
be ``a dagger at the heart and soul of Israel.'' Dukakis has said a
Palestinian state should be a matter of negotiations for Israel and
its neighbors.
   Also appearing with him was the area's congressman, Rep. Stephen
Solarz. He praised the work of Dukakis' wife Kitty as a member of a
national commission working to honor victims and survivors of the
Holocaust, ``of which there are more survivors here in Borough Park
and Brooklyn than any other city'' in America.
   The rabbi called Dukakis ``the best choice'' and said, ``I urge
my friends to follow me'' in voting for him.
   Some in the crowd, however, expressed reservations.
   Daniel Cohen, a Hebrew teacher, said, ``He was very vague in
regard to Israel. ... I find him hazy.''
   Several said they liked Gore, who has taken a strongly
pro-Israel stance recently, but they voiced concern that votes for
Gore would have the effect of enhancing Jackson's position in the
three-way primary.
   ``There is a fear of Jackson,'' said Cohen.
   A woman from Borough Park who would identify herself only as
Rachel said she liked Gore but ``we'd rather have Dukakis than to
give too much power to Jackson.''
</TEXT>
