<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PolygamistTrial     04-12 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polygamist Trial,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clan Leader Hoped For Confrontation, U.S. Attorney Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A polygamist clan leader bombed a Mormon
chapel to bring about a ``final confrontation'' he believed would
trigger the downfall of church and state, a federal prosecutor said
Tuesday.
   U.S. Attorney Brent Ward's opening statement began the trial of
four clan members facing charges relating to the Jan. 16 chapel
bombing and a 13-day standoff that ended Jan. 28 in gunfire that
killed a state corrections officer.
   In addition to opening statements, the first witnesses were
called to testify.
   And U.S. District Judge Bruce Jenkins denied a defense motion to
move the trial out of Utah.
   Ward for the first time officially identified John Timothy
Singer as the clan member authorities believe killed Corrections
Lt. Fred House when officers attempted to capture clan leader Addam
Swapp and his brother with attack dogs.
   Singer, 21, son of clan matriarch Vickie Singer, has not been
charged in the death. State authorities say they will file murder
charges following the federal trial.
   ``Vickie Singer and Addam Swapp made it clear there would be no
surrender and that the nation, church and state would have to be
destroyed first,'' said Ward, who detailed the bombing of the Kamas
Stake Center and the standoff at the clan's Marion homestead.
   ``Evidence and witnesses will show the events were part of a
pattern of criminal activity having a common purpose,'' Ward said.
``Evidence will show in this case that Addam Swapp was the bomber.''
   ``You will hear evidence that this was more than just a bombing
_ that it was an invitation to a violent confrontation,'' Ward said.
   The clan blamed the state and the Mormon church for various
problems, including the death nine years ago of Mrs. Singer's
husband, John, who was killed in a confrontation with police.
   Swapp, 27, married to two of Mrs. Singer's daughters, is charged
with seven counts and Mrs. Singer, 45, eight counts. John Timothy
Singer and Swapp's brother, Jonathan Swapp, 21, are charged with
attempted murder of federal agents, assault on federal officers and
two firearms violations.
   Swapp and Mrs. Singer face the same counts, plus use of an
explosive to damage the chapel and use and possession of a bomb.
Mrs. Singer also is charged with possession of a sawed-off shotgun.
   Using an aerial photograph and a surveyor's diagram, Ward also
walked jurors through the sequence of events leading up to the
clan's shootout with police.
   Kathryn Collard, representing Mrs. Singer, said there was no
evidence specifically linking her client to the eight charges.
``Mrs. Singer's defense in this case is simple. It is the truth,''
she said. ``There was not anything so much as a threatening gesture
from Vickie Singer.''
   John Timothy Singer's attorney, Fred Metos, urged the jury to
look closely at the attempted murder charge and determine whether
his client had the malice and intent to kill.
   The government, he said, ``must show that John Timothy Singer,
or whoever did the shooting at these officers, had the specific
intent to cause their death.''
   ``Except he will tell you that he had no intention of harming
anyone. He just wanted to keep the dogs off his brother-in-law and
Jonathan Swapp,'' Metos said.
   Attorneys for the Swapp brothers reserved their opening
statements for later.
   The government called its first two witnesses: a couple who live
across the highway from the bombed church building. They testified
about hearing the blast and later finding the damage.
</TEXT>
