<1ST_LINE>u i AM-HamadiTrial     04-12 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi Trial,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TWA Hijack Suspect to Be Tried Before Youth Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials said Tuesday that a
juvenile court will try a Lebanese man charged in a TWA hijacking
in which a U.S. sailor was killed.
   If convicted in the youth court, Mohammed Hamadi would face a
maximum 10-year term. He had been scheduled to go on trial next
month as an adult and could have drawn a maximum life sentence.
   In West Germany defendants under 21 are tried in youth court.
Hamadi's 21st birthday came two days before the hijacking on June
15, 1985, according to the Frankfurt state court.
   ``However, a possibility exists that the perpetration of the
crime that he is accused of may have begun before June 13, 1985,
and goes back to the time of his adolescence,'' a court statement
said.
   ``Therefore, the case has been turned over to the youth court,''
it said.
   Hamadi was charged in February with murder, hostage-taking and
other crimes stemming from the 1985 hijacking of a TWA jetliner to
Beirut during which U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem was killed and
39 U.S. citizens were held hostage for 17 days.
   Moving the case to a youth court means the news media could be
barred from Hamadi's trial and proceedings may not begin for
months, authorities said.
   Judicial sources in Frankfurt said they believed Hamadi's trial
was not likely to start before the end of the year.
   ``The Hesse state youth court will now need time to study the
case files before it can decide on when Mohammed Hamadi's trial
will start,'' the court statement said.
   A federal Justice Ministry spokesman who spoke on condition of
anonymity said the youth court could decide to exclude the press
from Hamadi's trial. He said the decision would not be made until
the trial begins.
   Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt airport on Jan. 13, 1987,
carrying liquid explosives and false documents.
   Last year, the United States asked for Hamadi's extradition on
air piracy and murder charges.
   The West German government refused the request after the
kidnapping in Beirut of West Germans Rudolf Cordes and Alfred
Schmidt in January 1987. It said he would be tried in West Germany
instead.
   Defense attorneys in Duesseldorf gave their closing arguments
Tuesday in the case of Hamadi's brother, Abbas.
   Abbas Hamadi is charged with kidnapping the two West Germans in
an attempt to force West German authorities to release his brother.
   Schmidt was released by his captors in September in what they
said was a ``goodwill gesture,'' but Cordes is still being held.
</TEXT>
