<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 2022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AviationAlliance     04-12 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aviation Alliance,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aviation Interests Form Coalition to Get More Airports,
Controllers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leaders of often-feuding factions in
American aviation joined forces Tuesday to fight for more airports
and air traffic control support to meet the needs of commercial and
private air transportation.
   ``Unless we modernize the (air traffic system) quickly, we'll
choke off growth to the detriment of all,'' said Robert Crandall,
chairman of American Airlines.
   Crandall was among five airline chief executives, and leaders of
groups representing aircraft manufacturers, business flyers,
private and commercial pilots and airport officials who called a
news conference to announce a new organization to promote the
expansion of airspace and airport capacity.
   The group, calling itself Partnership for Improved Air Travel,
envisions spending up to $15 million over the next two years to
publicize the need for more airports and an improve air traffic
control system.
   The executives said they hoped to enlist the support of the
traveling public to pressure Congress into providing more funds for
an expansion of aviation capacity. Although some ``modest''
increase in aviation taxes might be needed, most of the additional
money would come from funds now bottled up in the federal aviation
trust fund, the coalition leaders said.
   The Reagan administration has denied repeatedly that any money
is being held back and has argued that the surplus in the $5
billion aviation trust fund is only temporary.
   The group listed as founding members all of the major U.S. air
carriers, aircraft manufacturers and 16 other organizations from
aviation labor unions to airport operators.
   ``The nation has not yet made a commitment to create an
(aviation) system that can efficiently meet today's demand and
anticipate tomorrow's,'' said Herbert Kelleher, chairman both of
Southwest Airlines and of the new coalition.
   He and other airline executives said that unless the airspace
and ground capacity is expanded, flight delays and congestion will
not only continue but become more serious each year. The result
will be government-imposed constraints that will translate into
higher air fares, the executives suggested.
   The coalition voiced many of the same complaints heard before
from the aviation industry: too few air traffic controllers are
being hired and trained, federal efforts to modernize the air
traffic control technology is way behind schedule, there are too
few airports and the Federal Aviation Administration needs to be
restructured because it is hamstrung by bureacratic restrictions.
   ``There's not enough manpower, there are too few facilities,
equipment is outdated and the (the air traffic) system's management
structure is ill-suited to its mission,'' said American Airlines'
Crandall.
   Kellerer alluded to the ``unique alliance'' that is represented
by the coalition, which includes not only the largest air carriers
but also groups representing aviation labor and the pilots of
small, general aviation aircraft.
   ``We all share a common ground in wanting to modernize the
(aviation) system,'' added Kellerer.
   Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley briefly address the group
and acknowledged that the federal government ``cannot keep up with
the rapidly changing industry'' spawned by airline deregulation.
``We are ill-equipped to that kind of dynamic,'' he said.
   Burnley in the past has called for Congress to enact legislation
that would allow the FAA to streamline its procurement procedures
and personnel policies so that they may better react to sudden
changes in the aviation industry.
</TEXT>
