<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 1802EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DallasPolice Bjt   04-12 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dallas Police, Bjt,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Chief Resigns After Embattled Tenure</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0800 to CORRECT keyword to conform with
AM-News Digest.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DN7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By READ MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weary Police Chief Billy Prince said Tuesday he
is quitting a department in turmoil over public accountability, the
treatment of minorities and slayings of officers in a city he
claims breeds cop-haters.
   Prince came into office six years ago a young reformer but left
an entrenched insider. He tried to curb the use of deadly force but
presided over one of the bloodiest times in department history
before deciding the tension was too much.
   ``I woke up Easter Sunday and just didn't feel good about
returning,'' Prince said at a news conference. ``I told my wife
then, `I think it's time for me to go.'''
   Prince, 45, said he was stepping down immediately but would
serve in an advisory role through the summer. City Manager Richard
Knight appointed first Assistant Police Chief Louie C. Caudell as
interim chief in the nation's seventh-largest city.
   In recent months, Prince had come under fire for criticizing
City Council members and opposing efforts to increase the
accountability of a department embattled over recent police
shootings of black residents.
   At the request of local minority groups, the U.S. House
subcommittee on criminal justice held a day-long hearing in May
1987 into the department's use of deadly force but did not issue a
report.
   Within minutes of Prince's announcement, black City Council
members who have been critics of the department called for a black
chief, and insisted the new chief be an outsider. Caudell is white.
   Police and city leaders say Prince leaves a legacy of tension
that will mark the search for a new chief, the continuing struggle
over a citizens' review board and perhaps even the 1989 race for
mayor.
   Supporters of Prince, including one law-and-order city
councilman already talking about running for mayor, criticized
Mayor Annette Strauss and called the retiring chief a scapegoat who
was ``hounded out of office.''
   The mayor denied Prince was forced out, and the 24-year Dallas
police veteran said his decision to resign was ``totally my own.''
   Monica Smith, head of the Dallas Police Association, said Prince
was a casualty of the recent deaths of several officers, not of
political infighting. She saw more trouble on the horizon over
Prince's successor.
   The chief angered many opponents with an outburst in January
after a homeless black vagrant shot white Officer John Glenn Chase
in a downtown parking lot.
   He went on television to proclaim that city leaders' criticism
of his department had created a public so hostile that such a death
was inevitable. He then refused to back down even after Strauss
demanded an apology.
   Knight, who is black, also warned Prince against making public
remarks about the council.
   The department already had been facing criticism for the police
shootings of two black people.
   A 70-year-old black woman was shot to death by an officer
responding to a burglary call at her home in October 1986. After
Prince fired the officer, the Dallas Police Association passed a
``no confidence'' vote on the chief.
   Police also shot dead a teen-age black girl during a drug raid
at an apartment complex in November 1987.
   Prince sharpened his differences with the City Council last year
when he lobbied against an expansion of the powers of the review
board to evaluate the use of police force and the creation of a
special office to review minority hirings and promotions. The
council introduced both changes in December.
   The feud with the City Council and the Chase shooting has
produced a backlash of support for the police, and the DPA is
seeking to go over the heads of council members and force a
referendum on the review board.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
