<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL Auction,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PTL Tries To Auction Bakkers' House, But Nobody Bids</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGA CAY, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The troubled PTL ministry tried Tuesday to
auction the home used by former leaders Jim and Tammy Bakker, but
there were no bidders for the plush, million-dollar mansion.
   The auction of that home and eight other properties, chiefly
homes used by other ministry officials, raised only a fraction of
the $4 million that ministry officials had hoped for.
   The ministry accepted bids on five of the nine properties,
raising about $596,500. The Bakker home attracted no bids, bids on
two other properties were deemed insufficient, and a $425,000 bid
on former PTL President Richard Dortch's home is still being
considered, said PTL Trustee David Clark.
   Clark said the setback means the ministry based in nearby Fort
Mill will have to re-examine its options for raising $5.3 million
by a May 2 bankruptcy court deadline.
   ``I believe that we will make it in one way or another,'' Clark
said.
   The 9,300-square-foot lakeside house used by the Bakker and his
wife before he resigned a year ago amid a sex scandal boasts three
kitchens, four bedrooms and 5{ bathrooms.
   The grounds include a two-story, heated and air-conditioned
playhouse; a guardhouse; boardwalks to a white, sandy beach on
nearby Lake Wylie; and a large dock where the Bakkers once kept
their 58-foot houseboat and a small power cruiser.
   It was built in 1976 and enlarged four times after PTL bought it
in 1981 to be used as a parsonage by the Bakkers and their two
children.
   Auctioneer Rodney L. Robinson opened the sale of the Bakkers'
house by asking for $900,000. He stopped the auction when his
asking price fell to $500,000 without any takers. The house was
valued at about $1 million.
   ``We didn't get an offer that I thought was substantial enough
to open the bidding,'' Robinson said afterward. About 40 bidders
participated in the 30-minute auction.
   One of the rejected bids was $900,000 for 33 acres of
undeveloped land. Clark said that property and  No official cause has been
given for the explosions that ripped
through the ammunition depot, sending rockets showering across the
cities.
   The Los Angeles Times reported Tuesday that agents from the
pro-Soviet government in Afghanistan were apparently responsible.
   According to the newspaper, the blast was caused by three
incendiary devices carried to the ammunition dump by trucks bearing
Afghan license plates and equipped with time fuses. They were
exploded in sequence, the newspaper said.
   The newspaper, quoting unidentified sources, said Pakistani
military experts had told U.S. officials that this was the cause of
the blast.
   Unidentified U.S. sources told the newspaper the explosions
wiped out a major source of CIA-supplied tactical assault weapons
for guerrillas battling the Soviet-backed government in Afghanistan.
   The Pakistani Cabinet chaired by Prime Minister Mohammad Khan
Junejo and the Senate met Tuesday to review the situation.
   Pakistani television said that during the Cabinet meeting, it
was decided that a committee investigating the explosion should
submit its findings with recommendations within 10 days and that
they will be made public.
</TEXT>
