<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ChildAbuse     04-12 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Abuse,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Child Welfare Group Cites Increase in Abuse, Satanic Rituals</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Childhelp in 2nd graf is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Satanic and ritualistic practices and beliefs
may be a motivating factor in a one form of child abuse, a
children's welfare group said Tuesday.
   ``People have now moved to a new level of how to assault
children,'' said Dr. Daniel Saxton of Childhelp USA. ``Just abusing
the child in the home is not enough. We've gotten into this very
sadistic kind of stuff with children.''
   Saxton, who is director of a Childhelp hotline, based his
remarks on initial findings of a national study to determine the
extent of cult involvement in specific abuse cases. The results
represent 36 separate cases, documented by 59 questionnaires from
16 states.
   He said 97 percent of children reported male and female abusers,
50 percent described six or more perpetrators, and more than 30
percent told of more than 11 persons involved.
   Sixty percent of the children responding to the questionnaires
indicated the incidents lasted from seven months to two years.
   Seventy-eight percent of the children said they were
photographed in the nude, while more than 60 percent said they were
photographed during sexual activity.
   In two-thirds of cases, Sexton said the children said they were
drugged, saw or participated in rituals, animal killings and
mutilations as part of the incident. About half said they were
taken to cemeteries and curches for these rituals.
   Roughly 46 percent of the children were forced to eat or drink
bodily waste, while a little more than 40 percent were forced to
ingest what they were told was human flesh or blood.
   Although Sexton said it would be premature to say the figures
represent a national trend, he is receiving calls from therapists
nationwide about adult patients exhibiting behavior or
experienceing dreams similar to those of some sexually abused
children.
   Sexton told of an incident in which a therapist had a patient
who remembered having a baby when she was 13, but could not
remember what happened to the child.
   ``Two days later I get a call from this therapist saying, `Good
God, this woman remembers having to kill her child,''' he said.
Sexton also mentioned that one of his adult patients, who had been
a sexual abuse victim from ages 12 through 16, gave birth to five
children, all of whom ``disappeared'' in the same manner.
   Childhelp USA is California-based, non-profit organization that
assists child abuse victims and their families through public
education, clinical programs, research and its 24-hour child abuse
hotline.
   According to the information from hotline's 148,452 calls last
year, the incidence of sexual and physical child abuse is more than
double that of the nationally accepted figures. National statistics
indicate 11 percent of abuse reports are sexual, while 36 percent
of the hotline calls were for sexual abuse.
   Similarily, national figures indicate 15.5 percent of reported
abuse is physical, but calls for physical abuse totaled 37 percent
of the hotline calls last year.
   Randall Silverston, Childhelp research director, said many
children are being exposed to the threat of AIDS as a result of
sexual abuse. The organization and the University of California,
Irvine, were asking the National Institutes of Health to fund a
three-year study of those children who are in the high-risk
category.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
