<DOCNO> AP880412-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 2100EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Housing 1stLd-Writethru a0793 04-12 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Housing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0793,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>HUD Plans More Housing Vouchers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs with testimony before Senate subcommittee</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal housing officials plan to
significantly increase the number of people getting vouchers to
help pay their rent, Housing and Urban Development Secretary Samuel
R. Pierce said Tuesday.
   The voucher program, the Reagan administration's alternative to
building more public housing, now assists about 100,000 low-income
families, with another 34,000 to be added by the fall, Pierce told
a House Appropriations subcommittee.
   HUD plans to add another 100,000 families in 1989, he said.
   Rather than subsidizing housing units, the program gives poor
families a voucher which can be used to pay a portion of the rent
on living space they choose for themselves. The value of the
voucher is fixed according to each family's income, leaving the
amount of additional rent flexible. The program was made permanent
by Congress last year.
   ``Vouchers give families the dignity of choice, offering them
the opportunity to locate near family and friends, schools,
churches and jobs,'' rather than in public housing projects, said
Pierce. He appeared before the subcommittee on HUD-independent
agencies to discuss his $21.6 billion budget request for fiscal
1989. HUD's 1988 budget is $18.6 billion.
   Pierce said the number of households to be assisted by various
HUD programs would increase from 4.3 million in 1988 to 4.4 million
next year.
   Subcommittee Chairman Rep. Edward P. Boland, D-Mass., questioned
Pierce's conclusion that the major problem for low-income families
is not the availability of houses but their affordability. Boland
said some studies show a severe shortage of low-income housing as
units built in the 1960s are converted into more profitable uses.
   Pierce quoted Commerce Department statistics putting rental
vacancy rates at their highest in 20 years, with an 8.4 percent
vacancy rate among apartments renting between $200 and $249 a month.
   Boland also questioned HUD's estimate last week that it would
take between $7.5 billion and $9.2 billion to bring the nation's
1.3 million public housing units up to modern safety and sanitation
standards. He said other estimates put the cost as high as $20
billion.
   Rep. Bill Green, R-N.Y., asked Pierce if he is concerned that
many middle-income people are being priced out of the housing
market.
   ``I'm not as disturbed as you, because I don't see that it is
such a big problem,'' the secretary said.
   Pierce, who is the only Cabinet member still in office from
among President Reagan's original appointees, noted record sales
and record housing starts in recent years. ``Somebody's buying the
homes,'' he said.
   Thomas Demery, assistant secretary for housing, told the
subcommittee several factors have affected middle-class families'
ability to buy homes, including a decline in savings brought about
partly by increased education costs.
   Meanwhile, former developer James Rouse told a Senate
subcommittee that Congress should appropriate another $3.4 billion
a year to support a federal program to increase the supply of
low-income and rental housing by the year 2000.
   Rouse, who chaired an ad hoc committee which studied housing
needs in the United States, told a Senate banking subcommittee that
the nation faces the worst housing crisis in the past 10 years.
   Rouse, who headed his own development company and now is
chairman and chief executive officer of The Enterprise Foundation,
said the $3.4 billion would be added to the $13.6 billion currently
available.
   Half of the $3.4 billion would be allocated to the states, which
would be required to match the funds by various means: providing
land or distributing money to local authorities. The other half
would go directly to cities which would have wide discretion for
use of the funds but would not be required to match the money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
