<1ST_LINE>b i PM-Hijack 14thLd-Writethru a0762 04-12 1009</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hijack, 14th Ld - Writethru, a0762, a0813, a0815, a0818,1033</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hijackers Leave Larnaca After Freeing 12 Passengers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to INCORPORATE bulletin series; Picks up
5th graf pvs, ``The plane ...; CORRECTS date of departure to
Wednesday sted Tuesday. SUBS 13th graf, ``Fantis said ... with 1
graf to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LARNACA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hijacked jet left Cyprus for Algeria on
Wednesday carrying more than 30 hostages held for over a week by
Moslem gunmen demanding freedom for terrorists jailed in Kuwait.
   The blue-and-white Boeing 747 took off at 1:17 a.m. Wednesday
(6:17 p.m. EDT Tuesday) after the hijackers freed 12 hostages.
   Forty people were believed on board the aircraft after the
latest release, including a half-dozen hijackers. The plane was
seized a week ago by gunmen demanding freedom for 17 pro-Iranian
terrorists held in Kuwait.
   The plane was refueled after repeated demands by the hijackers,
who have killed two hostages in Larnaca.
   The freed passengers were driven from the Boeing 747 at around
10:25 p.m. (3:25 p.m. EDT) then taken to Larnaca General Hospital,
reporters at the scene and hospital officials said.
   A hijacker told the tower the released included two Palestinians
with Jordanian passports and 10 others who were sick, poor or had
numerous children.
   They said the releases were a ``goodwill'' gesture but added
also that the Jordanian nationals were freed as a ``present to the
uprising in Palestine,'' a reference to four months of anti-Israeli
violence in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The plane's engines started shortly after the latest passengers
were released, and loud bangs rang out across the tarmac. Officials
said the noise was caused by the engines.
   PLO and government negotiators held talks with the hijackers
before the latest hostages were being freed.
   The hijackers said earlier in the day that they had on death
shrouds. One hijacker, in a statement radioed to the Larnaca
Airport control tower, cited Koranic verses usually read at
funerals that said ``those killed in the name of God are always
alive.''
   PLO chairman Yasser Arafat was quoted today as saying the
hijackers want to fly to Algeria and ``arrangements are being made
to this end.'' The Kuwait News Agency said Arafat told reporters in
Kuwait he expected the hijacking to end tonight.
   In London, Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister Javad Larijana said
Iran had offered to take the jet by force after it was forced to
land in Iran last week, but Kuwait rejected the idea.
   At one point today, the hijackers radioed the control tower
demanding the plane be refueled in 45 minutes. The deadline passed
without incident after two Palestine Liberation Organization
officials went out on the tarmac and spoke with the hijackers.
   One hijacker later radioed that they had extended the deadline
``for a short time ... to permit the mediators to act'' in getting
the plane refueled.
   ``We are warning against false promises,'' he said in broken
English.
   When a C-130 military transport landed a short time later, one
of the hijackers screamed over the radio: ``Identify this plane.''
   The tower replied it was a Greek air force plane carrying
supplies.
   The hijacker replied: ``My men were about to shoot at it.''
   The hijackers of the Kuwait Airways Boeing 747 shot and killed a
second passenger Monday. The hijackers are demanding Kuwait free 17
convicted terrorists and have said they want to leave for an
unspecified ``neutral country.''
   The hijackers are armed with grenades and handguns. They have
repeatedly threatened to blow up the plane since the hijacking
began a week ago.
   The hijackers' statement today indicated, as had been suspected,
that the gunmen are Shiite Moslems.
   The statement said ``hail the glory of Imam Mahdi,'' the
messiah-like holy person Shiites believe will one day appear on
earth. Only Shiite Moslems revere the imams, or saints, among the
Islamic sects.
   The 17 pro-Iranian terrorists whose freedom is sought by the
hijackers were convicted in 1984 of bombing the U.S. and French
embassies in Kuwait. The emirate has rejected the demand. All but
one of the 17 are Shiites.
   Among those on the plane are three members of Kuwait's royal
family, a man and two women.
   Foreign Minister Sheik Sabah al-Ahmed Al-Sabah of Kuwait said
Monday his country is prepared to lose more hostages rather than
give in.
   ``We will try our utmost to protect our dear ones aboard the
plane, but we will not surrender to any blackmail, even if we lose
more of them,'' he said. He added that the presence of three
members of the ruling Al-Sabah family aboard the jet ``will not
influence our decision.''
   Terrorist groups in Lebanon have threatened to kill foreign
hostages they are holding, including three Americans, if security
forces storm the plane. Two of the Americans are held by a group
that also has demanded freedom for the 17 terrorists jailed in
Kuwait.
   In today's statement, the hijackers declared in classical,
Koranic Arabic: ``We have decided to call our plane the plane of
greatest martyrdom and death. Death with glory is better than life
under humiliation... We call on the Kuwaiti people to revolt
against the Kuwaiti dictatorship. We'd like to point out we're not
against the people of Kuwait, but against the regime.''
   They added: ``We have decided to wear the death shrouds under
our clothes and that either all our 17 brothers come back to us or
else we shall meet, in our shrouds, in the heaven of eternal
happiness.''
   The Kuwait News Agency identified the man killed Monday as
Khalid Ayyub Ismail Ayyub Bandar, a 20-year-old worker for Kuwait's
fire brigade. On Saturday, the hijackers killed another man, also a
Kuwaiti.
   The plane was hijacked April 5 with 112 people aboard on a
flight from Bangkok to Kuwait and forced down in Iran, where 57
people were freed. The jet left Iran on Friday after refueling.
   After Lebanon and Syria refused to let it land, the plane flew
to Larnaca.
   One hostage was freed in Larnaca on Saturday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
