<HEAD>23 Killed As Charter Plane Crashes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A twin-engine charter plane
crashed Tuesday night in South Africa's main gold mining region,
killing all 23 people on board, a government spokesman said.
   The World War II-vintage Dakota crashed about 90 miles northeast
of Bloemfontein, capital of the Orange Free State, said Leon Els, a
spokesman for the Department of Transportation.
   It had taken off from Bloemfontein for Johannesburg.
   There was no immediate word on the cause of the crash or the
identities of those on board the plane owned by United Airline, a
private domestic carrier.
   The South African Press Association said the plane was carrying
jockeys and horse racing officials returning to Johannesburg from a
race in Bloemfontein.
   The news agency said there was an unconfirmed report the plane
burst into flames before it crashed.
