<HEAD>Tearful Father Drops Baby Off For Visit With Surrogate Mom</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NR1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teary-eyed William Stern on Tuesday
gave his daughter to surrogate mother Mary Beth Whitehead-Gould for
a day of court-ordered visitation.
   Stern carried the 2-year-old girl into a Bergen County youth
center, and a smiling Mrs. Whitehead-Gould emerged with the child
and drove her to an unknown location.
   The visit is one of the first since a judge on April 6 awarded
Mrs. Whitehead-Gould gradually expanded, unsupervised visitation
with the child, known as Baby M in court papers and legally named
Melissa Stern.
   Mrs. Whitehead-Gould, who sparked a landmark court case by
refusing to part with the baby she bore under a $10,000 contract,
is allowed to spend one six-hour day a week with the child, with
the schedule expanded over the year to include overnights, holidays
and a three-week vacation next summer.
   Stern and his wife, Elizabeth, have custody of Melissa.
   A judge ordered attorneys not to comment on the specifics of
visitation or describe the visits. Calls to attorneys in the case
late Tuesday were not answered.
