<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 2106EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Ingersoll     04-12 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Ingersoll,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Publisher Says Free and Paid Newspapers Have Common Rivals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspapers that sell their issues and those that
distribute free have greater rivals than each other, Ralph
Ingersoll, chairman of Ingersoll Publications Co., said Tuesday.
   Ingersoll's company is the largest free-circulation publisher in
the United States, but publishes other newspapers with paid
circulation. He bought 10 regional British papers of both kinds in
January.
   ``In the United States, there are still paid daily publishers
who view free newspapers of any kind as a threatening phenomenon,
but we don't happen to feel that way ourselves,'' he told a
Financial Times conference on the newspaper industry.
   ``Free circulation and paid don't have to be pitched in mortal
combat. Indeed, both have more serious natural enemies, several of
which have yet to show their full strength in the U.K. (Britain).''
   He said the real rivals include development of local commercial
broadcasting, direct mail and outdoor advertising. Ingersoll said
his company publishes free-circulation newspapers wherever it
publishes paid papers in the United States.
   Also, he said, ``We publish free-circulation newspapers in
markets in which other publishers, paid or free, have defaulted on
their obligation to deliver dependable readership to local retail
advertisers.''
   Ingersoll Publications is the first foreign company to invest in
the British regional press, where ``the free versus paid wars ...
are relatively new,'' the publisher said.
   It acquired the Birmingham Post, Birmingham Evening Mail,
Coventry Evening Telegraph and the regional Sunday publication
Sunday Mercury, all paid newspapers, and six free weeklies in the
Midlands region.
   The privately held company publishes more than 40 daily papers,
including the Trentonian, and more than 200 weeklies. It has annual
revenues of $700 million and employs 11,000 people.
   ``It is arguable that the traditional paid daily no longer
exists,'' Ingersoll said, adding that papers rely on advertising
and not circulation revenue for their profits.
   He said daily newspaper circulation began deteriorating after
World War II because populations became more transient, sprawling
suburban markets developed and commerical broadcasting grew.
   Free papers moved into the gap, Ingersoll said.
</TEXT>
