<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Bertolucci     04-12 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Bertolucci,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oscar-Winning Director Acclaimed As National Hero</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Movie director Bernardo Bertolucci, who was
prosecuted in Italy for ``Last Tango in Paris,'' was a national
hero Tuesday after ``The Last Emperor'' swept the Academy Awards.
   It won nine Oscars, including best picture and best director.
   Congratulatory messages poured in from President Francesco
Cossiga, other politicians and figures in the Italian movie
industry hailing the victory as a great day for Italy.
   Bertolucci said in an interview with state-run RAI-TV from
Hollywood that he hoped the prizes would give a boost to Italy's
flagging movie industry.
   Recalling his visit to the set in Italy of ``The Last Emperor,''
Cossiga said the awards ``underlined yet again the great merit of
Italian cinema and its authors.``
   The film was an international production but five Italians
shared in the awards, for art direction, cinematography, film
editing and direction.
   Bertolucci, 48, won acclaim for his 1970 film ``The Conformist''
but ran into legal problems in Italy two years later because of the
sexual content of ``Last Tango in Paris.''
   Obscenity charges were filed against him and the stars, Marlon
Brando and Maria Schneider.
   They were acquitted eventually, but the movie was released for
showing in Italy only last year after an appeals court ruled that
what once was considered obscene need no longer be classified that
way.
   At one point, a judge ordered all copies of the movie destroyed,
but after Bertolucci appealed to then-President Giovanni Leone the
court allowed copies to be kept in the National Cinema Library.
   ``My film has been spared execution and the verdict commuted to
a life term in the archives,'' the director said at the time.
   The awards Monday night brought the number of Oscars won by
Italians to 31. Two other Italian directors, Federico Fellini and
Vittorio De Sica, each won four Oscars, but in the foreign film
category.
</TEXT>
