<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-12 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Snow Hits North Carolina Mountains, Rain over Southern
Atlantic Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press_</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A surprise spring storm dumped heavy snow in the western North
Carolina mountains and scattered rain and a few thundershowers over
the southern Atlantic Coast region into Florida.
   North Carolina's Mount Mitchell recorded 17 inches of snow and
other mountain areas near the Tennessee border reported between 5
and 10 inches of snow.
   The snow blocked roads in Avery County, which sits on the border.
   Up to six inches of snow covered mountain tops in northeast
Georgia and snow mixed with rain fell over central Georgia.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms were scattered across much of
Florida and rain also spread north into Virginia.
   Clouds covered parts of Southern California and the New England
coast. Skies were mostly sunny over much of the rest of the nation.
   Tuesday morning's low was 13 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 34 degrees at Bluefield,
W.Va. to 91 degrees at Phoenix and Tucson, Ariz.
   Scattered rain was forecast along the central Atlantic Coast for
Wednesday, with temperatures climbing into the upper 60s. Mostly
sunny or partly cloudy skies were predicted for most other regions.
   Highs in the 40s were forecast across the upper Mississippi
valley, Maine and coastal parts of New England; in the 50s from the
northern plains through the upper Great Lakes into interior New
England; in the 80s from eastern Oregon and southwest Idaho through
the California valleys, the southern Rockies and the central high
Plains into much of Texas; and in the 90s over the Southwest
deserts.
   Highs in the 60s or 70s were called for most of the rest of the
nation.
</TEXT>
