<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 2212EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0820 04-12 0792</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0820,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says He Hopes North, Poindexter Will Be Found Innocent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Trump fund-raiser, SUB grafs 20 and 21, ``Bush
was ...,'' picking up 22nd graf pvs, ``Bush has...''; to give
comments on Palestinian homeland, add two grafs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said Tuesday he hoped
former White House aides John Poindexter and Oliver North would be
found ``innocent of any wrongdoing'' in the Iran-Contra affair.
   As to a possible pardon, Bush said he would deal with that issue
only if he is forced to face it if elected president.
   Bush made the comments in interviews with New York reporters in
a day in which he pitched the first ball in a baseball game, called
it ``warming up'' for the fall and defended his attacks against the
``ghost of Jimmy Carter.''
   Bush was asked if he would pardon then-National Security Adviser
Poindexter and then-White House aide North if elected.
   He called the question ``too hypothetical,'' but then added: ``I
hope, my own personal hope is, they're found innocent of any
wrongdoing.''
   ``If I had to face that (a pardon) at some time, then I'd keep
my own counsel and make my own decision.'' It was the first time
the vice president had expressed a desire that the two indicted
former officials be found innocent.
   Bush defended anew his refusal to disclose the advice he gave
President Reagan on the Iran-Contra matter.
   ``I've taken lots of shots (on that). But it doesn't bother me
because I know I'm doing what's right,'' Bush told his interviewers.
   On another subject, Bush told reporters that he did not think he
was too aristocratic to build wide support.
   ``If so, why would I have cleaned them (Republican rivals) up in
the primaries?'' he asked.
   ``For you to suggest that some aristocratic bias makes it
impossible for me to reach out _ just you watch,'' Bush declared.
   Bush, campaigning in New York one week before the state's
primary elections, threw out the ball for the start of a New York
Mets baseball game.
   ``We're warming up for the fall race,'' he joked, practicing by
tossing an apple aboard Air Force Two with Rep. Guy Molinari, R-N.Y.
   The vice president continued what aides depicted as a generic
campaign against Democrats in speeches taking aim at the policies
of former President Carter.
   ``That's exactly what we'd have if we ended up electing one of
them,'' Bush told reporters at an airport news conference in
Syracuse.
   He said he saw little difference among the three Democratic
contenders, Jesse Jackson, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee _ all of whom were also in New
York, for a debate and for primary campaigning.
   Asked by reporters why we was campaigning against Carter, who
left office in 1981, Bush said: ``Because the policies of the
Democrats will take us right back to the high interest rates and
the double-digit inflation of the Carter years.''
   At a later speech at a shopping mall in Syracuse, Bush expanded
upon the theme, saying he had no problem ``running against the
ghost of Jimmy Carter.''
   ``Do you want Americans to go back to those terrible days of
malaise and darkness?'' he asked.
   Bush attended a $1,000-a-ticket fund-raising reception Tuesday
night sponsored by developer Donald Trump, who endorsed the vice
president's candidacy. ``He's a great gentleman,'' said Trump.
   Bush told the packed reception at New York's Plaza Hotel that
the Democratic contenders ``want to set the clock back'' and ``bust
the federal government.''
   Bush has already raised the $27 million allowable by federal
election law for direct campaign spending. His current fund-raising
activities are designed to raise money for accounting expenses
exempt from the limit and for party organizations.
   At a fund-raising breakfast Tuesday in Schenectady, Bush told
supporters, ``I can't wait to take on whichever one of those
Democrats win the Democratic nomination.''
   In his campaign stops in New York, Bush has focused on economic
achievements under President Reagan's administration.
   ``I want to lead the country in making good changes last, and
building on them,'' he told the Schenectady audience.
   Peter Teeley, Bush's spokesman, said it is still not clear when
Reagan will begin to give the vice president campaign assistance,
since Pat Robertson is still technically a candidate.
   ``We welcome any activity on the part of the president as
quickly as he feels it's appropriate,'' Teeley said.
   Before the Trump fund-raiser, Bush said he disagreed with
comments by Dukakis on a Palestinian state.
   ``We shouldn't have a Palestinian state,'' Bush said. ``It isn't
in the interest of the national security of the United
States...It's not good foreign policy. (But) solving the
Palestinian problem is.''
</TEXT>
