<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Violence     04-12 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Violence,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Men Slain in Grenade, Machine Gun Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assoiated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of men hurled grenades at a
house in northern Mexico, dashed inside and fired submachine guns
on the four sleeping occupants, killing them, according to news
reports Tuesday.
   Men in combat fatigues later fired grenades at the house from
helicopters, the reports said.
   The Mexico City daily newspapers El Universal and Excelsior
quoted Federico Valenzuela, Sonora state judicial police director,
as saying that the slayings were related to drug trafficking.
   Valenzuela said police had no suspects in the attack Monday in
Caborca, about 60 south of the Mexico-Arizona border.
   The men in the helicopters earlier planted a bomb in front of
another house in the city, but no injuries were reported,
newspapers said.
   Sonora state judicial police in Caborca said by telephone
Tuesday that federal authorities were handling the investigation.
An operator at the federal public ministry in Caborca said all
agents and federal police officers were out of the office and
unavailable for comment.
   According to the Mexico City reports and another published
Tuesday in the daily newspaper El Norte in Monterrey, the attacks
occurred about 6:30 a.m. Monday.
   Witnesses reported that men driving a small truck and two other
vechicles stopped in front of a house in a residential
neighborhood, threw grenades at the door, then burst inside firing
submachine guns at the four sleeping occupants.
   Police later recovered the bodies of the four men.
   Men in three helicopters then launched grenades at the home,
according to the Mexico City reports.
   Other witnesses reported seeing men in camouflage clothing with
black paint on their faces descend from one of the three
helicopters to another house, according to the news reports.
   The men planted explosives at the house, then returned to the
helicopter. The bombs detonated as the helicopter flew away, El
Norte said.
   According to police, the home is owned by Miguel Angel Caro
Quintero, brother of Rafael Caro Quintero, who is jailed in Mexico
City in connection with the slaying of American drug agent Enrique
Camarena Salazar, El Norte reported.
   The house apparently was vacant at the time.
</TEXT>
