<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Byrd 3rdLd-Writethru a0832 04-12 1035</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Byrd, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0832,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Byrd Stepping Down as Senate Democratic Leader</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 8th graf pvs, bgng: ``Byrd said ...''
to include governor's criticism; picks up 9th graf pvs, bgng: ``The
majority ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democratic Leader Robert C. Byrd
announced Tuesday he will not seek re-election to the party post he
has held for a dozen years, touching off a wide-open race to
succeed him.
   The 70-year-old West Virginian said he will run for a sixth
Senate term and, if elected and the chamber remains under
Democratic control, assume the chairmanship of the Senate
Appropriations Committee. He also would likely become Senate
president pro tempore, the post reserved for the most senior
majority member.
   ``I believe I have been fair, firm and honest, and I have done
my best,'' Byrd told his fellow Democrats. ``I hope that you agree
... I have led my party from the ambivalence of the Carter years
through the extremes of the Reagan administration ....''
   Some Democratic senators privately have criticized Byrd's
leadership style over the years, saying he looked bad on television
and did not project well when trying to present the party's
position to the nation.
   Sen. J. Bennett Johnson of Louisiana challenged Byrd for his
position in 1976, but dropped out when it became clear he did not
have the votes to win. He criticized Byrd at that time for
appearing to be out of step with the times.
   There had been rumors that Byrd told Democratic senators in 1986
that if re-elected to the leadership post he would not seek it
again. Those rumors were never confirmed.
   Byrd told reporters he had ``absolutely no doubt'' that he could
have won again as leader had he chosen to run.
   Byrd said that as chairman of the Appropriations Committee,
which provides money for all federal programs, he would be able to
help his state of West Virginia, which he said has suffered under
the administration's economic policies.
   However, West Virginia Gov. Arch Moore criticized Byrd's
decision, saying Byrd would have more influence as majority leader
than as appropriations chairman and that the change was unlikely to
benefit his state.
   ``Moving down to the chairmanship of the Senate Appropriations
Committee is very significant, and I would be hard-pressed to
suggest that West Virginians will notice any difference as a result
of the change,'' the Republican governor said in a statement.
   The majority leader of the Senate is that chamber's chief
strategist and controlling party spokesman. He sets the agenda.
   Byrd's decision drew immediate announcements from three
Democratic senators _ George Mitchell of Maine, Daniel Inouye of
Hawaii, and Johnston _ that they will seek the leadership post.
Senate Democrats will decide the issue in a party tally to be held
after next November's election.
   Several senators said there is no clear front-runner.
   ``This is Senator Byrd's day,'' said Mitchell. ``The emphasis
ought to be on his contribution.''
   Asked whether he will seek the top job, Inouye said, ``Yes, I
will,'' and added that he believes his prospects are ``very good.''
   Inouye said he did not believe lingering criticism over his
performance as chairman of the Senate Iran-Contra investigating
committee last summer would pose an obstacle to his bid. Some
Democratic senators have complained, mostly privately, that Marine
Lt. Col. Oliver L. North was permitted to steal the show.
   One senator who had been thought a possible candidate, Sen. Dale
Bumpers, D-Ark., said he would not make the race.
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas said Byrd had earned
a special place in history as ``the grand master of Senate rules
and procedure.''
   ``He is one tough ball carrier for his party,'' Dole said.
``He's a senator's senator.''
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said that while Byrd himself had
provided solid leadership, ``this institution will find new
leaders. There is a very competent group of people running.''
   Sen. John Melcher, D-Mont., said the announcement ``was not
unexpected. The likelihood of his running again seemed to fade over
the past year. The Democrats will seek a new leader now, and go on
from there.''
   Byrd's reign has been marked by his mastery of Senate rule and a
somewhat dry, if verbose, leadership style. Insider grumbling about
his leadership qualities has grown over the years.
   Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., said Byrd has been ``a very
effective leader.'' He added, however, that ``what we'll be looking
for in the leader is perhaps someone with less knowledge of the
process, but hopefully able to do it differently ... the time for
change I think is appropriate.,''
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said: ``I have all the respect
for Senator Byrd over the time he has served as majority leader and
minority leader. He made this judgment for the best interests of
the nation and the Senate.''
   Since he first entered the Senate in 1958, Byrd forged a
reputation as a courtly master strategist who revered the Senate
and its history and gained power inch-by-inch by attending to his
colleagues' smallest wishes.
   Orphaned at an early age, Byrd was raised by an aunt and uncle
in the impoverished coal country of West Virginia. He graduated
first in his class in high school, but he had to work 12 years at
such jobs as gas station attendant, grocery store clerk and butcher
before he could afford to attend college.
   Byrd's prowess as a country fiddle player helped his campaign
for the state legislature in 1946, and since then he has never lost
an election.
   After three House terms, Byrd won a Senate seat, rising in party
ranks by using his posts to do legislative and personal favors.
   In 1971, Byrd called in those favors and ousted Kennedy for the
No. 2 party post of assistant leader. He became a loyal aide to
Majority Leader Mike Mansfield, and succeeded him in 1976.
   With the 1980 loss of the Senate to the Republicans, Byrd lost
his position and became minority leader.
   In that role, Byrd led Democratic opposition to a highly popular
Republican president.
   But Byrd returned in triumph when the Democrats swept the 1986
elections, recapturing majority rule in the 100th Congress.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
