<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 2229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     04-12 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Athol Fugard's `The Road to Mecca' Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the dry, dusty South African outback, an
elderly woman creates an outdoor sculpture garden filled with
strange and wondrous things _ camels, wise men, owls, pyramids, a
Buddha, mermaids, peacocks, even a mosque made of beer bottles.
   She calls it her ``Mecca,'' and it is the catalyst for ``The
Road to Mecca,'' Athol Fugard's astonishing and affecting new play
which opened Tuesday at off-Broadway's Promenade Theater.
   Fugard is the South African playwright best known for such works
as ``Blood Knot'' and ``Master Harold . . . and the boys.'' They
deal with the pervasiveness of apartheid as well as the necessity
and inevitability of seeing everything in South Africa in terms of
black and white.
   ``The Road to Mecca,'' with its three white characters, touches
on an apartheid of a different sort. It concerns an adventurous
artist named Miss Helen, at odds with and cut off from the rigid
and unyielding Afrikaners around her. It's her eccentric art work
that severs her from society.
   Miss Helen stands at the center of a battle between Marius, a
staid minister, and Elsa, an embittered, frustrated English
teacher. Marius feels Miss Helen should move to a retirement home,
while the teacher champions the woman's right to remain where she
is and create her exotic statues.
   The fight for control of Miss Helen's life and artistic spirit
takes a while to develop. Fugard doesn't rush his story. He
examines each member of this trio with sensitivity and care.
   Act 1 focuses on the two women. Their relationship is the most
interesting aspect of the play. The younger woman admires Miss
Helen's independence, her ability to pursue what she wants,
regardless of the consequences. The older woman relishes the
companionship of the young teacher whose enthusiasm she admires.
   The minister comes between them in the second act, a powerful
explosion of drama that leads to a heartfelt and hopeful
conclusion. Fugard's mastery of language is never more evident than
near the end of Act 2 when Miss Helen explains how she came back to
life after a loveless marriage ended.
   Yvonne Bryceland, who plays Miss Helen, is a revelation. The
South African-born actress originally was rejected by Actors Equity
from performing in the United States because it felt she wasn't an
actress of international stature. Her performance confirms how
wrong the union was.
   The actress, dressed in a gray gunnysack of a dress, commands
the stage with her ingratiating smile and honey-combed voice. At
first, she projects a childlike enthusiasm but the demeanor is
deceptive. Gradually, the woman's crisis of faith is revealed, and
the iron will behind her infectious laugh comes through.
   Fugard, who also directed in a careful, deliberate manner,
offers a controlled performance as the rigid clergyman. He has a
difficult task _ to portray a sympathetic antagonist who is as much
a victim as he is a villain.
   Amy Irving starts on too strong a note as the volatile teacher,
and then has nowhere to go. It's an emotional, showy role, but the
part demands more shading than the actress gives it.
   Miss Helen's Mecca is never actually seen on stage but a glimpse
of its glories is offered in designer John Lee Beatty's
approximation of the woman's living room: Her home literally
glitters with the artist's handiwork, lighted by Dennis Parichy.
   The play ends on a reaffirmation of life, a reaffirmation by the
aging artist that recognizes the darkness while celebrating the
light. With Miss Bryceland as a most entrancing free spirit, ``The
Road to Mecca'' soars above every other play in New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880412-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 2230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Television-Trade     04-12 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Television-Trade,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Touts TV Development As Trade Boon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The development of high definition TV
offers U.S. industry a chance to improve the trade imbalance for
consumer electronics products, according to a government report
released Tuesday.
   The report by the National Telecommunications and Information
Administration, a Commerce Department agency, estimates the total
potential U.S. sales of high definition TV equipment at more than
$150 billion by the year 2010.
   ``The message of the report is that there is a huge amount of
money at stake and the strength of the consumer electronics
industry as well,'' said Alfred C. Sikes, head of NTIA, in
releasing the report on the final day of the four-day National
Association of Broadcasters annual convention here.
   Advanced television technology, including high definition TV,
was a hot topic at this year's convention, and most of the dozen or
so competing systems under development were demonstrated. The
technology produces clearer images with more brilliant colors on a
wider TV screen.
   Broadcasters are concerned that a Japanese lead in developing a
high definition technology could put them at a competitive
disadvantage to cable TV, video cassette recorders and satellite
distribution systems if the Japanese system, which is not
compatible with existing U.S. television sets, takes hold in the
United States.
   Sikes said he anticipates that HDTV will follow the same path as
color television sets and video cassette recorders, though he said
he could not predict how fast sales of HDTV equipment will grow.
   ``That will turn on general economic conditions, prices of
equipment and the availability of software,'' he said.
   The report, however, says that if HDTV sales grow as fast as
color receivers and VCRs, the new products would find their way
into about 1 percent of American households by 1997 and grow to
93.9 percent in 2008, when total sales of HDTV equipment would
reach $144 billion.
   The potential sales are ``immense,'' the report said, and
``substantial participation by U.S. manufacturers'' in this
developing market could help restore balance in the trade and
federal budget deficits.
   The debate over HDTV development in the United States has been
over deciding on an industry transmission standard. Sikes said he
believes a standard can be agreed upon by 1991.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
