<HEAD>Two Police Officers Wounded in Gunfight with Suspected Terrorists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PILAR, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Right-wing terrorists opened fire on two
police agents early Tuesday at a ranch, seriously wounding them,
police reported.
   They said officers Carlos Covilobos and Antonio del Valle were
shot by members of the extreme-right National Alert organization
and the gunmen then escaped in the agents' car.
   The shooting took place at a ranch 40 miles north of Buenos
Aires, police said.
   Police have blamed National Alert for four bombings in Buenos
Aires and Cordoba this month that injured four people. Two victims
were patrons in a movie theater and two policemen were wounded
trying to defuse a bomb.
   The Buenos Aires-based group seeks a return to military rule and
supports former Lt. Col. Aldo Rico, who led unsuccessful army
mutinies in January 1988 and April 1987. Rico is in the Magdalena
military prison near Buenos Aires awaiting trial on rebellion
charges.
   One of National Alert's leaders, Luis Alberto Vega, was shot to
death last week on a street in a Buenos Aires suburb. Officials
said police shot Vega, 24, after he threatened them with a grenade.
They said weapons and explosives were found in a search of Vega's
house.
   The Third Army Corps said Tuesday that two bombs exploded over
the weekend at an army compound in Cordoba but caused no injuries
or damage. It said no group or individual asserted responsibility
for the bombings.
