<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan-Killing     04-12 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan-Killing,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to fix slug.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Army Commander Killed; Crash Victims Buried</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem guerrillas killed the vice
commander of the Afghan army's central corps in an attack in the
western province of Parwan, Kabul Radio said Tuesday.
   In Moscow, meanwhile, a Soviet Foreign Ministry official told a
visiting Italian government delegation that the Kremlin will remove
50,000 troops from Afghanistan during a three-month period
beginning May 15, a source said.
   The statement by First Deputy Foreign Minister Yuli Vorontsov
appeared to be the first time an official source gave any
indication of the size of the Soviet force backing the Afghan
government.
   Official Kabul Radio said Brig. Gen. Aqa Shah was assaulted by
``extremist opposition elements'' _ a reference to the guerrillas _
in the town of Pul Mattak. He later died of his wounds, it said,
without giving a date.
   He was buried Tuesday along with several victims of a passenger
plane shot down by guerrillas on Sunday, said Kabul Radio,
monitored in Islamabad.
   Defense and Interior Ministry officials attended the funeral in
Kabul, it said. Other victims of the crash, in which 29 people were
killed, were buried in the northern province of Faryab. The
Soviet-made plane had been on a domestic flight in northern
Afghanistan.
   The radio said the guerrillas who downed the plane were ``guided
by leaders based in Peshawar,'' referring to the seven-party
guerrilla group which maintains headquarters in Pakistan.
   Under an accord to be signed Thursday in Geneva, the Soviet
Union has agreed to remove all of its soldiers from Afghanistan
within nine months of May 15, the first half of them by Aug. 15.
   The troop figure provided by Vorontsov would make the size of
the Soviet force about 100,000 soldiers. Western sources have
estimated there are 115,000 Soviet soldiers in Afghanistan, but the
Soviets never have provided a figure.
   The Italian source attended the meeting but spoke on condition
he not be further identified.
   Vorontsov told the group of eight Italian lawmakers that half of
the Soviet force would leave Afghanistan within three months, and
``he mentioned 50,000 soldiers,'' the source said.
   Vorontsov did not provide any further details.
   The Italian delegation that met with Vorontsov was headed by
Christian Democrat Flaminio Piccoli, president of the Foreign
Commission of the Italian Chamber of Deputies.
   Soviet soldiers entered Afghanistan in December 1979 and
replaced one pro-Soviet government with another. They remained to
help government forces fight anti-Communist insurgents, who have
received aid from Pakistan and the United States.
</TEXT>
