<1ST_LINE>u w AM-WalkingHorses 1stLd-Writethru a0826 04-12 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Walking Horses, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0826,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Won't Overrule Ban On Padded Shoes For Walking Horses</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 12-13 pvs, bgng: ``It's like ...'' to CORRECT
congressman to Cooper sted Gordon; Picks up 14th graf pvs, bgng:
``It's the ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge refused Tuesday to overrule a
ban ordered by the Agriculture Department last month on the use of
padded shoes on Tennessee Walking Horses.
   U.S. District Court Judge Oliver Gasch denied breeders and
displayers of the high-gait show horses a temporary restraining
order to lay aside Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng's order
prohibiting the use of the 4-inch-thick pads on the horses' front
hooves.
   Lyng issued the order on March 25 after Gasch had ruled four
days earlier that the department's present regulations allowing use
of the pads to accent the breed's high gait violated the 1970 Horse
Protection Act.
   The 1970 law was intended to eliminate the practice of
``soring'' _ using chemicals or devices to accent a horse's gait
through the infliction of pain to the animal _ in the Tennessee
Walker industry.
   Whether the 4-inch pads, sometimes called stacks, ``sore'' or
cause pain to a horse has been a legal dispute in Gasch's court for
the past four years through a suit by the American Horse Protection
Association.
   Gasch described the pads, which effectively elevate the front of
a horse and thus shift its weight to its rear legs, as being
similar to high-heeled shoes that a women might decide to quit
wearing because they hurt her feet.
   ``The horses, however, don't seem to have a choice,'' he added.
   The Tennessee Walking Horse Breeder's Association and a new
group called Friends of the Show Horse formed in response to Lyng's
ruling had petitioned Gasch for the restraining order.
   John Harmon, an attorney for the latter group, argued that Lyng
had overstepped the judge's March 25 ruling by immediately
implementing the ban instead of going through the normal, lengthy
process of rewriting the regulations after first holding hearings
and seeking comments.
   The Agriculture Department, which had defended its present
regulations and agreed with the breeders that the pads were legal,
has started that process of redrafting them. But in the interim, it
is prohibiting the padded shoes.
   Harmon said Lyng's action caused the immediate cancellation of
11 Tennessee Walking Horse shows and threatens another 24 scheduled
between now and the end of April around the country.
   ``It's like Pearl Harbor to Shelbyville,'' said Rep. Jim Cooper,
D-Tenn., whose district includes the town that is site to the
annual Tennessee Walking Horse National Celebration, the industry's
largest show.
   Cooper estimated that the show held each year just prior to
Labor Day pumps about $35 million into the Shelbyville area's
economy.
   ``It's the flashy, fast-gaited horses that draw the crowds,'' he
said. ``People in the business tell me the horses without pads are
not as exciting,''
   However, Sharon Rice, who owns a small stable of Tennessee
Walkers in Fairfax, Va., said she is now showing five horses that
have never had pads put on their hooves.
   ``They don't need to use them,'' she said of the devices. ``It
just makes it easier and quicker to train them. And for people
running large farms, that means they can just run that many more
horses through.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880412-0223 </DOCNO>
