<HEAD>Boy Returns After Disappearing With 37-year-old Woman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with woman arrested. Pickup 5th
graf pvs ``Welfare workers...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON5</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11-year-old boy was taken into welfare custody
Tuesday after he disappeared for six days, apparently with a
neighbor woman who his mother claims was infatuated with the
youngster.
   The woman allegedly involved, 37-year-old Janette Buckley, was
arrested by detectives at a house at Peterborough 75 miles north of
London on Tuesday night.
   Detectives later took her for questioning to Corby, where she
and the boy were neighbors, Northamptonshire police said in a
statement. Corby is 20 miles southwest of Peterborough.
   Mrs. Buckley, who is married and has five children, disappeared
from her home in Corby at about the same time April 6 that
schoolboy Wayne Burgess disappeared from his home a few doors away,
according to Press Association, the domestic news agency.
   Welfare workers took Wayne into their care Tuesday after he
telephoned police from Kettering, 60 miles north of London, and
then made his way about 10 miles north to the Corby police station.
   Wayne's mother, Kathleen Burgess, was quoted by the agency as
saying, ``I saw this unhealthy friendship developing over the past
year and warned Janet to stop it. ... She has taken the love and
affection of my son and I thought she was my friend.
   ``They just got too close and I warned her to leave him alone
but she wouldn't listen,'' she said.
   The agency quoted neighbors as saying Mrs. Buckley was
``completely besotted'' with the boy.
