<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0806,0764</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scattered Clashes In Occupied Territories While Arab Deportees
Appeal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with more clashes, Shamir says
more deportations. Pickup 2nd graf pvs: Beita's 6,000.... EDITS to
trim and conform. ^Precede BEITA</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians and Israeli troops clashed in the
occupied territories Tuesday while Arabs accused of inciting
violence fought deportation orders through the courts.
   More than two dozen Palestinians were injured by rubber bullets
or tear gas in scattered protests in the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
army sources said.
   Palestinians in the West Bank village of Beita, where an Israeli
teen-ager was killed last week, said they feared retaliation by
Jewish settlers once the army lifts a curfew, but insisted Arabs
were not to blame for the girl's death.
   In Gaza's Jabaliya refugee camp, troops shot rubber bullets and
live ammunition to disperse a demonstration near a military
building, Palestinian reporters said.
   An army helicopter hovered above the Beach camp, also in the
Gaza Strip, firing tear gas grenades and gravel at the protesters,
Israel Radio reported. The army clamped a curfew on the Beach camp
and its 42,000 residents.
   One resident, Hassan Mahmoud Kaoud, 21, reportedly perished
Tuesday. Arab sources told the Itim news agency he died after
inhaling tear gas on Monday.
   Army sources said 10 Gaza residents suffered beating injuries,
four were hurt by rubber bullets and 10 suffered tear gas
inhalation. They said one Arab was wounded by a regular bullet.
Ahli Arab hospital officials in Gaza City identified the victim as
a 12-year-old boy and said he had a gunshot wound in his left arm.
   In the West Bank village of Asira esh Shamaliya near Nablus, two
Palestinians were wounded in clashes with troops when residents
blocked the road and stoned a bus transporting soldiers, the army
reported. It said an army officer was injured when he was hit by a
rock.
   A virturally total commercial strike was observed in the West
Bank and Gaza, but many Arab workers left for work in Israel,
Israeli media reports said.
   Three of twelve Palestinians who received deportation notices on
Monday appealed the orders to a military tribunal, Israel Radio
reported. The rest said they plan to appeal.
   Eight Palestinians were deported to Lebanon Monday.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said the Jewish state will
continue ``to build the kingdom of Israel'' and threatened to
deport more Palestinian activists.
   Beita's 6,000 residents are living under a dusk-to-dawn curfew.
Soldiers patrol the village, which is surrounded by thick groves of
olive, fig and almond trees.
   Troops guard the village entrance.
   The army has ordered the deportation of six residents. Hundreds
have been detained, and Beita residents said 60 were still being
held Tuesday.
   ``This is an act of retaliation against us, against the whole
village,'' said Ahmed Hassan Salman, 27. ``It is a collective
punishment to satisfy the settlers' demands. A settler killed the
girl _ and they are punishing us.''
   Villagers said no Arabs were involved in the shooting of
15-year-old Tirza Porat on April 6, but they said the army has
destroyed 16 of their homes.
   Initial army reports said the girl was stoned to death by Arabs
while hiking through Beita, 35 miles north of Jerusalem, with a
group of Jewish teen-agers and two armed guards. Enraged Jewish
settlers screamed for revenge and attacked Arab homes and cars.
   After an autopsy, the army concluded that Tirza was accidentally
shot by one of the Israeli guards.
   Tirza was the first Israeli civilian to die since unrest broke
out Dec. 8 in the occupied territories Israel seized in the 1967
Middle East war. According to U.N. figures, 143 Palestinians have
died. On Israeli soldier also was killed.
   U.S. Ambassador Thomas Pickering expressed concern over Israeli
tactics in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, specifically
deportations, administrative detentions and house demolitions.
   He told an audience at Jerusalem's Hebrew University that it was
essential that basic concepts of due process be observed.
   Israel's deputy chief of staff, Gen. Ehud Barak, told Israeli
newspapers reserve soldiers would be called up for 62 days a year
instead of the usual 40 to cope with violence in the occupied
territories.
   Barak also said there were five times as many troops serving in
the occupied territories than a year ago due to recent unrest, the
Hadashot daily reported. He declined to give a figure in keeping
with military policy.
</TEXT>
