<1ST_LINE>a a PM-SingleGourmet Adv20   04-12 0789</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Single Gourmet, Adv 20,0809</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs, April 20, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Dining Club Thrives on Civilized Pleasures of the Table</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lighting is soft, the food and wine
exquisite, the conversation witty and sophisticated _ ingredients
for a perfect evening.
   But the men and women at the elegant restaurant are more
interested in salmon mousse than sizzling amour. Dalliance, though
welcome, is not the goal of The Single Gourmet _ a less romantic
but frequently more satisfying pleasure lies behind the
organization with about 10,000 members in North America.
   ``It's probably the best way to meet people,'' said Art Fischer,
who began the club in New York in 1982. ``It's not a dating agency.
It's not a matrimonial agency. It's a dining club. We try to bring
people together for good food and congenial conversation.''
   The organization's recipe, stirred by changes in courtship and
fascination with the arts of the kitchen, has been successful. The
New York branch has grown to 2,600 members, and 14 independent
chapters have opened in the United States and Canada, Fischer said
in a telephone interview.
   Members pay up to $75 a year to join The Single Gourmet and
$25-50, not including wine, for meals at restaurants or on other
outings. Most are upper-middle-class professionals _ lawyers,
business executives, stockbrokers and doctors, Fischer said.
   In keeping with the classy, low-key approach, members are not
afflicted with name tags, but are identified discreetly at tables
of six to 10 with placecards bearing only first names.
   In San Francisco, about 35 members of The Single Gourmet
recently enjoyed salmon tortellini, pear and parsnip soup, lamb
with couscous and other specialities of California cuisine at Cafe
Majestic, a popular restaurant in a restored Victorian hotel.
   ``I've wanted to come to this restaurant ever since it opened,
but I never dared come by myself,'' said Jenny, 49, a medical
secretary. ``So this is a real option for me.''
   The chapter, about 18 months old, has about 270 members in the
Bay area. One member travels from Nevada to attend its dinners,
winery tours and other functions, which occur about twice a month.
   Some regulars simply find The Single Gourmet a way to fit a
social life into their busy schedules.
   ``It forces you to go out. For instance, I would not on a
Tuesday night go out to Cafe Majestic or someplace like it,'' said
Louis Sclafani, a designer in his 30s.
   ``It gives you a nice experience trying different restaurants
and lets you experiment without, as a single man, having to go out
on a date,'' he said.
   Others, like Gary Sternitzke, first used the club as a way to
learn about good restaurants and find friends in a new city. He was
hooked when he ended up belly dancing at a Moroccan restaurant at
the first Single Gourmet dinner he attended a year and a half ago.
   Sternitzke, 35, credits the club for introducing him _ a native
of the Midwest raised on ``meat-and-potatoes stuff'' _ to culinary
adventure.
   ``I've tasted food I can't even say,'' he said. ``And I've tried
food when I've asked them not to tell me what it is until I've
eaten it.''
   But all the diners agreed they hadn't joined The Single Gourmet
as a singles club or dating service.
   ``I just enjoy meeting people. If it was single and married
people, I'd probably join then, too,'' said Jeanne Swift, who began
attending dinners six months ago.
   Jenny, who declined to give her last name, said sex wasn't a
factor in the civilized pleasure of enjoying food with others.
   ``When you're eating lovely food, you want to look across the
table and say, `This is wonderful; you must have a taste,''' she
said. ``I don't care if it's with men or women.''
   But changing sexual behavior has definitely helped The Single
Gourmet, members and coordinators said.
   ``It just seemed like an idea that came at the right time,''
Fischer said. ``It was the time (the novel and movie) `Looking for
Mr. Goodbar' was giving singles bars and discos a bad name. ... You
almost had to make up your mind about someone on eye contact.
That's hardly the way to get to know somebody.''
   But while people may not be looking for love when they join,
sometimes they find it anyway. The New York chapter has seen 28
marriages of club members in six years, Fischer said.
   Fischer, a retired film importer, owns The Single Gourmet name
and sells licenses for branches, which operate independently
although members may attend dinners and other Single Gourmet events
in other cities.
   End Adv for Wed PMs, April 20
</TEXT>
