<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices have leaped to the highest level of
the year, partly reflecting speculation that OPEC would be able to
recruit help from outside producers to constrict world supplies.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the May-delivery contract
for West Texas Intermediate crude oil jumped $1.01 per barrel on
Monday to $17.89, the highest level since a closing of $17.85
reached Jan. 5. It was one of the biggest one-day moves ever,
traders said.
   Some traders and analysts said the gain was not sustainable. But
others said it signaled a more fundamental change in market
sentiment that indicated the end of a low-price era in the
petroleum business.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration has indicated the
world's top industrial countries are near agreement on a proposal
to use the price of gold and other commodities to help in the
international coordination of exchange rates.
   The disclosure Monday came as representatives of the 151-nation
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank began five days of
high-level meetings with exchange rates, trade issues and Third
World debt dominating the agenda.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Odyssey Partners is keeping the heat on in the
contest for control of J.P. Stevens & Co.
   Odyssey increased its buyout price for the textile giant to
$1.22 billion Monday, hours after rival suitor West Point-Pepperell
Inc. raised its bid to $1.19 billion.
   Stevens indicated its prior agreement to merge with Odyssey
would remain in effect under the higher offer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
