<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most detailed assessment of the nation's
business schools in nearly 30 years has found widespread
complacency, poor planning and a lack of contact with the business
world.
   But the 372-page report, released Monday at a national
convention of business schools, drew immediate fire from deans and
corporate officials who said the report didn't go far enough in
addressing social and ethical issues, including minority
recruitment.
   The report chided schools for preaching long-term planning in
the corporate world, but doing little planning themselves beyond
the next semester.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The airline smoking ban that goes into effect
April 23 on commercial aircraft will apply to any flight scheduled
for two hours or less even if delays cause the flight to take
longer, the Federal Aviation Administration says.
   Congress required the smoking ban on short flights in
legislation last year. The FAA issued its final rules on the
prohibition Monday, although the general outline of the new
restrictions has been known for months.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp.'s planned closing of its
Kenosha auto plant would cost $209 million in welfare and
unemployment benefits, along with lost taxes, for the first two
years after the shutdown, a union-commissioned study says.
   The analysis released Monday by the Midwest Center for Labor
Research in Chicago estimated that the plant's closing would cost
federal, state and local governments a total of $38,000 for each
unemployed Chrysler worker.
   Chrysler announced in January it plans to end auto production at
Kenosha by Sept. 30, resulting in the layoffs of 5,500 workers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co.
has told shareholders a top priority this year will be eliminating
about $3.6 billion in debt incurred in fending off Sir James
Goldsmith's 1986 attempted takeover.
   Robert E. Mercer also said Monday he expected 1988 earnings to
surpass the $770.5 million earned last year, which included $257
million from discontinued operations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American public may be less willing
than the television industry believes to embrace a high-resolution
TV system with improved picture quality, clearer images and more
brilliant color, according to a new study.
   The results of the study, released Monday by the Media
Laboratory at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology,
``contradict the accepted wisdom ... which posits that high
definition TV knocks the socks off everyone who sees it.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market edged higher in quiet trading Monday, pushing
the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials up 5.80 to 2,095.99, a new
post-crash closing high.
   Bond prices tumbled by as much as $10 for every $1,000 in face
value in response to inflation speculation caused by soaring oil
prices.
   The dollar rose against most major currencies while gold prices
were mixed.
   Copper futures prices fell sharply, livestock and meat futures
rose and grains and soybeans were mixed.
</TEXT>
