<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     04-12 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise; Other Markets Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have soared to their highest
level so far this year, with the runup stirring inflation fears
that pushed interest rates sharply higher in the credit markets.
   Traders said oil prices rose Monday partly on speculation that
OPEC would encourage other oil producers to rein in production.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries' price
monitoring committee, which met over the weekend, said it would
meet soon with non-OPEC exporters to consider shared production
restraints.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the May-delivery contract
for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark crude oil, jumped $1.01
per barrel to close at $17.89, its highest level this year.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale heating
oil rose 2.42 cents a gallon to 47.88 cents, and wholesale unleaded
gasoline rose 2.18 cents a gallon to 50.95 cents.
   Oil market experts debated whether the gain was sustainable.
Some believe the jump in prices may be signaling an end to the
recent low-price era in the petroleum business.
   The sharp run-up had a negative impact on the credit markets,
where the yield on the bellwether 30-year Treasury bond rose to
8.77 percent from 8.68 percent late Friday.
   The stock market edged slightly higher, extending last week's
rally despite some resistance from sellers. The Dow Jones average
of 30 industrials rose 5.80 to 2,095.99 on top of last week's
102.13-point jump to new closing highs since the crash last fall.
   The dollar rose against most major currencies except the
Canadian dollar, while gold prices were mixed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880412-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0130EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Hanover-Finance     04-12 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hanover-Finance,0691</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manufacturers Hanover Agrees to Sell Consumer Finance Unit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manufacturers Hanover Corp. says it will retain
major consumer banking operations even after the proposed sale of
its consumer finance unit to a Texas company for $685 million cash.
   Manufacturers Hanover, the nation's sixth-largest bank holding
company, said Monday it had agreed in principle to sell the finance
unit to American General Corp., a financial services concern.
   The acquisition, if approved by the boards of both companies,
would nearly double the size of Houston-based American General's
consumer credit finance operations.
   The transaction also is subject to a definitive agreement being
reached.
   Although the proposed sale would remove one of its major
consumer operations, Manufacturers Hanover said it would remain a
strong player in the consumer market through its Branch Banking
Division, a New York area regional bank, and its nationwide credit
card operation.
   Manufacturers Hanover's decision to sell its consumer finance
unit, which is based in Huntingdon Valley, Pa., came as no surprise
as it tries to recover from heavy losses absorbed last year when it
boosted its loan loss reserve.
   The bank holding company posted a $1.14 billion loss in 1987 as
it boosted its loan-loss reserve by $1.7 billion in anticipation of
problems with some of its Third World loans.
   Manufacturers Hanover expected a pre-tax gain of about $300
million from the proposed sale.
   ``We are realizing a substantial premium over book value on this
well-managed company,'' said John F. McGillicuddy, chairman and
chief executive of Manufacturers Hanover.
   Manufacturers Hanover's common stock rose 12{ cents to $26 a
share and American General was off 50 cents a share to $32.50 on
the New York Stock Exchange.
   American General would make the acquisition through its
Credithrift Financial Corp., based in Evansville, Ind.
   The purchase would boost Credithrift's assets to more than $6
billion from $3.3 billion and give it a total of 1,400 branch
offices in 42 states, Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands.
   Both Credithrift and Manufacturers Hanover Consumer Services
market consumer and home equity loans and retail financing
services, and have insurance subsidiaries that provide
credit-related coverage.
   Lawrence Cohn, who follows the banking business for Merrill
Lynch & Co., said Manufacturers Hanover appeared to have gotten a
good price for the unit and that the sale should not hurt its
overall profitability.
   Manufacturers Hanover said the consumer finance unit earned
$55.2 million in 1987. Cohn said the company should be able to earn
that much in interest on proceeds from the sale.
   Cohn also said the sale will help Manufacturers Hanover toward
its goal of boosting the ratio between shareholder's equity and its
assets, a key indicator monitored by federal regulators.
   Manufacturers Hanover had told shareholders earlier this year
that it intended to boost that ratio to 4 percent by the end of
1988 through a combination of stronger operating earnings, $400
million in pre-tax gains on the sale of undervalued assets and use
of tax benefits.
   Manufacturers Hanover said the consumer finance sale would add
about $275 million to shareholders' equity and reduce total assets
by about $3 billion from $73.3 billion at the end of 1987.
   Cohn figured the sale would boost the equity-to-assets ratio to
about 3.32 percent from 2.81 percent at the end of 1987.
   American General posted a profit of $555 million in 1987 and had
$28 billion in assets. Its Credithrift subsidiary earned $68.9
million in 1987.
   Harold S. Hook, chairman and chief executive of American
General, said the purchase should not dilute American General's
earnings and there were no plans to alter the company's previously
announced stock repurchase plan.
   American General said it would change the name of its consumer
credit segment to American General Financial Services upon
completion of the deal.
   In addition to purchase price, Manufacturers Hanover said it
also would receive a cash dividend of $20 million representing the
consumer finance unit's earnings between Jan. 1 and the closing of
the transaction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880412-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TreasuryBills     04-12 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>T-Bills Mixed In Latest Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities were mixed in the government's latest auction, with
rates on three-month bills unchanged and rates on six-month bills
edged down slightly.
   The Treasury Department sold $6.4 billion in three-month bills
at an average discount rate of 5.98 percent on Monday, the same as
last week. Another $6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at an
average discount rate of 6.19 percent, down from 6.21 percent last
week.
   The three-month bill rate this week and last was the highest
since these bills averaged 6 percent on Dec. 14. The 6.19 percent
rate for six-month bills was the lowest since 6 percent on March 28.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 6.16 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,848.80 and 6.48 percent for six-month bills selling for
$9,687.10.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, was 7.01
percent last week, up from 6.78 percent the week before.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
