<HEAD>French Industrial Group Makes Offer For Vinyl Siding Maker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French industrial group is offering
$75.9 million to acquire Wolverine Technologies Inc., a maker of
vinyl siding and vinyl windows for the home remodeling industry.
   The $23 a share offer made Monday by SG Acquisition Corp., a
subsidiary of Compagnie de Saint-Gobain, topped an earlier
$18.50-a-share merger agreement Wolverine had with Ply-Gem
Industries Inc.
   Wolverine stock jumped $4.87{ to $23.25 a share on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   The Saint-Gobain offer, which expires May 6, was conditioned at
least 2.1 million of Wolverine's 3.3 million outstanding shares
being tendered, said Toney File, a Saint-Gobain spokesman in New
York.
   Although Wolverine had agreed to be acquired by Ply-Gem, its
board of directors will consider the new offer, said Thomas
Jeffers, Wolverine's treasurer and vice president for finance. A
board meeting has not been scheduled.
   ``We really need to find out more about it,'' Jeffers said.
``The cash price is certainly a more attractive offer as far as the
shareholders are concerned.''
   The Ply-Gem agreement prohibited Wolverine from soliciting other
offers but not from considering an offer, Jeffers said.
   Wolverine reported 1987 earnings of $8.4 million on revenue of
$111 million.
   Saint-Gobain has more than 300 plants and 140,000 employees in
17 countries. It owns 94.2 percent of the stock in CertainTeed
Corp. in the United States following a tender offer that expired
last week.
   Saint-Gobain manufactures industrial products including flat
glass, insulation, containers, fiber reinforcement, industrial
ceramics, pipe and machinery, and includes a contracting and
services unit.
   The Saint-Gobain Group had 1987 net income of about $515.7
million on consolidated net sales of $14.43 billion.
