<HEAD>AT&T Chairman Steps Down Temporarily After Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James E. Olson, the chairman and chief executive
of American Telephone & Telegraph Co., has relinquished his duties
temporarily following major surgery for removal of a malignant
tumor, the company has disclosed.
   Olson, 62, underwent surgery March 25 for removal of a tumor, a
spokesman told the New York Times on Monday. The tumor was
malignant and Olson is undergoing chemotherapy as an outpatient,
the spokesman said.
   Robert E. Allen, AT&T's president and chief operating officer,
has taken charge of the company.
   The spokesman, who was not identified by the Times, said it was
too soon to determine how long Olson would need to recover.
   Olson, a 44-year veteran of the telecommunications giant, has
served as its chairman and chief executive since 1986. He began his
career cleaning dirt from telephone manholes and eventually rose
through several management jobs at other Bell operating companies
before becoming president of Illinois Bell. He moved to AT&T
corporate headquarters in 1977.
