<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern-Pilots,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern, Pilots Union Break Off Contract Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secret contract talks between Eastern Airlines and
its pilots union to reach a labor agreement before a possible
Machinists' strike have broken off, according to company and union
officials.
   The talks, which were kept secret by ``a gentleman's agreement
of confidentiality,'' lasted ``a couple of months,'' said union
spokesman Ron Cole.
   They ended April 1, according to an April 8 letter from the
airline, that warned pilots a settlement with the company is the
``least preferred alternative'' of union leaders.
   Facing a possible Machinists' strike, Eastern has been seeking
to guarantee pilot stability and cooperation.
   ``It made sense to reach an agreement now ... than start all
over again with the pilots after the (Machinists) negotiations. The
time was right to reach an agreement because the company needed the
pilots,'' said the letter to pilots from Tom Matthews, Eastern's
senior vice president for human resources, and Don Breeding, vice
president for flight operations.
   The pilots' contract officially becomes open for amendment July
1, and the latest talks were not official negotiations, Cole said.
   Eastern has been negotiating a new contract with the Machinists,
the largest of the three unions at the financially troubled
carrier, since last fall.
   Eastern is a subsidiary of Houston-based Texas Air Corp., the
nation's largest airline holding company.
</TEXT>
