<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Chysler-Kenosha     04-12 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chysler-Kenosha,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study: Chrysler Plant Closing To Cost Taxpayers $209 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SOLOMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A union-commissioned study says Chrysler
Corp.'s planned shutdown of auto production here would cost more
than $209 million in the first two years for welfare and jobless
benefits and lost tax revenue.
   The two-year social cost analysis by the Midwest Center for
Labor Research in Chicago estimated the cost to local, state and
federal governments from the plant shutdown at $38,000 for each
unemployed Chrysler worker.
   Chrysler announced in January it plans to end auto production at
Kenosha by Sept. 30, laying off 5,500 workers. Chrysler took over
the plant last year as part of its purchase of American Motors Corp.
   ``Of about the two dozen studies that we've done, that's the
highest figure we've ever come up with,'' Greg LeRoy, MCLR research
director, told reporters at the United Auto Workers Local 72
headquarters Monday.
   LeRoy said the study, commissioned by Local 72, was based on a
previous MCLR study in 1985 but used more comprehensive welfare and
employment figures from the state, Kenosha and Racine counties and
the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics.
   It estimated that the plant's closing would result in $62.4
million in unemployment compensation, $54.5 million in lost federal
income tax revenue, $26 million in lost Social Security tax
revenue, $21.4 million in welfare expenditures and $17 million in
lost state sales and excise tax revenue.
   Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson has threatened to sue Chrysler,
claiming the automaker broke a promise to keep the plant open for
five years.
   Chrysler officials have said they may have been overly
optimistic when negotiating with the state for improvements and job
training funds, but have repeatedly denied making any such promise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
