<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 1033EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-NissanExports     04-12 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Nissan Exports,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nissan Will Curb Car Exports To the United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nissan Motor Co., Japan's No. 2 automaker, will
reduce car exports to the United States to ease pressure from
mounting inventories, Nissan officials said Tuesday.
   They wouldn't specify the scale of the planned reduction. But
Japanese press reports, which Nissan officials called speculative,
said the company will cut shipments of passenger cars by about 30
percent to 200,000 in the April-September period from 283,000 a
year earlier.
   Nissan dealers in the United States are flooded with unsold
cars, an auto-industry analyst in Tokyo said.
   According to U.S. industry estimates, Nissan had about 155 days'
worth of inventories in the U.S. at the beginning of March, well
above the 70-day average for Japanese carmakers as a whole.
   Nissan attributes its sales slump in the United States to
complete model changes planned later this year for some of its
popular cars, such as 200SX coupes and Maxima sedans. Consumers
tend to refrain from buying cars that are slated for restyling and
other major changes, Nissan officials explained.
   Industry watchers said Nissan's newly styled models in the
domestic market are proving popular among consumers. However,
because of the scale of the company, which sells about 2.7 million
units of motor vehicles worldwide annually, it takes about four
years to carry out a full, company-wide model changeover.
   Nissan began restraining U.S.-bound car shipments late last year
as a result of a sales slowdown following price hikes forced under
the yen's prolonged strength.
   Mainly because of Nissan's slower exports, Japan's car shipments
to the United States in the year ended March 31 fell short of the
2.3 million-unit limit for the first time since the restraints were
imposed by the Japanese government in 1980.
   According to unofficial industry figures, Japanese car exports
to the U.S. fell about 86,000 units short of the limit last year.
   Japan decided it would continue the ceiling at 2.3 million units
a year for the new year beginning April 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880412-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 1057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Switzerland-Banks     04-12 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Switzerland-Banks,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tighter Banking Scrutiny After Marcos, Duvalier Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swiss banks and big financial
institutions will come under closer supervision in accepting funds
from foreign leaders, the Swiss Banking Commission said Tuesday.
   The cases of deposed presidents Ferdinand Marcos of the
Philippines and Jean-Claude Duvalier of Haiti sparked the need for
stronger surveillance, the regulatory agency said in its annual
report.
   Philippines officials claim Marcos stashed up to about $5
billion in Switzerland during his 20-year rule. Duvalier is alleged
to have diverted several hundred million dollars into Swiss
accounts. Both were ousted from office in 1986.
   The commission's probe of the case failed to find any wrongdoing
by the banks involved, which were not named. But the agency said it
will now require top management of Swiss banks, rather than
lower-ranking employees, to judge whether to take up or continue
``such exposed business ties.''
   The panel also called for tougher Swiss laws against money
laundering, terming existing measures insufficient to combat the
practice. Lawmakers should consider criminal penalties for legal
entities caught laundering money, it said.
   On other topics, it said that in the wake of last October's
stock market crash, banks will have to report more openly on how
they cover losses in securities trading, and on notes issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
