<HEAD>Johnson & Johnson Ends Try For Playtex Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Johnson & Johnson has ended its attempt to
acquire the family products subsidiary of Playtex Holdings Inc.,
the companies said.
   The sale was scuttled because of ``difficulties in structuring
and completing the definitive agreements for the transaction,'' a
joint statement by both companies said Monday.
   Officials declined to elaborate further.
   ``The business had a highly successful year in 1987 and is off
to a strong start in 1988,'' Joel E. Smilow, chairman and chief
executive officer of Playtex, said in a statement.
   ``If you look in The Wall Street Journal, there are stories of
similar deals that fell through every day,'' said F. Robert
Kniffen, spokesman for Johnson & Johnson.
   Since news of the possible sale became public Feb. 16, there was
speculation that Johnson & Johnson would close or move the
subsidiary. Delaware officials had begun attempts to try to
persuade Johnson & Johnson to keep the jobs in the state. About 700
workers are employed at the complex.
   The family products subsidiary manufactures and markets tampons,
disposable baby bottles, rubber gloves and toothbrushes.
   Playtex's intimate apparel subsidiary is in Dover and the
facility also is the distribution point for products made by other
divisions.
   Playtex is continuing to seek a buyer for its Jhirmack hair
products subsidiary, Smilow said. Jhirmack products are distributed
through Dover.
