<HEAD>Troubled Bank's Chief Executive May Resign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gerald W. Fronterhouse, chairman of financially
troubled First RepublicBank Corp., is expected to submit his
resignation today, according to published reports.
   The resignation is believed to be part of a management shake-up
arranged by federal regulators overseeing recapitalization of the
big bank holding company, the Dallas Morning News reported.
   Spokesmen for the Dallas-based company declined to comment on
the report.
   A meeting of the full board of directors was scheduled for late
today. Board members also are expected to review the company's
first-quarter results, which banking analysts expect to include
another large loss.
   Fronterhouse, 51, succeeded James D. Berry as chairman of
predecessor RepublicBank Corp. in July 1986. He has spent his
entire 26-year banking career at First RepublicBank.
   Fronterhouse's resignation would add to a list of senior
management changes since the company's troubles began. The most
recent change came three weeks ago when Charles H. Pistor Jr.,
chairman of the lead bank First RepublicBank Dallas, announced he
would leave in mid-April and Fronterhouse would assume his duties.
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. loaned $1 billion last month
to First RepublicBank Corp., the nation's 13th-largest bank,
securing with it a deal with company officials that its most senior
executives would resign if asked to by the FDIC.
   The banking company, which claims $33.2 billion in assets,
reported a $656.8 million loss for 1987 after non-performing loans
in real estate, oil and other areas soared to nearly $4 billion.
</TEXT>
