<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 1351EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Trade     04-12 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Trade,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Notes Shift in Economy as Fiscal-Year Surplus Falls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KOZO MIZOGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A change in the structure of Japan's economy
contributed to the first decline in Japan's fiscal-year trade
surplus in eight years, government and private analysts said
Tuesday.
   The Finance Ministry announced Monday that Japan's overall trade
surplus dropped 15.3 percent in the fiscal year ended March 31 to
$76 billion from $89.7 billion in the previous fiscal year.
   It was the first decline since 1979, when Japan's oil import
bill soared because of the second oil crisis.
   Japan's trade surplus with the United States posted its first
annual decline since 1982, dropping 2.2 percent to $50.9 billion
from a record $52 billion the year before.
   ``A shift toward the direction of a decline in trade surplus is
taking place at a steady pace,'' said Nobuo Murakami, deputy
director of the Finance Ministry's Export Division.
   The yen's rapid appreciation against the dollar the past two
years and the government policy to promote domestic demand were
major factors in the decline in the surplus, Murakami said.
   The yen has roughly doubled in value against the dollar since
its most recent low in February 1985. In September 1985, monetary
authorities from seven major industrialized countries agreed to
drive down the dollar's value to help reduce the huge U.S. trade
deficit.
   A higher yen makes Japanese exports more expensive abroad and
less competitive, while imported products are cheaper in Japan.
   Japan sent 35.8 percent of its exports to the United States in
fiscal year 1987, down from 38 percent the previous year. Its
exports to the European Economic Community increased to 16.7
percent from 15.4 percent, and to Southeast Asian countries to 23.7
percent from 20.6 percent.
   ``It is clear that some major Japanese products, including
automobiles, are losing their competiveness on the U.S. market,
though personal computers and other office equipment remain in high
demand,'' said Taku Hiramatsu, assistant manager of the research
department of Bank of Tokyo.
   Hiramatsu said Japan's auto exports to the United States, which
accounted for about 30 percent of the nation's total exports to the
United States, ``will be getting further squeezed in the future''
because several Japanese automakers will be making car in the
United States in 1990s.
   Japanese automakers have fallen short of the government-set
export quota of 2.3 million passenger cars during the year, the
first such shortfall since Japan began limting its auto exports to
the U.S. market in 1981, local news reports said Tuesday.
   An official of the Japan Automobile Manufacturers Association
said the figures for Japan's car exports to the United States would
be announced late this month, and the volume would be ``far below''
the 2.3 million vehicles sent to America the previous year.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, blamed the
shortfall on the higher yen and the ``slower-than-expected increase
in the U.S. car market.''
   Japanese car makers have raised their export prices to the
United States by more than 20 percent on the average over the past
two years to make up for losses stemming from the dollar's
depreciation.
   ``More significant results in the reduction of (Japan's) trade
surplus with the United States will surely come in years to come,''
Murakami said. ``It's just two years since the yen's appreciation
began.''
</TEXT>
