<2ND_LINE>BC-India-Bhopal,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>District Judge Postpones Union Carbide Hearing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   District Court Judge M.W. Deo cancelled
Tuesday's scheduled hearing on the Bhopal gas disaster but set a
deadline of April 23 for outlining a hearing schedule in the case,
the United News of India reported.
   Deo adjourned the proceedings after lawyers for both Union
Carbide Corp. and the Indian government said they had not yet
received a copy of a higher court's ruling on Deo's earlier order
that Carbide pay interim reief to the victims of the accident.
   India is suing Union Carbide for $3 billion in damages for the
1984 gas leak from the pesticides plant operated by one of the
company's subsidiaries. More than 2,800 people were killed and
hundreds were injured in the accident.
   Last December, Deo ordered Union Carbide to pay interim relief
to the victims, and the company appealed the ruling to the High
Court in Jabalpur, about 150 miles east of Bhopal.
   The High Court on April 4 rejected Union Carbide's appeal and
ordered the multinational to pay $192 million in interim relief to
the victims.
   Union Carbide has not yet said whether it will appeal the
decision to the Indian Supreme Court.
