<DOCNO> AP880412-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 1409EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-Crash-Global Adv17   04-12 0815</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Crash-Global, Adv 17,0843</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday April 17 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Japan's Stock Market Glows As Others Glimmer</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Crash-Stocks</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese stock market's unrelenting climb to
new heights since Black Monday has made the land of the rising sun
and its booming economy the envy of every market struggling to
regain lost momentum.
   Unlike the crash, when markets from Brussels, Belgium to
Singapore plummeted in reaction to Wall Street's collapse, the
recovery of world markets since Oct. 19 has been relatively uneven.
   Markets have followed the pace of their own economies, and
investors who once roamed the globe in search of equities have
returned to the backyard markets they know best.
   ``I don't think I could describe any spillover effects,'' said
Robert Brusca, chief economist at Nikko Securities Co.
International Inc. ``It's more the case that stock markets seem to
be tracking economic growth internally.''
   So far this year, major stock markets outside the United States
are up about 13.5 percent, according to an index compiled by Morgan
Stanley & Co., while the U.S. market is up about 4.5 percent.
   European markets have turned in a mixed performance since the
crash. The Brussels exchange is up on takeover activity; West
Germany's market is sluggish; and a slow-growing French economy is
taking its toll on the Bourse.
   But if those markets show glimmers of life, the advance has been
blinding in Japan, home of the world's biggest equities market.
While the Dow Jones industrial average has sputtered to and fro
beneath pre-crash levels, Japan's key market barometer has reached
stunning all-time highs with ease.
   The key Nikkei 100-share index breezed its way into record
territory in early April.
   ``The story this year really is mostly a story about Japan,''
said Mark Sladkus, a vice president at Morgan Stanley. But, he
noted, the market's momentum isn't due to its magnetic attraction
for investors outside the island nation.
   ``It's totally due to domestic considerations,'' Sladkus said.
   Spurred by a roaring financial boom, Japan's stock market is
reaping the benefits of a surge in corporate profits, a sharp
increase in consumption and tax reforms that are likely to prompt
consumers to move their money out of savings accounts and into
equities.
   While the quick about-face isn't causing Japanese investors to
lose any sleep, some on the other side of the ocean watch with
furrowed brows.
   ``There's concern that with the market going up so strongly and
with the economy growing that maybe the Bank of Japan is not going
to be as accommodative,'' Brusca said, noting that some fear
Japan's central bank ``could take away one important underpinning
of the market _ the liquidity that helped spur the growth'' in the
first place.
   ``Nobody is quite comfortable that a country the size of
California and with half the population of the United States has
the biggest stock market, even though (the Japanese) seem to do
everything right,'' said Byron Wien, managing director and U.S.
investment strategist at Morgan Stanley.
   In London, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
remains about 25 percent below its level just prior to the crash.
Despite the fact that the market has been extremely volatile,
analysts aren't too concerned about the speed of its recovery.
   ``The equity market was overvalued before the crash,'' said
Randal Goldsmith, a market strategist with the London investment
firm James Capel & Co. ``There's no reason to go right back up to
that level yet.''
   The market has been supported by an increase in the number of
companies buying back their own shares, heightened takeover
activity, better-than-expected corporate profits and relief that
the economy wasn't hit harder by the crash.
   Thanks to the takeover battle for Societe Generale de Belgique,
the largest Belgian corporation, the Brussels Bourse has put in the
best performance among the European exchanges.
   In Hong Kong, where the stock exchange shut down for four days
following Black Monday, trading volume stalled and investor
confidence had to be rebuilt from the ground up. But the market is
enjoying some spillover enthusiasm from Japan, since ``the Asian
investment community is linked together,'' Brusca noted.
   West Germany, on the other hand, is a ``dog, if you will; it's a
real barker,'' Brusca said. ``They've been experiencing sluggish
growth, their monetary policy remains restrictive, and their
currency is appreciating, which makes it difficult for German firms
to sell their products overseas for a profit,'' he said.
   Trading volume throughout the world has been relatively light,
which analysts say is a sign of confusion among investors.
   To alleviate fears of the unknown, international investors went
home.
   ``People were operating in markets overseas that they didn't
understand that well, and so they brought their money home. These
markets may not be doing so well, but at least investors understand
them,'' Brusca said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday April 17</NOTE>
