<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Boeing-Defects 1stLd-Writethru f0032 04-12 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boeing-Defects, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0032,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Announces Investigation of Boeing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs, recasting lead and adding Boeing comment,
picking up 4th graf pvs, ``Airline, Boeing; Boeing newser scheduled
for 2:30 p.m. EDT, no lede planned; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration is
investigating safety complaints from airlines about Boeing 747 and
767 widebody jets and has issued a safety inspection directive for
one of the aerospace company's jetliner models.
   FAA officials revealed Monday that an ``airworthiness
directive'' on the 747-200 was issued Friday because of reports
that fuel leaking into cargo compartments.
   Boeing Commercial Airplanes officials refused Monday to respond
to the airline complaints or comment on the FAA action, but said
they would hold a news conference later.
   However, Phil A. Condit, executive vice president of Boeing
Commercial Airplanes, was quoted in today's editions of The Wall
Street Journal as saying letters from the airlines represent
``communications that go on between us and airlines all the time.
That's how we make our products better.''
   Airline, Boeing and FAA officials have noted that none of the
defects cited to date has been linked to a crash or other major
damage, but the directive warned, ``Fuel in this (cargo)
compartment could result in a fire and substantial damage.''
   The directive said the leaks were caused by loose or broken
bolts that attach fuel tanks to the wings and called for repairs
``before further flight.'' Boeing officials said the order applied
to 317 operating 747-200s.
   Nick Wantiez of the local FAA office said Monday the
investigation also would cover airline complaints ranging from
wrong parts to incorrectly installed firefighting systems.
   ``We are putting together a plan this week to deal with these
complaints and to determine what actions must be taken to assure
compliance with federal regulations,'' Wantiez said.
   He said the inspection order followed reports of incidents by
Japan Air Lines, Northwest Airlines, Lufthansa, Air India,
Aerolineas Argentinas and a leasing company, starting Nov. 21 with
a JAL report in Los Angeles of a fuel leak involving a bold that
had broken from corrosion.
   David Jimenez of Boeing confirmed Monday that letters citing
problems in 767s and 747s had been received from Japan Air Lines,
All Nippon Airways, British Airways and American Airlines.
   Problems cited by All Nippon included a wing flap disintegrating
in flight on the first day of service, smoke from a misassembled
power unit that caused an emergency landing, and problems in a fire
extinguisher system.
   Bob Baker, American's senior vice president for operations, said
his company's maintenance crews found three 767-200s with faulty
pipelines that carry firefighting chemicals to the forward and rear
cargo compartments.
   ``The pipes were misrouted,'' Baker said. ``If you light them
off for the forward belly system they go off in the rear.''
   Baker said that after being informed by American, Boeing found
one faulty system on its production line and All Nippon and JAL
found several in their planes.
</TEXT>
