<NOTE>$adv 17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday April 17 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>City Remains Cautious; Real Estate Soft; Job Outlook Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Crash-Stocks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York City, the epicenter of last October's
stock market quake, remains jumpy at any aftershocks and watches
warily for warning signs of future trouble.
   ``So far, so good,'' is the opinion of Samuel Ehrenhalt, the
regional commissioner of the federal Bureau of Labor Statistics.
``The economy has held up better than most expected, but we still
haven't got the situation fully in focus.''
   Among the fuzzy images, six months later:
   _The city, whose financial worries faded during the bull market,
has scaled back its plans for growth. The goal of a 30,000-member
police department is on hold, two firehouses are closed, and
museums and libraries found their budgets cut.
   _The real estate market, though still inflated by standards of
most American cities, has lost some steam, with office vacancy
rates up, several construction projects on hold and condos no
longer guaranteed to skyrocket in value.
   _Unemployment figures remain stable overall, but layoffs in the
financial sector may show up in the statistics later as severance
pay runs out for some and as businesses that depend on Wall Street
are forced to follow suit.
   The city adopted a cautious stance almost immediately after the
crash. Within 10 days, Mayor Edward I. Koch had ordered a 90-day
hiring freeze.
   ``We needed the three months to evaluate what the crash meant,''
said Anthony Shorris, deputy director of the city Office of
Management and Budget. The city recalculated its projections for
fiscal 1989 _ July 1 to June 30, 1989 _ and figured its tax
revenues would be about $270 million less than expected.
   ``A lot of people were doomsayers, taking terrible, grim
positions'' after the crash, Shorris said. ``In context, $270
million out of a tax base of $14 billion is hardly a major change.
But there was a reduction of growth.''
   The slowdown in the local economy will force the city to keep a
tight rein on spending. Plans to expand the Sanitation Department
were cut by 260 positions. The Department of Cultural Affairs saw
its fiscal 1989 budget cut by $5.6 million; libraries will get $7.7
million less than originally expected, which will probably result
in shorter hours and other cuts in services.
   Yet Shorris said the true effect of the crash shows up not so
much in the data about the city that pours into his office, but in
conversations and attitudes across the nation.
   ``More than the crash itself, it was reevaluation of nation's
economy that was the most important byproduct,'' Shorris said.
``That has a very important effect on us. New York City has been
more affected than almost any other city or state because of the
high concentration of security and finance activity.''
   One obvious casualty of the crash was a two-tower office complex
planned for the southwest corner of Central Park, with the
investment firm Salomon Brothers as the prime tenant. Though the
firm gave a variety of reasons for pulling out of the project, the
crash and subsequent cutbacks contributed.
   That also hurt the city, which was counting on selling the
property for $455 million, including $40 million in subway
improvements.
   ``There's really been a reassessment of new construction.
Several projects have been put on hold as a result of Black
Monday,'' said Lloyd Lynford, a real estate market analyst and
publisher of an industry newsletter.
   The office vacancy rate was at 9{ percent in October and may be
in the 14 percent range by the end of this year, Lynford said,
noting that one percentage point represents 3.5 million square feet
_ or more than half of one of the World Trade Center towers.
   In the residential market, he said, ``Unless you're talking
about the premier residential units in the city, there has been and
will be a comparatively more sluggish market than it has been the
last couple of years, with slower rates of appreciation.''
   Much of the shifting in the real estate market, both office and
residential, can be traced to job cuts in the financial services
industry, he said. From 1982 to 1987, 25 percent of the city's job
growth was in financial services.
   ``New York City is making a new transition into an economic
environment characterized by uncertainty, risk and vulnerability in
its dependence for growth on Wall Street and the financial
industry,'' said Ehrenhalt.
   ``We're not out of the woods yet.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday April 17</NOTE>
