<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     04-12 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0489</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was mixed in light trading
today as the market its digested recent gains and investors waited
for fresh economic data to be released later in the week.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 2.32 at 2,098.31
by mid-afternoon.
   Losers slightly outnumbered gainers by about 10 to 9 in the
overall tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 722
down, 681 up and 519 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 95.48 million shares at 2 p.m.
on Wall Street.
   ``The volume is very light, and what it shows is that there's no
enthusiasm,'' said Ronald Daino, a technical analyst at Smith
Barney, Harris, Upham & Co.
   Analysts were not surprised that the market was little changed,
noting that the impressive 102.13-point rise the Dow posted last
week had to be digested. While the market appeared to be staying
put throughout the session, most analysts agreed there are positive
underpinnings for equities.
   ``(The market) went up a long way, and we expect it to
retrench,'' said Hidegarde Zagorski, vice president of
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., but ``once the selling is over,
it will move into higher ground.''
   Meanwhile, many investors remain on the sidelines as they await
the release of new economic data. While they are certain to focus
on February's merchandise trade report due out on Thursday, the
release of retail sales figures and a meeting of the Group of Seven
major industrial countries, both scheduled for Wednesday, are
likely to attract attention.
   ``A lot of people are going to play it close to the vest until
they see some direction from the numbers coming out,'' said Peter
Vandenberg, a vice president at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Analysts also noted that investors are once again confronting
what has become a psychological barrier at the 2,100-level on the
Dow. Indeed, the key market barometer touched 2,101 shortly after
noon but then eased back.
   ``The Dow has bumped its head against that level so many times,
so there is some hesitation'' when it approaches the mark, Zagorski
said.
   Honda Motor was the shining star in an otherwise dull auto
sector, rising 3 to 146{. Aircraft issues were lower, with Boeing
falling | to 46}. The Federal Aviation Administration said it would
conduct an investigation into alleged defects in the some of the
company's wide-body jets.
   Electronic issues were mostly higher, with Honeywell up 1] to
70; Kyocera up 1} to 89{, and Matsushita up 2{ to 226.
   Among other actively traded Big Board issues, Zayre was up 1 to
24| and USX Corp. was up 1[ to 33[.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
unchanged at 152.47. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up 2.14 at 305.83.
</TEXT>
