<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Federated     04-12 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Federated,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canadian Buyer Nominates Federated Directors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp. has proposed a slate of five
executives headed by Chairman Robert Campeau to become directors of
Federated Department Stores Inc. once Campeau takes over Federated.
   Federated, under its merger agreement with the Canadian company,
agreed to obtain the resignation of all but three of its current 17
directors once Campeau's tender offer for all of Federated's stock
is completed.
   Campeau's offer to pay all Federated stockholders $73.50 a share
is to expire at 5 p.m. April 20, but may be extended to May 12.
   The director changes would give Campeau control of five of the
eight seats remaining on the revamped Federated board. Campeau said
its slate of directors would act to complete the merger with
Federated as soon as possible following completion of the tender
offer.
   Besides Campeau, 63, founder of the Toronto-based development
company, the other Campeau nominees are: James T. Roddy, 45,
Campeau Corp.'s president and chief operating officer; Ronald
Tysoe, 45, Campeau senior vice president for corporate development;
Robert H. Morosky, 46, president of Campeau's Allied Stores Corp.
who will become chairman and chief executive of Federated and
Allied; and Carolyn Buck Luce, 35, senior vice president of Campeau
Corp. and Allied Stores.
   A Federated representative said no decision on which of the
current directors will resign would be made until Campeau takes
control of the company.
   At least two of the three Federated directors who remain on the
board will be picked from Federated's non-management directors,
according to Campeau's tender offer document sent to shareholders.
   Campeau's offering to shareholders also disclosed that on April
1, when Campeau said Federated reached the merger agreement,
Federated representatives estimated the company had lost $20
million before taxes during February. Campeau said that was higher
than the $10 million to $15 million loss Federated projected to
Campeau on Feb. 28 when they were negotiating a merger before New
York's R.H. Macy & Co. made a bid for Federated.
   Federated also projected that income before taxes for March and
April would be between $35 million and $76 million, Campeau said.
For the fiscal year ended Jan 30., Federated had net income of
$312.9 million, or $3.32 a share.
</TEXT>
