<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 1536EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Europe-Takeover     04-12 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Europe-Takeover,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Societe Generale Shareholders To Vote On Takeover Thursday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shareholders of Societe Generale de
Belgique SA meet Thursday to seal the fate of the company that is
older than Belgium and controls a third of its economy.
   The meeting also will decide the fate of the 3-month-old hostile
bid of Italian industrialist-financier Carlo De Benedetti, which
has bogged down in a swamp of legal, political and managerial
conflicts.
   De Benedetti's offer rocked the company, long home to the
blue-blooded cream of Belgium's business leaders and one in which
Belgian royalty and the Roman Catholic Church are said to have
shares.
   De Benedetti, head of Italy's Olivetti SpA, claims he and his
allies own as much as 49 percent of shares in 166-year-old Societe
Generale.
   His bid has spawned a rival alliance led by Cie. Financiere de
Suez of France and Groupe AG, Belgium's biggest insurer, that
claims a 50.7 percent stake.
   After months of conflicting statements and claims, the
extraordinary shareholders meeting which De Benedetti called must
show who owns what exactly.
   Analysts say the meeting may turn into a peace conference or a
showdown. ``Anything is possible,'' said Maurice Lippens, head of
Groupe AG.
   Some 1,000 shareholders and 200 journalists are to attend the
meeting in a specially built tent at the company's headoffice.
   Lippens has said De Benedetti must agree to share in management
of Societe Generale, not run it.
   But De Benedetti has said he seeks a free hand in Societe
Generale which has stakes in some 1,300 companies around the globe
active in just about every field of industrial endeavor.
   He wants to turn the company into a pan-European holding before
1992 when the European Economic Community is to remove borders
within the EEC and, with it, a thicket of regulatory restrictions.
   His search for control is entirely in character.
   Early in his career, De Benedetti, 53, left the board of Fiat
SpA when it was too slow in adopting his ideas for change. He went
to Olivetti whose fortunes he turned around after taking control of
the Italian office automation giant.
   The battle for Societe Generale has drawn companies from eight
nations into the fray in a hodge-podge of coalitions.
   France's Suez has a stake of 30 percent of the shares.
   Its main partner is Belgium's Groupe AG which only has a share
of 3.78 percent. In all, the AG-Suez camp totals a dozen or so
Belgian, French, Luxembourg and Swiss firms.
   De Benedetti's allies include Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc of the
United States and other U.S, Swiss and Australian finance companies.
   He has created a holding company for some of the shares in his
stable to attract major European companies. The Swiss food giant
Nestle SA has agreed to buy into it and Philips, the Dutch
communications and electronics company, may follow suit.
   The confrontation over Societe Generale is more than just
counting heads.
   For one thing, the target was long considered untouchable.
Societe Generale was founded 1822 by King William I of the
Netherlands, eight years before Belgium became independent of Dutch
rule and for years was Belgium's central bank.
   Today, its interests extend to mining, energy, financial
services, chemicals and engineering and its estimated worth is $3
billion.
   De Benedetti's bid led Societe Generale to isse 12 million new
shares. This has sparked several court cases which will likely take
years to produce a final settlement and adding confusion to a
takeover bid already riddled with complex alliances.
   Andre Leysen, head of Belgium's Gevaert Group, a one-time rival
but now an ally of De Benedetti, has called the saga ```Dallas,'
but without women,'' referring to the popular American television
series.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
