<HEAD>Soybean Futures Close Lower; Grains Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures closed lower Tuesday on the
Chicago Board of Trade as profit-taking erased some of last week's
dramatic gains. Corn futures also retreated while wheat advanced.
   Soybeans started the session on a weak note and slipped even
lower during the day but firmed near the end of trading to finish
down only a few cents.
   ``They came up fairly good on commercial buying,'' said Joel
Karlin, a research analyst for Research Department Inc. in Chicago.
   Corn futures retreated in sympathy with soybeans. Dim prospects
for corn exports and indications that the Agriculture Department
may move to make more surplus corn available on the open market
pressured corn futures, Karlin said.
   Wheat was supported by reports that China had bid for 500,000
metric tons of U.S. wheat offered under the USDA's subsidized
export sales program, and by indications that India is seeking to
buy U.S. wheat, he said.
   At the close, wheat was unchanged to 2} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.19 a bushel; corn was { cent to
1{ cents lower with May at $2.06\ a bushel; oats were } cent to 1\
cents lower with May at $1.66{ a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 3{
cents lower with May at $6.78{ a bushel.
