<HEAD>London Shares Close Slightly Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with trading activity, closing
index; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices ended slightly lower in thin,
featureless trading Tuesday, as investors awaited news from a
meeting of monetary officials of the Group of Seven major
industrialized nations.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 5.2
points, or 0.3 percent, at 1,805.3 at the close.
   Volume was scant at 364.7 million shares, down from 405.4
million on Monday.
   Shares traded in positive territory for much of the day but fell
off in the afternoon on lack of buying interest.
   Prices also were weakened by market rumors, later denied, that
Tesco PLC, a major British supermarket chain, would launch a new
share issue Wednesday when it reports its 1987 earnings. Recently
announced share issues have depressed share values.
   Share prices got little help from the British pound's continued
retreat against both the U.S. dollar and the West German mark,
which boosted shares Monday.
   One dealer said, ``People are awaiting more news on the G-7
meeting,'' to take place Wednesday in conjunction with a meeting of
the International Monetary Fund in Washington.
   There was little corporate news to move the market. Among the
100-share index stocks, 58 were lower, 14 were unchanged and 28
showed gains.
</TEXT>
