<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ResortsInternational     04-12 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Resorts International,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trump Rejects Griffin's Planned $105 Million Tender Offer for
Resorts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer-businessman Merv Griffin stepped
up the pressure Tuesday in his attempt to gain control of Resorts
International Inc., announcing he will make a $105 million tender
offer for a majority of the company's stock.
   New York investor Donald Trump, who controls 88 percent of the
hotel-casino operator's voting power, rejected the offer out of
hand, calling it ``a feeble and futile attempt to recast his prior
offers to further confuse the marketplace.''
   The $36-per-share offer to stockholders, to be initiated within
the next five days, follows Griffin's March 30 offer to management
to acquire all of Resorts' Class A common shares. The earlier offer
also is for $36 a share.
   ``Our new tender offer would effectively give Resorts' Class A
shareholders the opportunity to vote on Griffin's March 30 bid
now,'' said Michael Nigris, president of the Griffin Co.
   The offer would carry the condition that at least 2.9 million
shares be offered, a majority of the 5.7 million shares of Class A.
   Other conditions are that Resorts' board approve the merger and
that it agree to sell Griffin 1.2 million newly issued shares of
Class B stock for $36 a share. The Class B stock carries 100 votes
per share while the Class A carries one vote per share.
   The last condition, also part of Griffin's original offer, would
require the company to issue additional Class B stock and would
give him more voting strength than Trump. Trump owns 95 percent of
the 572,000 Class B shares that presently exist.
   In his response, Trump again made clear he has no intention of
sharing control of the company with Griffin, the former talk show
host who has built a private entertainment and real estate empire.
   ``Mr. Trump explained that Mr. Griffin's latest offer contained
nothing new and is still contingent upn Mr. Trump's aproval, an
approval which will never be granted,'' his news release said.
   A special committee of Resorts' management met with a Griffin
representative Friday to discuss his efforts to buy the company,
but resolved nothing, said Harvey Freeman, executive vice president
of the Trump organization and a director of Resorts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
