<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0231</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market advanced to a post-crash high
today in a late wave of buying spurred by computerized trading, a
firmer dollar and rebounding bond prices.
   The Dow Jones industrial average surged to close firmly above
the 2,100 mark for the first time since the market collapsed almost
six months ago.
   Analysts noted the Dow average had flirted with the
psychological barrier on several recent occasions, but investors
shed their inhibitions when the key market barometer held above
that level in mid-afternoon.
   Stock prices were mixed earlier in the session and the market
appeared to lack direction despite its sound underpinnings. Many
investors sat on the sidelines awaiting fresh economic data due out
later this week.
   Those who were waiting for new statistics from the Commerce
Department, scheduled to release February's merchandise trade data
on Thursday, missed the market's latest uptick, analysts said.
   ``A lot of people are going to play it close to the vest until
they see some direction from the numbers coming out,'' said Peter
Vandenberg, a vice president at Smith Barney, Harris, Upham & Co.
   Analysts also noted, however, that volume remained extremely
light, initially indicating a lack of investor enthusiasm but then
serving to accentuate the move upward once buyers did step in.
