<HEAD>International Paper Posts Big Earnings Jump in 1st Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Paper Co. said Tuesday its
first-quarter profit jumped 76.7 percent as revenue rose 27.8
percent, reflecting strong demand for all of its major products.
   The company said it earned $159 million, or $1.38 a share, in
the first three months of 1988 compared with $90 million, or 82
cents a share, a year earlier.
   Revenue for the first quarter rose to $2.3 billion from $1.8
billion in 1987.
   John A. Georges, chairman and chief executive, said prices for
most of the company's products are ``holding firm or increasing.''
   ``Demand across our major products lines _ white papers, coated
papers, containerboard, bleached board, pulp and lumber _ remains
strong,'' he said.
   He said the sales increase also reflected the benefits of recent
acquisitions, and that earnings should continue to improve from
last year if the economy remains strong.
