<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Batus-Farmers Bjt   04-12 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Batus-Farmers, Bjt,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Batus Says It Will Raise Stock Offer Price</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Batus Inc. told the
nation's third largest home and auto insurer Tuesday his company is
ready to open friendly merger talks and boost its $4.35 billion
takeover offer.
   Patrick Sheehy made the proposal in a letter sent to
representatives of the Farmers Group Inc., which is based in Los
Angeles. On Monday, Farmers Group had indicated that it is willing
to open talks with Batus under certain conditions.
   In over-the-counter trading, Farmers Group edged up 12{ cents a
share to close at $65 a share.
   Sheehy said the Louisville-based Batus, a subsidiary of the
British retailing, tobacco and financial services concern BAT
Industries PLC, was prepared to pay more than its current bid of
$63 per share ``in a friendly negotiated transaction.''
   Farmers Group had about 69.7 million shares of common stock
outstanding as of April 1. Batus already owns 696,000 shares of
Farmers stock, putting the value of its offer for the stock it does
not own at $4.35 billion.
   Sheehy also said Batus would like to receive the same
confidential information that Farmers had made available to other
parties.
   Sheehy asked, however, that the confidentiality agreement be
modified to ensure ``that there would be no unreasonable
restrictions on the freedom of Batus to pursue its offer if
negotiations failed, and that a fully level playing field would be
established between Batus and any other potential acquirer.''
   Tom Welch, director of corporate investments for Farmers, said
``the next step will be for our attorneys to look over their
request for a modification of the agreement. Then, we will respond
to them but I don't know when that will be.''
   Farmers has scheduled its annual meeting for May 20.
   The company has been resisting overtures from Batus' overtures
but altered its position Monday in a letter from Leo E. Denlea Jr.,
chairman and chief executive officer.
   Denlea said the board of directors would consider a bid from
Batus only if ``you are prepared to state unequivocally that Batus
is, in fact, prepared to offer a higher price and, if so, what that
price is. I am requesting hereby that you advise us without delay
of any higher offer you are prepared to make.''
   Denlea's letter also offered to share confidential information
disclosed to other potential suitors if Batus agreed to
confidentiality guidelines.
   ``You should be aware that at this point, Farmers' board of
directors has made no decision to pursue a sale of the company,''
Denlea wrote. ``That possibility is, as you may expect, under
continuous review. Depending on your response to the request made
herein, and other circumstances, the board of directors may or may
not revise its decision.''
   Batus, with businesses in retail sales, tobacco and paper goods,
made an unsolicited $63-a-share offer for Farmers on March 3. Last
week, Sheehy said the company would consider increasing its offer
if Farmers management would agree to negotiate.
   BAT has been seeking a foothold in the U.S. financial services
market for some time.
</TEXT>
