<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Hilton,0148</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Earnings Up 15 Percent in First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hilton Hotels Corp. reported
Tuesday that first-quarter earnings rose 15 percent, paced by
strong performances in both hotel and gambling operations.
   Net profit for the quarter was $27.6 million, or $1.15 per
share, up from $24.0 million, or 96 cents a share in the first
quarter of 1987, the company reported. Revenues for the quarter
ended March 31 were $214.2 million, up from $201.2 million for the
same period in 1987.
   Per-share earnings rose more than net earnings because the
company bought back 1.1 million shares.
   Chairman and President Barron Hilton said hotel revenues were up
12 percent, attributing the gain to completion of large renovation
projects. Gambling revenues also rose 12 percent because of
improved performances at the Las Vegas Hilton and Flamingo Hilton,
he said.
 
</TEXT>
