<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Budget 1stLd-Writethru f0238 04-12 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0238,0741</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Social Security Surpluses Said Hiding True Extent of Fiscal 1989
Deficit</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New in first 6 new grafs with Senate vote on amendment; picks
up 4th graf pvs bgng: The Senate ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fiscal 1989 budget hides the true size of
the federal deficit because it factors in huge surpluses from the
Social Security system and other programs, senators said Tuesday
while considering the $1.1 trillion spending plan.
   By an 85-8 vote, the Senate gave preliminary approval to an
amendment to the budget urging the lawmakers to discount the
surpluses amassed by two funds set aside for highway and aviation
projects when calculating the federal deficit.
   The two funds have a combined projected surplus of $2 billion
for next year.
   The Senate budget blueprint officially predicts the deficit
problem is easing.
   But under an amendment offered by Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla.,
chairman of the budget committee, the mammoth surplus the Social
Security program accumulates each year would no longer be counted
when figuring the federal deficit. That amendment could be voted on
as early as Wednesday.
   ``The deficit is heading up, not down,'' said Chiles.
   The Senate budget, which Chiles helped write, predicts the red
ink will shrink to $136 billion in the fiscal year beginning Oct.
1, a drop of more than $10 billion from the amount anticipated in
the current fiscal year.
   However, that counts a $46 billion surplus in Social Security,
which is expected to grow even larger through the beginning of the
next century. The funds then would be expended when the Baby Boom
generation reaches retirement age.
   Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., said that even if the Congress and
president meet their promise under the Gramm-Rudman law for a
balanced budget by fiscal 1993, the deficit that year actually
would be more than $100 billion if the Social Security surplus
isn't counted.
   Sen. Dan Evans, R-Wash., said he thought the amendment was an
inadequate gesture and that major revisions of the federal
accounting system were needed, not just non-binding legislative
language.
   There was less debate about the substance of the budget, which
would carry out the mandate of last fall's deficit-reduction
agreement between President Reagan and congressional leaders.
   The spending plan, like the agreement, calls for $294 billion in
military spending, $16.1 billion for foreign assistance and $169.2
billion for domestic agencies, outside of entitlements and other
programs set by automatic formulas.
   The Senate plan features a 27 percent increase in spending on
the space program and big boosts in AIDS research, both requested
by Reagan. Education would receive $1.2 billion, a 7.4 percent
boost.
   Like the president's plan, the budget doesn't call for new taxes
beyond the $14 billion for fiscal 1988 which was enacted last
December.
   The Senate plan also calls for:
   _A 4.3 percent pay increase for the military and 2 percent for
civilian federal workers. Reagan had requested the different pay
boosts, but the House voted for 3 percent across the board.
   _$500 million for more farm commodities for the poor, to replace
exhausted surplus stocks.
   _Expansion of Medicaid health program and enactment of Medicare
catastrophic illness insurance, assuming fees raised to pay for
them.
   _An 11 percent increase for National Science Foundation for its
research programs and a 25 percent increase in Energy Department
nuclear physics program, toward development of the superconducting
super collider project.
   _A 3 percent cut in rural housing assistance, along with
reductions in elderly housing and community and regional
development.
   _Aviation safety increase of 19 percent from $5.5 billion this
year, to hire 900 more air traffic controllers and modernize the
system.
   The House budget, approved last month, also follows the overall
budget guidelines of last fall but it differs in detail from the
Senate plan. For example, the House voted to spend more on aid to
local communities and less on space than the Senate plan.
   The two chambers must agree on a single spending plan, after
which it serves as a guide for regular fiscal legislation. The
budget is a congressional resolution that does not require the
president's signature.
   The official deadline for completing the budget is Friday.
Although Congress is unlikely to meet that target, this year's
budget action is coming at the earliest dates in years.
</TEXT>
