<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Pepperell     04-12 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Pepperell,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pepperell Overall Earnings Down, Continuing Operations Income Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Point-Pepperell Inc. reported
Tuesday its net income declined 2.1 percent in its second quarter,
although income from continuing operations rose 22.4 percent.
   The West Point-based company, which is involved in a
billion-dollar bidding war for rival textile giant J.P. Stevens &
Co., reported net income of $15.3 million, or 51 cents per share,
in the quarter ended March 26. That compared with a profit of $15.6
million, or 53 cents per share, in the same quarter last year.
   Sales for the quarter totaled $459.9 million, up 12 percent from
$410.4 million in the year-earlier quarter.
   Income from continuing operations rose to $18.6 million from
$15.2 million a year earlier.
   Joseph L. Lanier Jr, chairman and chief executive officer,
stated the rise in operating earnings stemmed from solid sales
increases in knit apparel fabrics and in the company's bed and bath
lines and from lower tax rates in 1988.
   Lanier said the company had an after-tax charge of $3.3 million
against a gain on the sale of discontinued carpet operations. West
Point sold substantially all of its assets of its carpet and rug
division last November to Shaw Industries Inc.
   For the first six months of its fiscal year, Pepperell reported
net income of $40.9 million, up 11.8 percent from the previous
period's $36.6 million. Per-share earnings rose to $1.34 from $1.25
in the previous quarter.
   Sales for the first half were $940.9 million, up 12.9 percent
from $833.1 million a year earlier.
   Pepperell is dueling with Odyssey Partners for control of J.P.
Stevens. New York-based Stevens has entered a merger agreement with
Odyssey, an investment group, but Pepperell has continued bidding
for the company. Odyssey on Monday offered $1.22 billion for
Stevens, topping Pepperell's $1.19 billion bid made earlier in the
day.
   Lanier has said Pepperell may consider topping Odyssey's latest
price.
</TEXT>
