<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Greenspan-Banks     04-12 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greenspan-Banks,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greenspan: Banking Reserves Must Be Increased To Handle Global
Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hazards of deregulated banking on a
global scale demand that banks increase their reserves, Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said Tuesday.
   Greenspan said the need for bigger bank reserves was underscored
last year when major banks took big losses because of reserves set
aside to cover bad loans to Latin America. For some banks, those
moves erased most of a decade's worth of growth in their capital
reserves.
   Such losses might be digested by healthy banks in a stable
domestic economy, Greenspan said. But the volatile nature of
international lending and increasing bank involvement in real
estate, insurance and securities brokering demanded a bigger safety
net, he told the Conference of State Bank Supervisors.
   Last December, federal banking officials and supervisory
officials from the 10 largest industrialized nations jointly
proposed establishing uniform international capital requirements.
   The plan would set an internationally accepted minimum equity
capital requirement and a menu of acceptable non-traditional assets
that could supplement a bank's equity base.
   Greenspan said the plan should be viewed as a crude first step
in focusing attention on the need for additional reserves.
   ``Some revisions may be required over time, but it provides an
important base to allow bank organizations to adapt in years
ahead,'' Greenspan said.
</TEXT>
